{"title_page": "Teiu\u0219", "text_new": "{{about||the village in [[Bac\u0103u County]]|Parava, Bac\u0103u|the village in [[Olt County]]|Scornice\u0219ti}}\n{{Distinguish|Teiu\u0219u (disambiguation){{!}}Teiu\u0219u}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Alba\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map = Teius jud Alba.png\n|map_caption = Location in Alba County\n|official_name=Teiu\u0219\n|image_shield=ROU AB Teius CoA.jpg\n|leader_name=Mirel H\u0103l\u0103lai<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=PSD\n|area_total_km2=44.56\n|coordinates   = {{coord|46|12|0|N|23|40|48|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website=\n}}\n'''Teiu\u0219''' ({{IPA-ro|te\u02c8ju\u0283}}, {{lang-de|Dreikirchen, Dornstadt}}; {{lang-hu|T\u00f6vis}}) is a town in [[Alba County]], [[Romania]], near the junction between the [[Geoagiu River (Alba)|Geoagiu River]] and the [[Mure\u0219 River]], with a population of 7,284 inhabitants. The town, declared as such in 1994, is a junction point on the [[Cluj-Napoca]]&ndash;[[Sighi\u0219oara]] railway. It has several old churches, the most notable being the 17th century [[Uniate]] church and the [[Roman Catholic]] church, built for [[John Hunyadi]] in 1449 and rebuilt (1701\u20131704) in a simple [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] style.\n\nThe town administers four villages: Beldiu (''Marosb\u00e9ld''), C\u0103pud (''Magyarkapud''), Co\u0219lariu Nou (''\u00dajkosl\u00e1rd'') and Pe\u021belca (''Pacalka'').\n\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1850 |2935\n|1880 |3311\n|1910 |5088\n|1930 |6636\n|1941 |7023\n|1956 |6614\n|1966 |7162\n|1977 |7718\n|1992 |7199\n|2002 |7284\n|2011 |6695\n}}\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Gara Teius.jpg|Teiu\u0219 railway station\nFile:HouseInTeius.JPG|House in Teiu\u0219 near railway station\nFile:Biserica reformata Teius.jpg|Reformed church in Teiu\u0219\nFile:TeiusChurch.JPG|Interior of the Greek-Catholic church in Teiu\u0219\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Teiu\u0219}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{LocalitiesAlba}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teius}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Alba County]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n\n{{Alba-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about||the village in [[Bac\u0103u County]]|Parava, Bac\u0103u|the village in [[Olt County]]|Scornice\u0219ti}}\n{{Distinguish|Teiu\u0219u (disambiguation){{!}}Teiu\u0219u}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Alba\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map = Teius jud Alba.png\n|map_caption = Location in Alba County\n|official_name=Teiu\u0219\n|image_shield=ROU AB Teius CoA.jpg\n|leader_name=Mirel H\u0103l\u0103lai\n|leader_party=[[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PSD]]\n|area_total_km2=44.56\n|coordinates   = {{coord|46|12|0|N|23|40|48|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website=\n}}\n'''Teiu\u0219''' ({{IPA-ro|te\u02c8ju\u0283}}, {{lang-de|Dreikirchen, Dornstadt}}; {{lang-hu|T\u00f6vis}}) is a town in [[Alba County]], [[Romania]], near the junction between the [[Geoagiu River (Alba)|Geoagiu River]] and the [[Mure\u0219 River]], with a population of 7,284 inhabitants. The town, declared as such in 1994, is a junction point on the [[Cluj-Napoca]]&ndash;[[Sighi\u0219oara]] railway. It has several old churches, the most notable being the 17th century [[Uniate]] church and the [[Roman Catholic]] church, built for [[John Hunyadi]] in 1449 and rebuilt (1701\u20131704) in a simple [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] style.\n\nThe town administers four villages: Beldiu (''Marosb\u00e9ld''), C\u0103pud (''Magyarkapud''), Co\u0219lariu Nou (''\u00dajkosl\u00e1rd'') and Pe\u021belca (''Pacalka'').\n\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1850 |2935\n|1880 |3311\n|1910 |5088\n|1930 |6636\n|1941 |7023\n|1956 |6614\n|1966 |7162\n|1977 |7718\n|1992 |7199\n|2002 |7284\n|2011 |6695\n}}\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Gara Teius.jpg|Teiu\u0219 railway station\nFile:HouseInTeius.JPG|House in Teiu\u0219 near railway station\nFile:Biserica reformata Teius.jpg|Reformed church in Teiu\u0219\nFile:TeiusChurch.JPG|Interior of the Greek-Catholic church in Teiu\u0219\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Teiu\u0219}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{LocalitiesAlba}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teius}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Alba County]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n\n{{Alba-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teiu%C8%99"}
{"title_page": "Arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te", "text_new": "{{about||the Belgian resistance group|Arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te (Belgium)|the Algerian war dissident organisation|Organisation arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te}}\n{{Expand French|Arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te (France)|date=March 2019|topic=mil}}\n{{refimprove|date= July 2008}}\n\n{{Infobox Organization\n| name             = Arm\u00e9e Secr\u00e8te\n| native_name_lang = French\n| image            = Insigne Arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te Haute savoie.jpg\n| image_size       = 150\n| legend           = Insignia of the Arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te in Haute-Savoie\n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_caption      = The geographic organization of the Resistance\n| motto            = \n| region           = [[France]]\n| formation        = {{start date|1942|11|11|df=y}}\n| dissolution      = {{date|1|f\u00e9vrier|1944}}\n| extinction       = {{end date and age|1944|02|01}}\n| predecessor      = \n| type             = [[List of networks and movements of the French Resistance|Resistance network]]\n| headquarters     = \n| latitude         = \n| longitude        = \n| coords           = \n| language         = French\n| budget           = \n| membership       = \n| leader_title     = Chef\n| leader_name      = [[Charles Delestraint]]\n| leader_title2    = Chef d'\u00e9tat-major\n| leader_name2     = {{Interlanguage link multi|Fran\u00e7ois Morin-Forestier|fr}}, later [[Pierre Dejussieu-Pontcarral]]\n| leader_name3     = \n| leader_title3    = \n| key_people       = [[Henri Frenay]], [[Jean Moulin]]\n| affiliations     = [[Mouvements unis de la R\u00e9sistance]] (MUR)\n| site web         =\n}}\n\n[[File:R\u00e9gions r\u00e9sistance.jpg|thumb|300px|Regional organization of the [[French Resistance]]]]\n[[File:20_rue_Vauban_\u00e0_Lyon_-_plaque_comm\u00e9morative_mouvement_Combat_(gros_plan).jpg|thumb|350px|Commemorative plaque in Lyon]]\nIn [[World War II]] France this military organization grouped the paramilitary formations of the three most important [[Gaullist]] resistance movements in the southern zone: Combat, Lib\u00e9ration-Sud and the [[Franc-Tireur]]s.\n\nIn mid-1942, in the R1 Region, these three major movements wanted to coordinate the military units at their disposal to make them more effective. [[Henri Frenay]], leader of Combat, claimed command of the new structure, but faced opposition from [[Emmanuel d'Astier de La Vigerie]], leader of Liberation-Sud and [[:fr:Jean-Pierre L\u00e9vy (r\u00e9sistant)|Jean-Pierre Levy]], head of the Franc-Tireurs. [[Jean Moulin]] insisted that the post should go to someone who with no affiliation to one of these groups, so Frenay proposed [[Charles Delestraint]], a general recalled from his retirement during the [[Battle of France]], who admired De Gaulle and detested Vichy. He was the only general officer who had been promoted despite that defeat; the proposal was unanimously accepted.\n\nJean Moulin and General Delestraint first met on August 28, 1942 in Lyon. At the end of the interview, Jean Moulin ordered the three regional chiefs of the paramilitary formations of the great movements made available to Delestraint, for him to choose the best suited to the regional direction of the Secret Army. To this position, eminently clandestine and dangerous, the general named Captain {{ILL|Claudius Billon|fr}}. As early as September, Billon appointed each of the AS departmental heads for R1, with the exception of the AS chief for [[Ain]], named by Delestraint himself.\n\nIn October, Delestraint was appointed (officially) by [[General de Gaulle]]. [[Jean de Lattre de Tassigny|General de Lattre]] had also been approached for this post, but had refused. Delestraint took command on November 11, 1942. His secretary was {{ILL|Francois-Yves Guillin|fr}}; the head of the 2nd AS office was {{ILL|Joseph Gastaldo|fr}}. [[Andr\u00e9 Lassagne]] was the deputy of Gastaldo, before becoming Delestraint, and the information was entrusted to Albert Lacaze (4th office). Its chief of staff was {{ILL|Fran\u00e7ois Morin-Forestier|fr}}, from Combat, staff in which is also integrated [[Raymond Aubrac]].{{what|date=May 2019}}\n \nOn November 27, 1942 in [[Collonges-au-Mont-d'Or]], the constituent meeting of the Southern Zone Coordination Committee was held and the head of the Secret Army was presented by Jean Moulin. This committee intended to unite the three major resistance movements.\n\nIn December, Delestraint, inexperienced in the constraints of illegal life, crossed the demarcation line to make contact with the major movements in the northern zone: Liberation, the Civil and Military Organization (CMO) National, Lib\u00e9ration-Nord. Then, back in the free zone, he took part in the creation of the United Movements of the Resistance (MUR) on January 26, 1943 in Miribel, in Ain.\n\nAt the beginning of February 1943, {{ILL|Hugo Geissler|fr}}, Kommandeur of the [[Sicherheitspolizei|Sipo]]-[[Sicherheitsdienst|SD]] in Vichy, decapitated the Secret Army of the R1 region. On February 1 in Lyon's Place du Pont, he arrested Billon, head of the AS in R1 (eleven departments), along with his deputy Pierre Lavergne. On February 3, at 31, rue Basse-des-Rives in Saint-\u00c9tienne, during a secret meeting of the headquarters of the departmental AS, he also arrested the head of AS Loire, Lieutenant Vidiani, and his companions. On February 10, in [[Le Puy-en-Velay]], they continued to dismantle the AS in R1 with the arrest of the chief of AS in Haute-Loire Alfred Salvatelli and his companions at his home. After the February 10 arrest, the Haute-Loire resistance joined region R6 (Auvergne). On 27 May 1943, these three arrests, orchestrated by Geissler, featured prominently at the beginning of the [[Ernst Kaltenbrunner]]'s report addressed to [[Joachim von Ribbentrop]], Minister of Foreign Affairs for the Reich.\n\nDelestraint then fought against the advice of Frenay (who had been provisionally delegated general of the Secret Army) to put the Army under the tutelage of the MUR. Frenay, on the one hand the No. 2 of the Secret Army and on the other a member of the Coordination Committee of the same army, then wished the recall of Delestraint and his own appointment as head of the Secret Army, which were rejected by the other members of the Coordinating Committee, Moulin, d'Astier and Levy.\n\nIn London in February 1943 to meet Allied authorities, Delestraint was asked to make his troop the \"nucleus of the future French army\", estimated at 150,000 men. Unfortunately, Francois Morin-Forestier was arrested in March with Raymond Aubrac, [[Maurice Kriegel-Vallimont]] and {{ILL|Serge Ravanel|fr}} of the MUR, and only  released in May, thanks to the action of his former co-detainee Raymond Aubrac. His release did not allow his return to the staff: too exposed, he was ex-filtered to London. In April, Delestraint returned to Paris, arriving April 11. By the June 4 report, Moulin deplores the risks that Delestraint was taking, working alone when he would do better if assisted.\n\nOn June 9, 1943, Delestraint, Gastaldo and their deputy Jean-Louis Th\u00e9obald were arrested in Paris. On June 21, a staff meeting was held to find a successor to Delestraint in [[Caluire-et-Cuire]]. L\u00e9onard \u00c9mile Schwarzfeld, candidate to replace Delestraint, Aubrac, candidate for the leadership in the northern zone, and Lassagne for the southern zone, as well as other leaders of the Resistance such as Moulin, [[Henri Aubry]], [[Ren\u00e9 Hardy]], {{ILL|Albert Lacaze|fr}} and {{ILL|Bruno Larat|fr}} were taken prisoner. In July 1943, Colonel [[Pierre Dejussieu-Pontcarral]] was appointed chief of staff of a Secret Army now without an official leader. The Chief of Staff of the Southern Zone was General Jouffrault, until he was also arrested in August 1943.\n\nOn February 1, 1944, the Gaullist Secret Army merged with the [[French Forces of the Interior]] (FFI), with the Army Resistance Organization (ORA) and the French Francs-tireurs et partisans (FTPF, communists, not to be confused with the Franc-Tireur movement).\n\nThis structure was mainly found in the southern half of France: [[Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]] (R1) and [[Auvergne]] (R6), but also [[Limousin]] (R5), South-East and the Southwest (R4). It corresponded to the organizational structure used by Combat.\n\nUniting the regions of the free zone took only a few weeks, the various chiefs being chosen from among the regional chiefs in office. In Region A, the workforce was almost entirely composed of members of the CMO.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Regions==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable centre\" style=\"text-align:center; width=80%;\"\n|+ Layout of Resistance forces\n!width=\"25%\" | Region || Departement || Leader || Others\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | '''B''' || '''Region''' || General [[Louis-Eug\u00e8ne Faucher]] ||\n|-\n| [[Deux-S\u00e8vres]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Edmond Proust|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | '''M''' || '''Region''' || General {{Interlanguage link multi|Louis-Alexandre Audibert|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | '''M2''' || '''Region''' || General {{Interlanguage link multi|Marcel Allard|fr}} ||\n|-\n| [[Finist\u00e8re]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Mathieu Donnart|fr}}<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Roger Bourri\u00e8res|fr}} ||\n|-\n| [[Morbihan]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Maurice Guillaudot|fr}}<br/>[[Paul Chenailler]] ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" | '''R1 - Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes''' || '''Region''' || Captain {{Interlanguage link multi|Claudius Billon|fr}}<br/><br/>Capt. {{Interlanguage link multi|Albert Chambonnet|fr}}<br/>|| {{Interlanguage link multi|Pierre Lavergne|fr}} (Maquis)<br/><br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Andr\u00e9 Vansteenberghe|fr}} (intelligence)\n|-\n| [[Ain (d\u00e9partement)|Ain]] || Andr\u00e9 ''Bob'' Fornier<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maquisdelain.org/index.php?r=personnage&id=60 |language=French |title=Maquis de l'Ain et du Haut-Jura |trans-title=Maquis of the Ain and Haut-Jura |access-date=2015-07-07}}</ref><br/>Capt. [[Henri Romans-Petit]]<ref name=\"Petit\">{{cite web |url=http://www.memoire-deportation-ain.fr/la-r\u00e9sistance-arm\u00e9e.aspx |language=French |title=La R\u00e9sistance arm\u00e9e |trans-title=Armed Resistance |publisher=M\u00e9moire de la D\u00e9portation dans l'Ain (1939-1945) |access-date=2014-02-22}}.</ref> || Jean Perret<br/>Marcel Gagneux<ref name=\"Lyon\">{{cite web|language=French |url=http://www2.ac-lyon.fr/etab/colleges/col-01/vailland/IMG/pdf/armee_secrete.pdf |type=pdf |title=Structuration de l'Arm\u00e9e Secr\u00e8te et unification au sein des Mouvements Unis de la R\u00e9sistance |trans-title=Organization of the Arm\u00e9e Secr\u00e8te and Consolidation Within the United Resistance Movement |website=Acad\u00e9mie de Lyon |access-date=2011-07-01 }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. {{dead link|date=July 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Haute-Savoie]] || Cmdr. [[Jean Vallette d'Osia]]<br/>[[Henri Romans-Petit]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Maurice Anjot|fr}} (adjoint)<br/>[[Tom Morel]] (maquis)\n|-\n| [[Is\u00e8re (d\u00e9partement)|Is\u00e8re]] || Samuel Job<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Albert Reynier|fr}}<ref>{{Harvsp|Muller|2003|p=26}}.</ref><br/>Cmdr. de Reyni\u00e8s<ref>{{Harvsp|Muller|2003|p=151}}.</ref> || Cmdr. Albert S\u00e9guin de Reyni\u00e8s (genl. staff)<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Louis Nal|fr}}<ref>{{Harvsp|Muller|2003|p=152}}.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Jura (d\u00e9partement)|Jura]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Valentin Abeille|fr|3=Valentin Abeille (r\u00e9sistant)}} ||\n|-\n| [[Loire (d\u00e9partement)|Loire]] || Lt. {{Interlanguage link multi|Ga\u00ebtan Vidiani|fr}} ||\n|-\n| [[Haute-Loire]] || Capt. {{Interlanguage link multi|Alfred Salvatelli|fr}} ||\n|-\n| [[Sa\u00f4ne-et-Loire]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Georges de la Fert\u00e9-S\u00e9nect\u00e8re|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | '''R2 - Sud-Est''' || '''Region''' || {{Interlanguage link multi|Henri Masi|fr}} || {{Interlanguage link multi|Charles Gonard|fr}} (volunteer corps)<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Jean Garcin|fr}} (volunteer corps)\n|-\n| [[Bouches-du-Rh\u00f4ne]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Andr\u00e9 Aune|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | '''R3 - Sud''' || '''Region''' ||||\n|-\n| [[Gard]] || Albert Thomas ||\n|-\n| [[H\u00e9rault (d\u00e9partement)|H\u00e9rault]] || || {{Interlanguage link multi|Georges Flandre|fr}} \n|-\n| [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Orientales]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Louis Torcatis|fr}}<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Dominique Cayrol|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | '''R4 - Sud-Ouest''' || '''Region''' || Delmas<ref name=\"Brutus\">{{Harvsp|Boyer|Binot|2007}}</ref><br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Maurice Rousselier|fr}} ||\n|-\n| [[Ari\u00e8ge (department)|Ari\u00e8ge]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Joseph-Paul Rambaud|fr}} ||\n|-\n| [[Haute-Garonne]] || Cmdr. Rigal<ref>{{cite book |language=French |last1=Maru\u00e9jol |first1=Ren\u00e9 |last2=Vielzeuf |first2=Aym\u00e9 |title=Le maquis Bir-Hakeim |trans-title=The Bir-Hakeim Maquis |publisher=\u00e9ditions Le Camariguo |year=1982 <!-- |passage=26 -->}}.</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Tarn (d\u00e9partement)|Tarn]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Robert Rossi|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | '''R5 - Limousin''' || '''Region''' ||||\n|-\n| [[Corr\u00e8ze (d\u00e9partement)|Corr\u00e8ze]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Martial Brigouleix|fr}} || {{Interlanguage link multi|Marius Guedin|fr}} (maquis)<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Louis Lemoigne|fr}} (civilian)\n|-\n| [[Creuse (d\u00e9partement)|Creuse]] ||  || {{Interlanguage link multi|Marcel Fleisser|fr}} (maquis)<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Albert Fossey-Fran\u00e7ois|fr}} (maquis)\n|-\n| [[Dordogne (d\u00e9partement)|Dordogne]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Raymond Berggren|fr}}<ref name=\"Brutus\"/><br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Mojzesz Goldman|fr}}<ref>{{cite book |language=French |title=Mojzesz Goldman dit \"Mireille\": premier chef d\u00e9partemental du maquis A.S., Dordogne, 1943 |trans-title=Moises \"Mireille\" Goldman: First Departmental Director of the Maquis |last1=Le Bail |first1=Sylvain |publisher=Ch\u00eane Vert |year=2001}}.</ref> || Maurice Loupias (''Bergeret'', volunteer corps)<ref name=\"Brutus\"/><br/>\n|-\n| [[Haute-Vienne]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Yves Tavet|fr}}<ref name=\"Brutus\"/> ||\n|-\n| [[Indre (d\u00e9partement)|Indre]] || Capt. Ren\u00e9 Antoine (Carpy)<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Paul Mirguet|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | '''R6 - Auvergne''' || '''Region''' || Jean Chappat<ref>{{cite book |language=French |last1=Adler |first1=Laure |title=Fran\u00e7oise |trans-title=Fran\u00e7oise  |date=2011-01-19 |publisher=Grasset}}.</ref>||\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Resistance during World War II]]\n*[[Maquis (World War II)]]\n*[[Military history of France during World War II]]\n*[[Free France]]\n*[[Organisation de r\u00e9sistance de l'arm\u00e9e]]\n*[[zone libre]]\n*[[Francs-Tireurs et Partisans]]\n*[[French Forces of the Interior]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Armee Secrete}}\n[[Category:French Resistance networks and movements]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the Belgian resistance group|Arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te (Belgium)|the Algerian war dissident organisation|Organisation arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te}}\n{{Expand French|Arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te (France)|date=March 2019|topic=mil}}\n{{refimprove|date= July 2008}}\n\n{{Infobox Organization\n| name             = Arm\u00e9e Secr\u00e8te\n| native_name_lang = French\n| image            = Insigne Arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te Haute savoie.jpg\n| image_size       = 150\n| legend           = Insignia of the Arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te in Haute-Savoie\n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_caption      = The geographic organization of the Resistance\n| motto            = \n| region           = [[France]]\n| formation        = {{start date|1942|11|11|df=y}}\n| dissolution      = {{date|1|f\u00e9vrier|1944}}\n| extinction       = {{end date and age|1944|02|01}}\n| predecessor      = \n| type             = [[List of networks and movements of the French Resistance|Resistance network]]\n| headquarters     = \n| latitude         = \n| longitude        = \n| coords           = \n| language         = French\n| budget           = \n| membership       = \n| leader_title     = Chef\n| leader_name      = [[Charles Delestraint]]\n| leader_title2    = Chef d'\u00e9tat-major\n| leader_name2     = {{Interlanguage link multi|Fran\u00e7ois Morin-Forestier|fr}}, later [[Pierre Dejussieu-Pontcarral]]\n| leader_name3     = \n| leader_title3    = \n| key_people       = [[Henri Frenay]], [[Jean Moulin]]\n| affiliations     = [[Mouvements unis de la R\u00e9sistance]] (MUR)\n| site web         =\n}}\n\n[[File:R\u00e9gions r\u00e9sistance.jpg|thumb|300px|Regional organization of the [[French Resistance]]]]\n[[File:20_rue_Vauban_\u00e0_Lyon_-_plaque_comm\u00e9morative_mouvement_Combat_(gros_plan).jpg|thumb|350px|Commemorative plaque in Lyon]]\nIn [[World War II]] France this military organization grouped the paramilitary formations of the three most important [[Gaullist]] resistance movements in the southern zone: Combat, Lib\u00e9ration-Sud and the [[Franc-Tireur]]s.\n\nIn mid-1942, in the R1 Region, these three major movements wanted to coordinate the military units at their disposal to make them more effective. [[Henri Frenay]], leader of Combat, claimed command of the new structure, but faced opposition from [[Emmanuel d'Astier de La Vigerie]], leader of Liberation-Sud and [[:fr:Jean-Pierre L\u00e9vy (r\u00e9sistant)|Jean-Pierre Levy]], head of the Franc-Tireurs. [[Jean Moulin]] insisted that the post should go to someone who with no affiliation to one of these groups, so Frenay proposed [[Charles Delestraint]], a general recalled from his retirement during the [[Battle of France]], who admired De Gaulle and detested Vichy. He was the only general officer who had been promoted despite that defeat; the proposal was unanimously accepted.\n\nJean Moulin and General Delestraint first met on August 28, 1942 in Lyon. At the end of the interview, Jean Moulin ordered the three regional chiefs of the paramilitary formations of the great movements made available to Delestraint, for him to choose the best suited to the regional direction of the Secret Army. To this position, eminently clandestine and dangerous, the general named Captain {{ILL|Claudius Billon|fr}}. As early as September, Billon appointed each of the AS departmental heads for R1, with the exception of the AS chief for [[Ain]], named by Delestraint himself.\n\nIn October, Delestraint was appointed (officially) by [[General de Gaulle]]. [[Jean de Lattre de Tassigny|General de Lattre]] had also been approached for this post, but had refused. Delestraint took command on November 11, 1942. His secretary was {{ILL|Francois-Yves Guillin|fr}}; the head of the 2nd AS office was {{ILL|Joseph Gastaldo|fr}}. [[Andr\u00e9 Lassagne]] was the deputy of Gastaldo, before becoming Delestraint, and the information was entrusted to Albert Lacaze (4th office). Its chief of staff was {{ILL|Fran\u00e7ois Morin-Forestier|fr}}, from Combat, staff in which is also integrated [[Raymond Aubrac]].{{what|date=May 2019}}\n \nOn November 27, 1942 in [[Collonges-au-Mont-d'Or]], the constituent meeting of the Southern Zone Coordination Committee was held and the head of the Secret Army was presented by Jean Moulin. This committee intended to unite the three major resistance movements.\n\nIn December, Delestraint, inexperienced in the constraints of illegal life, crossed the demarcation line to make contact with the major movements in the northern zone: Liberation, the Civil and Military Organization (CMO) National, Lib\u00e9ration-Nord. Then, back in the free zone, he took part in the creation of the United Movements of the Resistance (MUR) on January 26, 1943 in Miribel, in Ain.\n\nAt the beginning of February 1943, {{ILL|Hugo Geissler|fr}}, Kommandeur of the [[Sicherheitspolizei|Sipo]]-[[Sicherheitsdienst|SD]] in Vichy, decapitated the Secret Army of the R1 region. On February 1 in Lyon's Place du Pont, he arrested Billon, head of the AS in R1 (eleven departments), along with his deputy Pierre Lavergne. On February 3, at 31, rue Basse-des-Rives in Saint-\u00c9tienne, during a secret meeting of the headquarters of the departmental AS, he also arrested the head of AS Loire, Lieutenant Vidiani, and his companions. On February 10, in [[Le Puy-en-Velay]], they continued to dismantle the AS in R1 with the arrest of the chief of AS in Haute-Loire Alfred Salvatelli and his companions at his home. After the February 10 arrest, the Haute-Loire resistance joined region R6 (Auvergne). On 27 May 1943, these three arrests, orchestrated by Geissler, featured prominently at the beginning of the [[Ernst Kaltenbrunner]]'s report addressed to [[Joachim von Ribbentrop]], Minister of Foreign Affairs for the Reich.\n\nDelestraint then fought against the advice of Frenay (who had been provisionally delegated general of the Secret Army) to put the Army under the tutelage of the MUR. Frenay, on the one hand the No. 2 of the Secret Army and on the other a member of the Coordination Committee of the same army, then wished the recall of Delestraint and his own appointment as head of the Secret Army, which were rejected by the other members of the Coordinating Committee, Moulin, d'Astier and Levy.\n\nIn London in February 1943 to meet Allied authorities, Delestraint was asked to make his troop the \"nucleus of the future French army\", estimated at 150,000 men. Unfortunately, Francois Morin-Forestier was arrested in March with Raymond Aubrac, [[Maurice Kriegel-Vallimont]] and {{ILL|Serge Ravanel|fr}} of the MUR, and only  released in May, thanks to the action of his former co-detainee Raymond Aubrac. His release did not allow his return to the staff: too exposed, he was ex-filtered to London. In April, Delestraint returned to Paris, arriving April 11. By the June 4 report, Moulin deplores the risks that Delestraint was taking, working alone when he would do better if assisted.\n\nOn June 9, 1943, Delestraint, Gastaldo and their deputy Jean-Louis Th\u00e9obald were arrested in Paris. On June 21, a staff meeting was held to find a successor to Delestraint in [[Caluire-et-Cuire]]. L\u00e9onard \u00c9mile Schwarzfeld, candidate to replace Delestraint, Aubrac, candidate for the leadership in the northern zone, and Lassagne for the southern zone, as well as other leaders of the Resistance such as Moulin, [[Henri Aubry]], [[Ren\u00e9 Hardy]], {{ILL|Albert Lacaze|fr}} and {{ILL|Bruno Larat|fr}} were taken prisoner. In July 1943, Colonel [[Pierre Dejussieu-Pontcarral]] was appointed chief of staff of a Secret Army now without an official leader. The Chief of Staff of the Southern Zone was General Jouffrault, until he was also arrested in August 1943.\n\nOn February 1, 1944, the Gaullist Secret Army merged with the [[French Forces of the Interior]] (FFI), with the Army Resistance Organization (ORA) and the French Francs-tireurs et partisans (FTPF, communists, not to be confused with the Franc-Tireur movement).\n\nThis structure was mainly found in the southern half of France: [[Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]] (R1) and [[Auvergne]] (R6), but also [[Limousin]] (R5), South-East and the Southwest (R4). It corresponded to the organizational structure used by Combat.\n\nUniting the regions of the free zone took only a few weeks, the various chiefs being chosen from among the regional chiefs in office. In Region A, the workforce was almost entirely composed of members of the CMO.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Regions==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable centre\" style=\"text-align:center; width=80%;\"\n|+ Layout of Resistance forces\n!width=\"25%\" | Region || Departement || Leader || Others\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | '''B''' || '''Region''' || General [[Louis-Eug\u00e8ne Faucher]] ||\n|-\n| [[Deux-S\u00e8vres]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Edmond Proust|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | '''M''' || '''Region''' || General {{Interlanguage link multi|Louis-Alexandre Audibert|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | '''M2''' || '''Region''' || General {{Interlanguage link multi|Marcel Allard|fr}} ||\n|-\n| [[Finist\u00e8re]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Mathieu Donnart|fr}}<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Roger Bourri\u00e8res|fr}} ||\n|-\n| [[Morbihan]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Maurice Guillaudot|fr}}<br/>[[Paul Chenailler]] ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"8\" | '''R1 - Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes''' || '''Region''' || Captain {{Interlanguage link multi|Claudius Billon|fr}}<br/><br/>Capt. {{Interlanguage link multi|Albert Chambonnet|fr}}<br/>|| {{Interlanguage link multi|Pierre Lavergne|fr}} (Maquis)<br/><br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Andr\u00e9 Vansteenberghe|fr}} (intelligence)\n|-\n| [[Ain (d\u00e9partement)|Ain]] || Andr\u00e9 ''Bob'' Fornier<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maquisdelain.org/index.php?r=personnage&id=60 |language=French |title=Maquis de l'Ain et du Haut-Jura |trans-title=Maquis of the Ain and Haut-Jura |access-date=2015-07-07}}</ref><br/>Capt. [[Henri Romans-Petit]]<ref name=\"Petit\">{{cite web |url=http://www.memoire-deportation-ain.fr/la-r\u00e9sistance-arm\u00e9e.aspx |language=French |title=La R\u00e9sistance arm\u00e9e |trans-title=Armed Resistance |publisher=M\u00e9moire de la D\u00e9portation dans l'Ain (1939-1945) |access-date=2014-02-22}}.</ref> || Jean Perret<br/>Marcel Gagneux<ref name=\"Lyon\">{{cite web|language=French |url=http://www2.ac-lyon.fr/etab/colleges/col-01/vailland/IMG/pdf/armee_secrete.pdf |type=pdf |title=Structuration de l'Arm\u00e9e Secr\u00e8te et unification au sein des Mouvements Unis de la R\u00e9sistance |trans-title=Organization of the Arm\u00e9e Secr\u00e8te and Consolidation Within the United Resistance Movement |website=Acad\u00e9mie de Lyon |access-date=2011-07-01 }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. {{dead link|date=July 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Haute-Savoie]] || Cmdr. [[Jean Vallette d'Osia]]<br/>[[Henri Romans-Petit]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Maurice Anjot|fr}} (adjoint)<br/>[[Tom Morel]] (maquis)\n|-\n| [[Is\u00e8re (d\u00e9partement)|Is\u00e8re]] || Samuel Job<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Albert Reynier|fr}}<ref>{{Harvsp|Muller|2003|p=26}}.</ref><br/>Cmdr. de Reyni\u00e8s<ref>{{Harvsp|Muller|2003|p=151}}.</ref> || Cmdr. Albert S\u00e9guin de Reyni\u00e8s (genl. staff)<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Louis Nal|fr}}<ref>{{Harvsp|Muller|2003|p=152}}.</ref>\n|-\n| [[Jura (d\u00e9partement)|Jura]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Valentin Abeille|fr|3=Valentin Abeille (r\u00e9sistant)}} ||\n|-\n| [[Loire (d\u00e9partement)|Loire]] || Lt. {{Interlanguage link multi|Ga\u00ebtan Vidiani|fr}} ||\n|-\n| [[Haute-Loire]] || Capt. {{Interlanguage link multi|Alfred Salvatelli|fr}} ||\n|-\n| [[Sa\u00f4ne-et-Loire]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Georges de la Fert\u00e9-S\u00e9nect\u00e8re|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | '''R2 - Sud-Est''' || '''Region''' || {{Interlanguage link multi|Henri Masi|fr}} || {{Interlanguage link multi|Charles Gonard|fr}} (volunteer corps)<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Jean Garcin|fr}} (volunteer corps)\n|-\n| [[Bouches-du-Rh\u00f4ne]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Andr\u00e9 Aune|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | '''R3 - Sud''' || '''Region''' ||||\n|-\n| [[Gard]] || Albert Thomas ||\n|-\n| [[H\u00e9rault (d\u00e9partement)|H\u00e9rault]] || || {{Interlanguage link multi|Georges Flandre|fr}} \n|-\n| [[Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Orientales]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Louis Torcatis|fr}}<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Dominique Cayrol|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | '''R4 - Sud-Ouest''' || '''Region''' || Delmas<ref name=\"Brutus\">{{Harvsp|Boyer|Binot|2007}}</ref><br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Maurice Rousselier|fr}} ||\n|-\n| [[Ari\u00e8ge (department)|Ari\u00e8ge]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Joseph-Paul Rambaud|fr}} ||\n|-\n| [[Haute-Garonne]] || Cmdr. Rigal<ref>{{cite book |language=French |last1=Maru\u00e9jol |first1=Ren\u00e9 |last2=Vielzeuf |first2=Aym\u00e9 |title=Le maquis Bir-Hakeim |trans-title=The Bir-Hakeim Maquis |publisher=\u00e9ditions Le Camariguo |year=1982 <!-- |passage=26 -->}}.</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Tarn (d\u00e9partement)|Tarn]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Robert Rossi|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | '''R5 - Limousin''' || '''Region''' ||||\n|-\n| [[Corr\u00e8ze (d\u00e9partement)|Corr\u00e8ze]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Martial Brigouleix|fr}} || {{Interlanguage link multi|Marius Guedin|fr}} (maquis)<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Louis Lemoigne|fr}} (civilian)\n|-\n| [[Creuse (d\u00e9partement)|Creuse]] ||  || {{Interlanguage link multi|Marcel Fleisser|fr}} (maquis)<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Albert Fossey-Fran\u00e7ois|fr}} (maquis)\n|-\n| [[Dordogne (d\u00e9partement)|Dordogne]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Raymond Berggren|fr}}<ref name=\"Brutus\"/><br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Mojzesz Goldman|fr}}<ref>{{cite book |language=French |title=Mojzesz Goldman dit \"Mireille\": premier chef d\u00e9partemental du maquis A.S., Dordogne, 1943 |trans-title=Moises \"Mireille\" Goldman: First Departmental Director of the Maquis |last1=Le Bail |first1=Sylvain |publisher=Ch\u00eane Vert |year=2001}}.</ref> || Maurice Loupias (''Bergeret'', volunteer corps)<ref name=\"Brutus\"/><br/>\n|-\n| [[Haute-Vienne]] || {{Interlanguage link multi|Yves Tavet|fr}}<ref name=\"Brutus\"/> ||\n|-\n| [[Indre (d\u00e9partement)|Indre]] || Capt. Ren\u00e9 Antoine (Carpy)<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Paul Mirguet|fr}} ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | '''R6 - Auvergne''' || '''Region''' || Jean Chappat<ref>{{cite book |language=French |last1=Adler |first1=Laure |title=Fran\u00e7oise |trans-title=Fran\u00e7oise  |date=2011-01-19 |publisher=Grasset}}.</ref>||\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Resistance during World War II]]\n*[[Maquis (World War II)]]\n*[[Military history of France during World War II]]\n*[[Free France]]\n*[[Organisation de r\u00e9sistance de l'arm\u00e9e]]\n*[[zone libre]]\n*[[Francs-tireurs et Partisans]]\n*[[French Forces of the Interior]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Armee Secrete}}\n[[Category:French Resistance networks and movements]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in France]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling correction; redirect bypass fromFrancs-tireurs et PartisanstoFrancs-Tireurs et Partisansusingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arm%C3%A9e_secr%C3%A8te"}
{"title_page": "Enlargement of NATO", "text_new": "{{about|the historical and future expansion of NATO|the composition of NATO|Member states of NATO}}\n{{short description|countries joining the military alliance}}\n{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n[[File:Map of NATO chronological.gif|350px|right|thumb|Map of NATO countries' chronological membership|alt=An animation showing the year and location of counties as they joined the alliance.]]\n\n'''Enlargement of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization''' ('''NATO''') is the process of including new member states in [[NATO]]. NATO is a [[military alliance]] of twenty-eight [[Europe]]an and two [[North America]]n countries that constitutes a system of [[collective defense]]. The process of joining the alliance is governed by Article 10 of the [[North Atlantic Treaty]], which allows only for the invitation of \"other European States\", and by subsequent agreements. Countries wishing to join have to meet certain requirements and complete a multi-step process involving political dialogue and military integration. The accession process is overseen by the [[North Atlantic Council]], NATO's governing body.\n\nAfter its formation in 1949 with [[North Atlantic Treaty#Founding members|twelve founding members]], NATO grew by including [[Greece]] and [[Turkey]] in 1952 and [[West Germany]] in 1955, and then later [[Spain]] in 1982. After the [[Cold War]] ended, and [[Germany reunited]] in 1990, there was a debate in NATO about continued expansion eastward. In 1999, [[Poland]], [[Hungary]], and the [[Czech Republic]] joined NATO, amid much debate within the organization and Russian opposition. Another expansion came with the accession of seven [[Central and Eastern Europe]]an countries: [[Bulgaria]], [[Estonia]], [[Latvia]], [[Lithuania]], [[Romania]], [[Slovakia]], and [[Slovenia]]. These nations were first invited to start talks of membership during the [[2002 Prague summit]], and joined NATO shortly before the [[2004 Istanbul summit]]. [[Albania]] and [[Croatia]] joined on 1 April 2009, prior to the [[2009 Strasbourg\u2013Kehl summit]]. The most recent member states to be added to NATO are [[Montenegro]] on 5 June 2017 and [[North Macedonia]] on 27 March 2020.\n\nAs of 2020, NATO officially recognizes [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] as an official candidate and two aspiring members: [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and   [[Ukraine]]. Future expansion is currently a topic of debate in several countries outside the alliance, and countries like [[Sweden]], [[Finland]], and [[Serbia]] have open political debate on the topic of membership, while in countries like [[Ukraine]], support and opposition to membership is tied to ethnic and nationalist ideologies. The incorporation of countries formerly part of the [[Eastern Bloc]] and the [[Soviet Union]] has been a cause of [[NATO-Russia relations|increased tension]] between NATO countries and [[Russia]].\n\n==Past enlargements==\n{{See also|Member states of NATO}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-27106-0001, Paris, Verhandlungen \u00fcber NATO-Beitritt.jpg|thumb|[[London and Paris Conferences|Negotiations in London and Paris]] in 1954 ended the [[Allied-occupied Germany|allied occupation]] of [[West Germany]] and allowed for its rearmament as a NATO member.|alt=Four men stand behind podiums with their country names of France, Germany, United Kingdom, and United States, in front of a backdrop of the Eiffel Tower.]]\nNATO has added new members eight times since its founding in 1949 to include thirty members. Twelve countries were part of the founding of NATO: [[Belgium]], [[Canada]], [[Denmark]], [[France]], [[Iceland]], [[Italy]], [[Luxembourg]], [[the Netherlands]], [[Norway]], [[Portugal]], the [[United Kingdom]], and the [[United States]]. The [[Cold War (1947\u20131953)|early years of the Cold War]] saw a stark divide between Capitalist states, backed by United States, and [[Soviet Empire|Communist satellite states]] of the [[Soviet Union]]. This divide eased inclusion of [[Portugal under Salazar]] in NATO and encouraged the anti-Communist governments of [[Greece]] and [[Turkey]] to join NATO in 1952. Greece would suspend its membership in 1974, over the [[Turkish invasion of Cyprus]], but rejoined in 1980 with Turkey's cooperation.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.ibtimes.com/why-turkey-nato-704333 |title= Why Is Turkey In NATO? |work= The International Business Times |first= Palash |last= Ghosh |date= 26 June 2012 |accessdate= 13 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Bonn\u2013Paris conventions]] ended the allies\u2019 occupation of [[West Germany]], and were ratified in part on the condition that West Germany join NATO, which it did in 1955.<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://www.nato.int/docu/review/2005/issue2/english/history.html |title= Germany's accession to NATO: 50 years on |journal= NATO Review |date=Summer 2005 |first= Helga |last= Haftendorn |accessdate= 13 September 2014}}</ref> Though initially isolationist, [[Francoist Spain|Spain under Francisco Franco]] was staunchly anti-Communist, and bound by regular defence agreements with NATO countries.{{sfn|Magone|2009|p=439}} After [[Spanish transition to democracy|its transition to democracy]], [[Spain]] came under pressure to normalize its European relations, including joining NATO, which it did in 1982. A [[1986 Spanish NATO membership referendum|referendum in 1986]] confirmed popular support for this.{{sfn|Magone|2009|pp=385\u2013386}}\n\n===German reunification===\nThe first post-Cold War expansion of NATO came with [[German reunification]] on {{Nowrap|3 October}} 1990, when the former [[East Germany]] became part of the Federal Republic of Germany and the alliance. This had been agreed in the [[Treaty on the Final Settlement with Respect to Germany|Two Plus Four Treaty]] earlier in the year. To secure Soviet approval of a united Germany remaining in NATO, it was agreed that foreign troops and nuclear weapons would not be stationed in the former East Germany, and the topic of further NATO expansion east was raised.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/141845/mary-elise-sarotte/a-broken-promise |title= A Broken Promise? |first= Mary Elise |last= Sarotte |work= [[Foreign Affairs]] |date=September\u2013October 2014 |accessdate= 28 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThere is no mention of NATO enlargement in the September\u2013October 1990 agreements on German reunification, so there was no ''formal commitment'' not to expand.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Kramer|first=Mark|last2=Shifrinson|first2=Joshua R. Itzkowitz|date=2017-07-01|title=NATO Enlargement\u2014Was There a Promise?|journal=International Security|volume=42|issue=1|pages=186\u2013192|doi=10.1162/isec_c_00287|issn=0162-2889}}</ref><ref name=\"International Security\" /> Whether or not the West ''informally committed'' to not enlarge NATO to the East is a matter of dispute among historians and international relations scholars.<ref name=\":0\" /> Harvard University historian Mark Kramer rejects that an informal agreement existed,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kramer|first=Mark|date=2009-04-01|title=The Myth of a No-NATO-Enlargement Pledge to Russia|journal=The Washington Quarterly|volume=32|issue=2|pages=39\u201361|doi=10.1080/01636600902773248|issn=0163-660X}}</ref> whereas [[Texas A&M University]] political scientist Joshua R. Itzkowitz Shifrinson argues that an informal agreement existed.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"International Security\" /> In December 2017, Svetlana Savranskaya and Tom Blanton of the [[National Security Archive]] at George Washington University argued that newly declassified documents showed that an informal agreement existed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nsarchive.gwu.edu/briefing-book/russia-programs/2017-12-12/nato-expansion-what-gorbachev-heard-western-leaders-early|title=NATO Expansion: What Gorbachev Heard {{!}} National Security Archive|last=|first=|date=|website=nsarchive.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/when-washington-assured-russia-nato-would-not-expand|title=When Washington Assured Russia NATO Would Not Expand {{!}}}}</ref>\n\n[[Jack Matlock]], US ambassador to the Soviet Union during its final years, said that the West gave a \"clear commitment\" not to expand, and declassified documents indicate that Soviet negotiators were given the oral impression by diplomats like [[Hans-Dietrich Genscher]] and [[James Baker]] that NATO membership was off the table for countries such as [[Czechoslovakia]], [[Hungary]], or [[Poland]].<ref name=\"Spiegel review\">{{Cite news |last1= Klussmann |first1= Uwe |last2= Schepp |first2= Matthias |last3= Wiegrefe |first3= Klaus |date= 26 November 2009 |title= NATO's Eastward Expansion: Did the West Break Its Promise to Moscow? |url= http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/nato-s-eastward-expansion-did-the-west-break-its-promise-to-moscow-a-663315.html |work= [[Spiegel Online]] |accessdate= 7 April 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"International Security\">{{cite news|title= Deal or No Deal? The End of the Cold War and the U.S. Offer to Limit NATO Expansion |doi=10.1162/ISEC_a_00236}}</ref> In 1996, Gorbachev wrote in his ''Memoirs'', that \"during the negotiations on the unification of Germany they gave assurances that NATO would not extend its zone of operation to the east,\"{{sfn|Gorbachev|1996|p=675}} and repeated this view in an interview in 2008.<ref name=\"me\">{{cite news |title = Gorbachev: US could start new Cold War |author=Blomfield A and Smith M |location=Paris |date=6 May 2009 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/russia/1933223/Gorbachev-US-could-start-new-Cold-War.html |publisher=The Telegraph |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> However, in 2014, Gorbachev said \"The topic of 'NATO expansion' was not discussed at all [in 1990], and it wasn't brought up in those years. I say this with full responsibility. Western leaders didn't bring it up, either.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2014/11/06/did-nato-promise-not-to-enlarge-gorbachev-says-no/|title=Did NATO Promise Not to Enlarge? Gorbachev Says \"No\"|last=Pifer|first=Steven|date=|work=Brookings|access-date=2017-09-11|language=en-US}}</ref> Eduard Shevardnadze, foreign minister of the Soviet Union between 1985 and 1991, has always maintained that \"NATO's expansion beyond German borders never came up for negotiation.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> According to [[Robert Zoellick]], a [[United States Department of State|State Department]] official involved in the Two Plus Four negotiating process, no formal commitment regarding enlargement was made.<ref>{{cite news |first=Robert B. |last=Zoellick |url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-65576869 |title=The Lessons of German Unification |publisher=[[The National Interest]] |date=22 September 2000}}</ref>\n\n===Visegr\u00e1d Group===\n[[File:NATO Summit in Washington 1999.jpg|thumb|NATO added the [[Czech Republic]], [[Hungary]], and [[Poland]] at the [[1999 Washington summit]], and established the protocol for Membership Action Plans.|alt=A long red table makes a pentagon around a blue floor with the NATO compass logo, while many rows of people in suits sit on all sides.]]\nIn February 1991, Poland, Hungary, and the [[Czech Republic]] and [[Slovakia]] (as Czechoslovakia) formed the [[Visegr\u00e1d Group]] to push for [[European integration]] under the [[European Union]] and NATO, as well as to conduct military reforms in line with NATO standards. Internal NATO reaction to these former [[Warsaw Pact]] countries was initially negative, but by the [[1991 Rome summit]] in November, members agreed to a series of goals that could lead to accession, such as market and democratic liberalization, and that NATO should be a partner in these efforts. In subsequent years, wider forums for regional cooperation between NATO and its eastern neighbors were set up, including the [[North Atlantic Cooperation Council]] (later the [[Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council]]) and the [[Partnership for Peace]].{{sfn|David|Levesque|1999|p=200\u2013201}}\n\nWhile the other Visegr\u00e1d members were invited to join NATO at its [[1997 Madrid summit]], Slovakia was excluded based on what several members considered undemocratic actions by nationalist Prime Minister [[Vladim\u00edr Me\u010diar]].{{sfn|Gheciu|2005|p=72}} [[Romania]] and [[Slovenia]] were both considered for invitation in 1997, and each had the backing of a prominent NATO member, France and Italy respectively, but support for enlargement was not unanimous, particularly in the [[United States Congress|US Congress]].{{sfn|Barany|2003|pp=23\u201325}} In an open letter to US President [[Bill Clinton]], more than forty foreign policy experts including [[Bill Bradley]], [[Sam Nunn]], [[Gary Hart]], [[Paul Nitze]], and [[Robert McNamara]] expressed their concerns about NATO expansion as both expensive and unnecessary given the lack of an external threat from Russia at that time.{{sfn|Barany|2003|pp=16\u201318}}\n\nA 2006 study in the journal ''Security Studies'' argued that the NATO enlargements in 1999 and 2004 contributed to democratic consolidation in Central and Eastern Europe.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Epstein|first=Rachel|date=2006|title=Nato Enlargement and the Spread of Democracy: Evidence and Expectations|journal=Security Studies|volume=14|pages=63\u2013105|doi=10.1080/09636410591002509}}</ref>\n\n===Vilnius Group===\n[[File:Flags of Nato, Bulgaria, European Union - Military club, Plovdiv, Bulgaria.JPG|thumb|250px|Flags of NATO, Bulgaria, European Union at the Military club of [[Plovdiv]], [[Bulgaria]]]]\n\nShortly after the fall of the Berlin wall in 1989, the [[Presidency of George H. W. Bush|George H.W. Bush administration]] (1989-1993) began to debate internally whether enlargement of NATO was feasible and desirable.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Shifrinson|first=Joshua R.|date=2020|title=NATO enlargement and US foreign policy: the origins, durability, and impact of an idea|url=https://doi.org/10.1057/s41311-020-00224-w|journal=International Politics|language=en|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1057/s41311-020-00224-w|issn=1740-3898|via=}}</ref> By mid-1992, a consensus emerged within the administration that NATO enlargement was a wise realpolitik measure to strengthen American hegemony.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shifrinson|first=Joshua R. Itzkowitz|date=2020-04-01|title=Eastbound and down:The United States, NATO enlargement, and suppressing the Soviet and Western European alternatives, 1990\u20131992|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/01402390.2020.1737931|journal=Journal of Strategic Studies|volume=0|issue=0|pages=1\u201331|doi=10.1080/01402390.2020.1737931|issn=0140-2390}}</ref> In the absence of NATO enlargment, Bush administration officials worried that the European Union might fill the security vacuum in Eastern Europe, and thus challenge American post-Cold War influence.<ref name=\":2\" /> There was an active debate within the [[Presidency of Bill Clinton|Clinton administration]] (1993-2001) about the enlargement of NATO. Within the administration, some preferred a \"relatively swift conferral of full membership to a narrow range of countries\" whereas others wanted \"a slower, phased conferral of limited membership to a wide range of states\". Ultimately, the proponents of the former won the debate within the administration. This coupled with \"pleas from Central and Eastern European leaders, missteps by Russian President Boris Yeltsin, and victory by the pro-expansion Republican Party in the 1994 U.S. congressional election all helped advocates of full-membership enlargement to win.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sarotte|first=M.E.|date=2019-07-01|title=How to Enlarge NATO: The Debate inside the Clinton Administration, 1993\u201395|journal=International Security|volume=44|issue=1|pages=7\u201341|doi=10.1162/isec_a_00353|issn=0162-2889}}</ref>\n\nDomestic politics in Central and Eastern European countries continued to push for more enlargement, and political parties reluctant to move on NATO membership, such as the [[Bulgarian Socialist Party]] and Slovak [[People's Party \u2013 Movement for a Democratic Slovakia|HZDS]], were voted out of office.{{sfn|Barany|2003|pp=190, 48\u201350}} Hungary's interest in joining was confirmed by a [[1997 Hungarian NATO membership referendum|November 1997 referendum]] that returned 85.3 percent in favor of membership.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/17/world/hungarians-approve-nato-membership.html |title= Hungarians Approve NATO Membership |first= Jane |last= Perlez |work= The New York Times |date= 17 November 1997 |accessdate= 4 December 2014}}</ref> Russia's actions in the [[First Chechen War]] were also a motivating factor for several countries that had memories of similar Soviet offensives.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Chechnya Summons Uneasy Memories in Former East Bloc |url = http://articles.latimes.com/1995-01-14/news/mn-20008_1_soviet-union |newspaper= The Los Angeles Times |first= Dean E. |last= Murphy |date= 14 January 1995 |accessdate= 22 November 2015 |issn= 0458-3035}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bulgaria, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Romania, Slovakia, and Slovenia Join NATO DOD 106625793-5d3e18a1d58aa.webm|thumb|right|250px|start=00:14|US President [[George W. Bush]] makes a speech when Bulgaria, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Romania, Slovakia, and Slovenia Join NATO]]\nAt the [[1999 Washington summit]], where Hungary, Poland, and the Czech Republic officially joined, NATO also issued new guidelines for membership with individualized \"Membership Action Plans\" for [[Albania]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Estonia]], [[Latvia]], [[Lithuania]], [[North Macedonia]], Romania, Slovakia, and Slovenia.{{sfn|Wolchik|Curry|2011|p=148}} In May 2000, these countries joined with [[Croatia]] to form the [[Vilnius Group]] in order to cooperate and lobby for common NATO membership, and by the [[2002 Prague summit]] seven were invited for membership, which took place at the [[2004 Istanbul summit]].<ref name=soured>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-29030744 |title= Why Nato-Russia relations soured before Ukraine |date= 2 September 2014 |accessdate= 1 October 2014 |first= Laurence |last= Peter |work= BBC News}}</ref>  Russia was particularly upset with the addition of the three [[Baltic states]], the first countries that were part of the Soviet Union to join NATO.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Umland|first=Andreas|date=2016|title=Intermarium: The Case for Security Pact of the Countries between the Baltic and Black Seas|url=http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:0168-ssoar-48562-7|journal=IndraStra Global|language=en|volume=2|issue=4|pages=2}}</ref><ref name=soured/>\n\n===Adriatic Charter===\n\nCroatia also started a Membership Action Plan at the 2002 summit, leading to a national debate on whether a referendum on NATO membership needed to be held there. Croatian Prime Minister [[Ivo Sanader]] ultimately agreed in January 2008, as part of forming a coalition government with the [[Croatian Peasant Party|HSS]] and [[Croatian Social Liberal Party|HSLS]] parties, not to officially propose one.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://dalje.com/en-croatia/no-smoking-law-alcohol-limit-yes-referendum-no/111642 |title= No Smoking Law, Alcohol Limit-Yes, Referendum-No |work= Dalje |date= 4 January 2008 |accessdate= 9 January 2015 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150109232942/http://dalje.com/en-croatia/no-smoking-law-alcohol-limit-yes-referendum-no/111642 |archivedate= 9 January 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> [[Montenegro]] declared independence on 3 June 2006, and the new country subsequently joined the Partnership for Peace programme at the [[2006 Riga summit]].  Albania and Croatia were invited to join NATO at the [[2008 Bucharest summit]] that April, though Slovenia threatened to hold up Croatian membership over [[Croatia\u2013Slovenia border disputes|their border dispute]] in the [[Bay of Piran]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/23/world/europe/23croatia.html |title= Slovenia Border Spat Imperils Croatia's NATO Bid |work= The New York Times |first= Dan |last= Bilefsky |date= 22 March 2009 |accessdate= 9 January 2015}}</ref> Slovenia did ratify Croatia's accession protocol in February 2009,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://dalje.com/en-croatia/slovenia-ratifies-croatias-accession-in-nato/232508 |title= Slovenia Ratifies Croatia's Accession in NATO |date= 9 February 2008 |accessdate= 9 January 2015 |work= Dalje |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150109232952/http://dalje.com/en-croatia/slovenia-ratifies-croatias-accession-in-nato/232508 |archivedate= 9 January 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> and Croatia and Albania both officially joined NATO just prior to the [[2009 Strasbourg\u2013Kehl summit]], with little opposition from Russia.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.nbcnews.com/id/29995397/ns/world_news-europe/t/albania-croatia-become-nato-members/ |title= Albania, Croatia become NATO members |work= NBC News |agency= Associated Press |date= 1 April 2009 |accessdate= 9 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nMontenegro applied for a Membership Action Plan on 5 November 2008,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/60927/montenegro-hands-over-application-for-nato-s-map.html|title=Montenegro Hands over Application for NATO's MAP|date=6 November 2008|accessdate=9 February 2015|work=Turkish Weekly|agency=MIA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209180451/http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/60927/montenegro-hands-over-application-for-nato-s-map.html|archivedate=9 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which was granted in December 2009.<ref name=\"rttnews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rttnews.com/Content/GeneralNews.aspx?Node=B1&Id=1148255|title=Montenegro Joins NATO Membership Action Plan|date=4 December 2009|accessdate=4 December 2009}}</ref> Montenegro also began full membership with the [[Adriatic Charter]] of NATO aspirants in May 2009.<ref name=\"montenegro-timeline\">{{cite web |url= http://www.mvpei.gov.me/en/sections/NATO/Development-of-relations-between-Montenegro-and-NA/ |title= Development of relations between Montenegro and NATO \u2013 key dates |work= Ministry of Foreign Affairs and European Integration |year= 2013 |accessdate= 5 June 2015 |archive-url= https://archive.today/20160316070917/http://www.mvpei.gov.me/en/sections/NATO/Development-of-relations-between-Montenegro-and-NA/ |archive-date= 16 March 2016 |url-status= dead }}</ref><ref name=\"nato-montenegro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_49736.htm|title=NATO's relations with Montenegro|date=19 November 2014|accessdate=9 February 2015|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref>  On December 2, 2015, NATO formally invited Montenegro to join the alliance,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/12/02/us-nato-montenegro-idUSKBN0TL0J620151202 |title= NATO invites Montenegro to join alliance, defying Russia |first1= Robin |last1= Emmott |first2= Sabine |last2= Siebold |work= Reuters |date= 2 December 2015 |accessdate= 2 December 2015}}</ref> with negotiations concluding in May 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://staging.hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/E/EU_NATO?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-05-19-12-59-28 |title= NATO formally invites Montenegro as 29th member |agency= Associated Press |first1= John-Thor |last1= Dahlburg |first2= Matthew |last2= Lee |date= 19 May 2016 |accessdate= 19 May 2016 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://archive.today/20160521123400/http://staging.hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/E/EU_NATO?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-05-19-12-59-28 |archivedate= 21 May 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Montenegro formally joined NATO on 5 June 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/06/06/world/politics-diplomacy-world/montenegro-becomes-natos-29th-member-amid-bitter-opposition-moscow/ |title= Montenegro becomes NATO's 29th member amid bitter opposition from Moscow |website= The Japan Times |agency= AFP-JIJI |date= 5 June 2017 |accessdate= 5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[North Macedonia]] joined the [[Partnership for Peace]] in 1995, and commenced its Membership Action Plan in 1999, at the same time as [[Albania]]. At the [[2008 Bucharest summit]], [[Greece]] blocked a proposed invitation because it believed that its neighbor's constitutional name implies territorial aspirations toward its own region of [[Macedonia (Greece)|Greek Macedonia]]. NATO nations agreed that the country would receive an invitation upon resolution of the [[Macedonia naming dispute]].<ref name=veto>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7329963.stm|title= Nato Macedonia veto stokes tension|first=Oana|last=Lungescu|work=BBC News |date=2 April 2008|accessdate=12 May 2008}}</ref> Macedonia sued Greece at the [[International Court of Justice]] (ICJ) over their veto of Macedonia's NATO membership.  Macedonia was part of the [[Vilnius Group]], and had formed the [[Adriatic Charter]] with Croatia and Albania in 2003 to better coordinate NATO accession.{{sfn|Thiele|2005|pp=73\u201374}}  On 12 June 2017, Prime Minister [[Zoran Zaev]] signaled he would consider alternatives names for the country in order to strike a compromise with Greece, settle the naming dispute, and lift Greek objections to Macedonia joining the alliance.  The naming dispute was resolved with the [[Prespa Agreement]] in June 2018 under which the country adpoted the name North Macedonia, which was supported by [[2018 Macedonian referendum|a referendum]] in September 2018. NATO invited North Macedonia to begin membership talks on 11 July 2018,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/nato-invites-macedonia-begin-membership-talks-join-issue-56511753|title=NATO invites Macedonia to begin membership talks, says it can join once name issue is resolved|date=2019-07-11|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711200547/https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/nato-invites-macedonia-begin-membership-talks-join-issue-56511753|archive-date=11 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> and formal accession talks began on 18 October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_159541.htm|title=Formal Accession Talks with Skopje begin at NATO Headquarters|date=2018-10-08|website=NATO|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref> NATO's members signed North Macedonia's accession protocol on 6 February 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47139118|title=Macedonia signs Nato accession agreement|date=2019-02-06|website=[[BBC]]|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref> and most countries ratified the accession treaty in 2019, with [[Spain]] ratifying its accession protocol in March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.dailysabah.com/world/europe/nato-door-open-to-north-macedonia-after-spains-approval |title= North Macedonia will join NATO after depositing it's instrument of accession. |newspaper= Daily Sabah |agency= German Press Agency |date= 17 March 2020 |accessdate= 19 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Assembly of North Macedonia|Sobranie]] also ratified the treaty unanimously on 11 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/02/11/world/europe/ap-eu-north-macedonia-nato.html |title= North Macedonia Parliament Backs NATO Accession |newspaper= The New York Times |agency= Associated Press |date= 11 February 2020 |accessdate= 17 February 2020}}</ref> North Macedonia eventually became a NATO member state on 27 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_174589.htm|title=North Macedonia joins NATO as 30th Ally |date=27 March 2020 |website=NATO}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/north-macedonia-joins-the-nato-alliance/ |title=North Macedonia Joins the NATO Alliance |date=27 March 2020 |website=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Country\n!Enlargement\n|rowspan=20|[[File:History of NATO enlargement.svg|700px|Map of NATO expansion since 1949|alt=A map of Europe with eight colors that refer to the year different countries joined the alliance.]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 18 February 1952 || {{flagcountry|Greece}} || rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|First\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Turkey}}\n|-\n|9 May 1955 || {{flagcountry|Germany}} || align=center| Second\n|-\n|30 May 1982 || {{flagcountry|Spain}} || align=center| Third\n|-\n|3 October 1990 || style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| [[German reunification]]\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 12 March 1999 || {{flagcountry|Czech Republic}} || rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Fourth\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Hungary}}\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Poland}}\n|-\n|rowspan=7| 29 March 2004 || {{flagcountry|Bulgaria}} || rowspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Fifth\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Estonia}}\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Latvia}}\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Lithuania}}\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Romania}}\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Slovakia}}\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Slovenia}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1 April 2009 || {{flagcountry|Albania}} || rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Sixth\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Croatia}}\n|-\n|5 June 2017 || {{flagcountry|Montenegro}} || align=center| Seventh\n|-\n|27 March 2020 || {{flagcountry|North Macedonia}} || align=center| Eighth\n|}\n\n==Criteria and process==\n\n===Article 10===\nThe [[North Atlantic Treaty]] is the basis of the organization and as such, any changes including new membership requires ratification by all current signers of the treaty. The treaty's Article 10 describes how non-member states may join [[NATO]], and outlines NATO's \"open door\" policy:\n{{quote|1=The Parties may by unanimous agreement, invite any other European State in a position to further the principles of this Treaty and to contribute to the security of the North Atlantic area to accede to this Treaty. Any State so invited may become a Party to the Treaty by depositing its instrument of accession with the Government of the United States of America. The Government of the United States of America will inform each of the Parties of the deposit of each such instrument of accession.<ref>{{cite wikisource |title=North Atlantic Treaty |year=1949}}</ref>}}\nThis article poses two general limits to non-member states. First, only European states are eligible for new membership, and second, these states not only need the approval of all the existing member states, but every member state can put some criteria forward that have to be attained. In practice, NATO formulates a common set of criteria, but for instance [[Greece]] blocked the Republic of Macedonia's accession to NATO for many years due to the [[Macedonia naming dispute|disagreement over the use of the name Macedonia]]. Turkey similarly opposes the participation of the [[Republic of Cyprus]] with NATO institutions as long as the [[Cyprus dispute]] is not resolved.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.economist.com/node/14416843 |title= Fogh in the Aegean |date= 10 September 2009 |work= [[The Economist]] |accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nSince the [[1991 Rome summit]], when the delegations of its member states officially offered cooperation with Europe's newly democratic states, NATO has addressed and further defined the expectations and procedure for adding new members. The [[1994 Brussels summit#Accomplishments|1994 Brussels Declaration]] reaffirmed the principles in Article 10 and led to the \"Study on NATO Enlargement\". Published in September 1995, the study outlined the \"how and why\" of possible enlargement in Europe,<ref name=Trifunovska>{{harvnb|Trifunovska|2010|pp=36\u201337}}</ref> highlighting three principles from the 1949 treaty for members to have: \"democracy, individual liberty, and rule of law\".{{sfn|Frappi|Carati|2009|p=50}}\n\nAs NATO Secretary General [[Willy Claes]] noted, the 1995 study did not specify the \"who or when,\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/transatlantic-rift-haunts-nato-1571999.html |title= Transatlantic rift haunts Nato |first= Andrew |last= Marshall |date= 8 February 1995 |accessdate= 30 December 2014}}</ref> though it discussed how the then newly formed [[Partnership for Peace]] and [[North Atlantic Cooperation Council]] could assist in the enlargement process,{{sfn|Trifunovska|1996|pp=16\u201317}} and noted that on-going territorial disputes could be an issue for whether a country was invited.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.themoscowtimes.com/opinion/article/putins-nato-fears-are-groundless/502886.html |title= Putin's NATO Fears Are Groundless |first= Steven |last= Pifer |work= The Moscow Times |date= 2 July 2014 |accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref> At the [[1997 Madrid summit]], the heads of state of NATO issued the \"Madrid Declaration on Euro-Atlantic Security and Cooperation\" which invited three Eastern European countries to join the alliance, out of the twelve that had at that point requested to join, laying out a path for others to follow.<ref name=Trifunovska/>\n\n===Membership Action Plan===\nThe biggest step in the formalization of the process for inviting new members came at the [[1999 Washington summit]] when the Membership Action Plan (MAP) mechanism was approved as a stage for the current members to regularly review the formal applications of aspiring members. A country's participation in MAP entails the annual presentation of reports concerning its progress on five different measures:<ref>{{cite press release |url= http://www.nato.int/docu/pr/1999/p99-066e.htm |title= Membership Action Plan (MAP) |id= NAC-S(99)66 |work= NATO |date= 24 April 1999 |accessdate= 5 February 2015}}</ref>\n*Willingness to settle international, ethnic or external territorial disputes by peaceful means, commitment to the rule of law and human rights, and democratic control of armed forces\n*Ability to contribute to the organization's defence and missions\n*Devotion of sufficient resources to armed forces to be able to meet the commitments of membership\n*Security of sensitive information, and safeguards ensuring it\n*Compatibility of domestic legislation with NATO cooperation\n\nNATO provides feedback as well as technical advice to each country and evaluates its progress on an individual basis.<ref name=topic>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_49212.htm |title=NATO enlargement |work=NATO Topics |date=12 June 2014 |accessdate=29 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206200940/http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_49212.htm |archivedate=6 February 2015 }}</ref> Once a country is agreed to meet the requirements, NATO can issue that country an invitation to begin accession talks.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1079718.html |title= NATO: What Is A Membership Action Plan? |first= Claire |last= Bigg |work= Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date= 2 April 2008 |accessdate= 6 February 2015}}</ref> Currently, one country has a Membership Action Plan: [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref name=MAP>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_37356.htm |title=Membership Action Plan (MAP) |date=18 February 2019 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |publisher=[[NATO]] |df=dmy }}</ref> Former MAP participants were [[Accession of Albania to NATO|Albania]] and [[Accession of Croatia to NATO|Croatia]] between May 2002 and April 2009, [[Montenegro-NATO relations|Montenegro]] between December 2009 and June 2017 and [[North Macedonia-NATO relations|North Macedonia]] between April 1999 and March 2020, when they joined NATO. The final accession process, once invited, involves five steps leading up to the signing of the accession protocols and the acceptance and ratification of those protocols by the governments of the current NATO members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/docu/comm/2002/0211-prague/more_info/membership.htm|title=The Road to NATO membership|work=[[NATO]]|date=21 September 2007|accessdate=14 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Intensified Dialogue===\nIntensified Dialogue was first introduced in April 2005 at an informal meeting of foreign ministers in Vilnius, Lithuania, as a response to Ukrainian aspirations for NATO membership and related reforms taking place under President [[Viktor Yushchenko]], and which followed the 2002 signing of the NATO\u2013Ukraine Action Plan under his predecessor, [[Leonid Kuchma]].<ref name=topic/> This formula, which includes discussion of a \"full range of political, military, financial and security issues relating to possible NATO membership\" had its roots in the [[1997 Madrid summit]], where the participants had agreed \"to continue the Alliance's intensified dialogues with those nations that aspire to NATO membership or that otherwise with to pursue a dialogue with NATO on membership questions\".<ref name=\"NATO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/docu/update/2005/04-april/e0421b.htm|title=NATO launches 'Intensified Dialogue' with Ukraine|publisher=NATO|date=20 April 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2006, [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] became the second to be offered the Intensified Dialogue status, following a rapid change in foreign policy under President [[Mikhail Saakashvili]],<ref name=\"georgia-id\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/docu/update/2006/09-september/e0921c.htm|title=NATO offers Intensified Dialogue to Georgia|publisher=NATO|date=21 September 2006}}</ref> and what they perceived as a demonstration of military readiness during the [[2006 Kodori crisis]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1070226.html |title= Georgia: Kodori Operation Raises NATO Questions |first= Richard |last= Giragosian |work= Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date= 31 July 2006 |accessdate= 5 February 2015}}</ref> [[Montenegro]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], and [[Serbia]] similarly received offers at the April [[2008 Bucharest summit]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://euobserver.com/defence/25921 |title= France signals full return to NATO |work= EUobserver |first= Elitsa |last= Vucheva |date= 4 April 2008 |accessdate= 6 February 2015}}</ref> While their neighbors both requested and accepted the dialogue programme, Serbia's offer was presented to guarantee the possibility of future ties with the alliance.<ref name=Serbia_ID/>\n\n==Current status==\n[[File:NATO affiliations in Europe.svg|thumb|400px|Map of NATO in Europe{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}{{legend|darkblue|[[Members of NATO]]|outline=black}}{{legend|#2a7fff|[[Membership Action Plan]]|outline=black}}{{legend|darkgreen|[[Intensified Dialogue]]|outline=black}}{{Col-break}}{{legend|#ffd900|[[Individual Partnership Action Plan]]|outline=black}}{{legend|#ff7826|[[Partnership for Peace]] (PfP)|outline=black}}{{legend|red|[[Partnership for Peace#Aspiring members|Aspiring PfP members]]|outline=black}}{{col-end}} note that Membership Action Plan and Intensified Dialogue countries are also Partnership for Peace members |alt=A map of Europe with countries in six different colors based on their affiliation with NATO.]]\nBosnia and Herzegovina is the only country with a Membership Action Plan, which together with Georgia, were named NATO \"aspirant countries\" at the North Atlantic Council meeting on 7 December 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/natosource/russia-says-georgias-entry-to-nato-could-lead-to-war |title= Russia says Georgia's entry to NATO could lead to war |date= 9 December 2011 |agency= RIA Novosti |accessdate= 30 December 2014 |work= The Atlantic Council}}</ref>  Ukraine was recognized as an aspirant country after the [[2014 Ukrainian revolution]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+ NATO Aspirant Countries\n!Country<ref name=aspirant>{{cite web|url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/topics_49212.htm|title=Enlargement|date=2018-03-09|accessdate=2018-03-10|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref>\n![[Partnership for Peace]]<ref name=pfpsigs>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/pfp/sig-cntr.htm|title=Signatures of Partnership for Peace Framework Document|date=10 January 2012|accessdate=9 February 2015|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref>\n![[Individual Partnership Action Plan]]<ref name=IPAP>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_49290.htm|title=Individual Partnership Action Plans|accessdate=2013-11-13|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref>\n!Intensified Dialogue\n!Membership Action Plan<ref name=MAP/>\n!Accession Protocol\n|-\n|{{flag|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}||<span style=\"display:none\">2006\u201312</span> December 2006||<span style=\"display:none\">2008-01</span> September 2008<ref name=bosnia>{{cite web |url= http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_49127.htm |title= NATO's relations with Bosnia and Herzegovina |work= NATO |date= 17 June 2014 |accessdate= 5 June 2015}}</ref>||<span style=\"display:none\">2008-04</span> April 2008<ref name=bbc2008>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7329963.stm |work= BBC News |title= Nato Macedonia veto stokes tension |date= 4 April 2008 |accessdate= 5 February 2015}}</ref>||<span style=\"display:none\">2010-04</span> December 2018<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/nato-approves-membership-action-plan-with-bosnia-12-05-2018|title=NATO Approves Membership Action Plan for Bosnia|last=|first=|date=|website=balkaninsight.com|access-date=}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Originally invited to join the MAP in April 2010 under the condition that no Annual National Programme would be launched until one of the conditions for the [[High Representative for Bosnia and Herzegovina#Conditions for closure of the Office of the High Representative|OHR closure]] \u2013 the transfer of control of immovable defence property to the central Bosnian authorities from the two regional [[Political divisions of Bosnia and Herzegovina|political entities]] \u2013 was fulfilled.<ref name=\"bbcbih\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8638794.stm|title=Bosnia gets Nato membership plan|work=BBC News |date=22 April 2010|accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref>  Condition waived in 2018.|group=Note}} ||\n|-\n|{{flag|Georgia (country)|name=Georgia}} ||<span style=\"display:none\">1994-03</span> March 1994||<span style=\"display:none\">2004\u201310</span> October 2004||<span style=\"display:none\">2006\u201309</span> September 2006<ref>{{cite news |url= http://civil.ge/eng/article.php?id=13613|work= Civil Georgia|title=NATO Grants 'Intensified Dialogue' to Georgia|date=21 September 2006|accessdate=15 September 2008}}</ref>|| || \n|-\n|{{flag|Ukraine}} ||<span style=\"display:none\">1994-02</span> February 1994 || <span style=\"display:none\">2002-11</span> {{#tag:ref|NATO\u2013Ukraine Action Plan adopted on 22 November 2002.<ref name=NATOUkraineAP>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/ar/SID-40166323-FEE6CCD2/natolive/official_texts_19547.htm|title=NATO-Ukraine Action Plan|date=2002-11-22|accessdate=2013-11-11|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref>|group=Note}} || <span style=\"display:none\">2005-04</span> April 2005<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nato.int/docu/update/2005/04-april/e0421b.htm|work= NATO Update|title=NATO launches 'Intensified Dialogue' with Ukraine|date=21 April 2005|accessdate=21 April 2005}}</ref>|| ||\n|}\n{{reflist|group=Note|close}}\n\n===Bosnia and Herzegovina===\n{{main|Accession of Bosnia and Herzegovina to NATO}}\n[[File:Romanian Armored Personnel Carrier.JPEG|thumb|NATO-led Romanian [[IFOR]] peacekeepers patrolled Bosnia and Herzegovina under [[Operation Joint Endeavour]].|alt=A green tank with white letters spelling \"IFOR\" drives on a paved road lined with trees.]]\nThe [[Operation Deliberate Force|1995 NATO bombing of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] targeted the [[Army of Republika Srpska|Bosnian Serb Army]] and together with international pressure led to the resolution of the [[Bosnian War]] and the signing of the [[Dayton Agreement]] in 1995. Since then, NATO has led the [[Implementation Force]] and [[Stabilisation Force in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Stabilization Force]], and other peacekeeping efforts in the country. Bosnia and Herzegovina joined the Partnership for Peace in 2006, and signed an agreement on security cooperation in March 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region.php?yyyy=2007&mm=03&dd=19&nav_id=40222| title=Bosnia, NATO sign security deal|date=19 March 2007|work= B92|accessdate=22 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nBosnia and Herzegovina began further cooperation with NATO within their Individual Partnership Action Plan in January 2008.<ref name=bosnia/> The country then started the process of Intensified Dialogue at the [[2008 Bucharest summit]].<ref name=bbc2008>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7329963.stm |work= BBC News |title= Nato Macedonia veto stokes tension |date= 4 April 2008 |accessdate= 5 February 2015}}</ref> The country was invited to join the [[Adriatic Charter]] of NATO aspirants in September 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://2009-2017.state.gov/p/eur/rls/fs/112766.htm |title= Adriatic Charter Fact Sheet |work= Bureau of European and Eurasian Affairs |publisher= U.S. Department of State |date= 25 August 2011 |accessdate= 5 June 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] within [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] has expressed willingness to join NATO, however, it faces consistent political pressure from [[Republika Srpska]], the other political entity in the country, alongside its partners in [[Russia]].  On 2 October 2009, [[Haris Silajd\u017ei\u0107]], the Bosniak Member of the Presidency, announced official application for Membership Action Plan. On 22 April 2010, NATO agreed to launch the Membership Action Plan for Bosnia and Herzegovina, but with certain conditions attached.<ref name=\"bbcbih\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8638794.stm|title=Bosnia gets Nato membership plan|work=BBC News |date=22 April 2010|accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref> Turkey is thought to be the biggest supporter of Bosnian membership, and heavily influenced the decision.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.danas.org/content/nato_bih/2020960.html |title= BiH dobila zeleno svjetlo za MAP |work= |first= Lejla |last= Sari\u0107 |date= 23 April 2010 |accessdate= 6 February 2015 |language= Bosnian}}</ref>\n\nThe conditions of the MAP, however, stipulated that no Annual National Programme could be launched until 63 military facilities are transferred from [[Political divisions of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia's political divisions]] to the central government, which is one of the conditions for the [[High Representative for Bosnia and Herzegovina#Conditions for closure of the Office of the High Representative|OHR closure]].<ref name=BosniaMAP>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/news_62811.htm|title=Bosnia and Herzegovina and Membership Action Plan|date=22 April 2010|accessdate=17 November 2013|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/07/05/nato-rules-out-admitting-new-members-anytime-soon/ |title= NATO rules out admitting new members anytime soon |work= Fox News |date= 5 July 2014 |agency= Associated Press |accessdate= 6 February 2015}}</ref> The leadership of the [[Republika Srpska]] has opposed this transfer as a loss of autonomy.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://euobserver.com/defence/29924 |title= Nato grants Bosnia pre-membership status |work= EUobserver |first= Valentina |last= Pop |date= 23 April 2010 |accessdate= 6 February 2015}}</ref> All movable property, including all weapons and other army equipment, is fully registered as the property of the country starting 1 January 2006.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.mod.gov.ba/files/file/zakoni/Zakon-o-odbrani-bs.pdf|title=Law on Defence of Bosnia and Herzegovina|access-date=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403214419/http://www.mod.gov.ba/files/file/zakoni/Zakon-o-odbrani-bs.pdf|archive-date=3 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>  A ruling of the [[Constitutional Court of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] on 6 August 2017 decided that a disputed military facility in [[Han Pijesak]] is to be registered as property of Bosnia and Herzegovina. It is expected to be a precedent for all other similar facilities, and could thus be the final factor that will enable the activation of the MAP for Bosnia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/court-rejects-bosnian-serb-claim-to-army-facilities-08-16-2017|title=Court Rejects Bosnian Serb Claim to Army Facilities|date=2017-08-16|accessdate=2017-08-18|first=Danijel|last=Kovacevic}}</ref>  Despite that all immovable property is not fully registered, NATO approved the activation of the Membership Action Plan for Bosnia and Herzegovina, and called on Bosnia to submit an Annual National Program on 5 December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/nato-approves-membership-action-plan-with-bosnia-12-05-2018|title=NATO Approves Membership Action Plan for Bosnia|last=Lakic|first=Mladen|date=2018-12-05|website=Balkan Insight|language=en|access-date=2018-12-05}}</ref>\n\nAn August 2010 poll showed that 70 percent of the country supports NATO membership, but results were very different in the two constituent entities. While 90 percent of the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] supported NATO membership, only 33 percent in Republika Srpska did.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.debatesinternational.org/sites/default/files/Bosnia%20and%20Herzegovina%20Poll%20Report%20August%202010.pdf |page= 35 |title= Public Opinion Poll Bosnia and Herzegovina |date= August 2010 |work= National Democratic Institute |accessdate= 25 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nBosnian chances of joining NATO may depend on Serbia's attitude towards the alliance, since the leadership of Republika Srpska might be reluctant to go against Serbian interests.<ref name=\"Srpska\">{{cite news|title=Bosnia's NATO hopes 'depend on Serbia'|url=http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/164962/bosnia-39-s-nato-hopes-39-depend-on-serbia-39.html|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=The Journal of Turkish Weekly|date=27 March 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328042929/http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/164962/bosnia-39-s-nato-hopes-39-depend-on-serbia-39.html|archivedate=28 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In October 2017, the [[National Assembly (Republika Srpska)|National Assembly of the Republika Srpska]] passed a nonbinding resolution opposing NATO membership for Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/bosnian-serbs-pass-resolution-against-nato-membership/2017/10/18/ced82e48-b3e0-11e7-9b93-b97043e57a22_story.html|title=Bosnian Serbs pass resolution against NATO membership|date=18 October 2017|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=18 October 2017|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n===Georgia===\n{{Further|Georgia\u2013NATO relations}}\n[[File:Nato poster tbilisi.jpg|thumb|upright|An August 2009 sign in downtown [[Tbilisi]] promoting eventual integration with NATO|alt=A blue poster at a bus stop with the NATO logo and the words \"OUR FOREIGN POLICY PRIORITY IS THE INTEGRATION INTO NATO\" in white.]]\n[[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] moved quickly following the [[Rose Revolution]] in 2003 to seek closer ties with NATO. Georgia's northern neighbor, [[Russia]], opposed the closer ties, including those expressed at the [[2008 Bucharest summit]] where NATO members promised that Georgia would eventually join the organization.<ref name=stopped/>\n\nComplications in the relationship between NATO and Georgia includes the presence of Russian military forces in internationally recognized Georgian territory as a result of multiple recent conflicts, like the 2008 [[Russo-Georgian War]] over the territories of [[Abkhazia]] and [[South Ossetia]], both of which are home to a large number of citizens of the Russian Federation. On 21 November 2011, [[President of Russia|Russian President]] [[Dmitry Medvedev]] while addressing soldiers in [[Vladikavkaz]] near the Georgian border stated that Russia's 2008 invasion had prevented any further NATO enlargement into the former [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] sphere.<ref name=stopped>{{cite news| url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2011/11/21/idINIndia-60645720111121 | work=Reuters | title=Russia says Georgia war stopped NATO expansion | date=21 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nA [[2008 Georgian referendum|nonbinding referendum in 2008]] resulted in 72.5 percent of voters supporting NATO accession.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sputniknews.com/world/20080111/96285713.html|title=Georgians back NATO membership in referendum|date=11 January 2008|agency=RIA Novosti|work=Sputnik International|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref> In May 2013, [[Prime Minister of Georgia|Georgian Prime Minister]] [[Bidzina Ivanishvili]] stated that his goal was to get a Membership Action Plan (MAP) for his country from NATO in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurasianet.org/node/66914|title=Ivanishvili: We Will Get NATO MAP in 2014|last=Kucera|first=Joshua|date=2 May 2013|accessdate=17 August 2013}}</ref> In June 2014, diplomats from NATO suggested that while a MAP was unlikely, a package of \"reinforced cooperation\" agreements was a possible compromise.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/06/20/us-nato-georgia-idUSKBN0EV1HZ20140620 |title= NATO unlikely to grant Georgia step to membership: diplomats |first= Adrian |last= Croft |work= Reuters |date= 20 June 2014 |accessdate= 20 June 2014}}</ref> [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]] confirmed that this could include the building of military capabilities and armed forces training.<ref name=\"georgia-2014\">{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/06/25/us-nato-enlargement-idUSKBN0F00IJ20140625 |title= NATO will not offer Georgia membership step, avoiding Russia clash |first= Adrian |last= Croft |work= Reuters |date= 25 June 2014 |accessdate= 25 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Russian Foreign Minister [[Sergey Lavrov]] said that \"NATO approaching our borders is a threat to Russia.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Lavrov: If Georgia Joins NATO, Relations Will Be Spoiled |url=http://georgiatoday.ge/news/17482/Lavrov%3A-If-Georgia-Joins-NATO%2C-Relations-Will-Be-Spoiled |work=Georgia Today |date=26 September 2019}}</ref> He was quoted as saying that if [[NATO]] accepts Georgian membership with the article on collective defense covering only Tbilisi-administered territory (i.e., excluding the Georgian territories of [[Abkhazia]] and [[South Ossetia]], both of which are currently an [[List of states with limited recognition|unrecognized breakaway republics]] supported by Russia), \"we will not start a war, but such conduct will undermine our relations with NATO and with countries who are eager to enter the alliance.\"<ref name=LavrovNATO2019>{{cite web|url=https://agenda.ge/en/news/2019/2582 |title=Russian FM Lavrov supports resumption of flights to Georgia as Georgians 'realised consequences' of June 20 |publisher=Agenda.ge |date=2019-09-26 |accessdate=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n\n===Ukraine===\n{{Further|Ukraine\u2013NATO relations}}\n[[File:Vladimir Putin and Viktor Yanukovych in 2006.jpg|thumb|As president, [[Viktor Yanukovych]] pursued closer relations with Russia.|alt=Two men in suits sit talking around a low wooden table.]]\n[[Ukraine]]'s present and future relationship with NATO has been politically divisive, and is part of a larger debate between Ukraine's political and cultural ties to both the European Union and Russia. It established ties to the alliance with a NATO\u2013Ukraine Action Plan on 22 November 2002,<ref name=NATOUkraineAP>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/ar/SID-40166323-FEE6CCD2/natolive/official_texts_19547.htm|title=NATO-Ukraine Action Plan|date=2002-11-22|accessdate=2013-11-11|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_37750.htm?|title=NATO's relations with Ukraine|date=16 December 2014|accessdate=9 February 2015|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref> and joined NATO's [[Partnership for Peace]] initiative in February 2005.{{sfn|Yekelchyk|2007|p=202}} Then in April 2005, Ukraine entered into the Intensified Dialogue programme with NATO.<ref name=\"NATO\"/>\n\nIn March 2008, under [[President of Ukraine|Ukrainian President]] [[Viktor Yushchenko]] and [[Prime Minister of Ukraine|Prime Minister]] [[Yulia Tymoshenko]], Ukraine sent an official letter of application for a Membership Action Plan (MAP), the first step in joining NATO. These leaders however guaranteed their opposition that membership in any military alliance would not pass without public approval in a referendum.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/ukraine/2008/ukraine-080119-rianovosti01.htm|title=Ukraine will not join NATO without referendum|work=GlobalSecurity|date=19 January 2008|accessdate=20 September 2008| volume=5|issue=173}}</ref> This idea had gained support from a number of NATO leaders, particularly those in [[Central and Eastern Europe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://spectator.sme.sk/c/20001838/president-gasparovic-meets-ukrainian-foreign-affairs-minister.html|title= President Ga\u0161parovi\u010d meets Ukrainian Foreign Affairs Minister|work=[[The Slovak Spectator]]|date=20 March 2006|accessdate=20 September 2008| first=Marta|last=\u010eurianov\u00e1}}</ref> Russian leaders like Prime Minister and President-Elect [[Dmitry Medvedev]] made clear their opposition to Ukraine membership, and leading up to the April [[2008 Bucharest summit]] their emissary actively lobbied against a Ukrainian MAP. After some debate among members at the summit, NATO Secretary General [[Jaap de Hoop Scheffer]] declared in a press conference that Ukraine, together with Georgia, would someday join NATO, but neither would begin Membership Action Plans.{{sfn|Ambrosio|2013|pp=150\u2013154}} At this summit, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]], in his last international speech before switching jobs with Medvedev, listed his grievances with NATO, and called Ukrainian membership \"a direct threat\" to his country.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/05/world/europe/05nato.html |title= Putin, at NATO Meeting, Curbs Combative Rhetoric |first= Steven |last= Erlanger |date= 5 April 2008 |work= The New York Times |accessdate= 27 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:\u041c\u0430\u043a\u043a\u0435\u0439\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u0404\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0456.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Euromaidan]] protests that led to [[Viktor Yanukovych]] fleeing the presidency attracted support from Western politicians.|alt=Dozens of blue and yellow Ukrainian flags are held aloft in a wide crowd watching large screens on a square building.]]\nThe [[2010 Ukrainian presidential election|2010 election]] returned [[Viktor Yanukovych]] to the presidency and marked a turnaround in Ukraine's relations with NATO. In February 2010, he stated that Ukraine's relations with NATO were currently \"well-defined\", and that there was \"no question of Ukraine joining NATO\". He said the issue of Ukrainian membership of NATO might \"emerge at some point, but we will not see it in the immediate future\".<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/ukraine/2010/ukraine-100213-rianovosti02.htm Yanukovych opens door to Russian navy keeping base in Ukraine] GlobalSecurity.org Retrieved on 9 March 2010</ref> While visiting [[Brussels]] in March 2010, he further stated that there would be no change to Ukraine's status as a member of the alliance's outreach programme.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/ukraines-yanukovych-eu-ties-a-key-priority-60720.html |title= Ukraine's Yanukovych: EU ties a 'key priority' |work= [[Kyiv Post]] |date= 1 March 2010 |accessdate= 7 April 2015 |agency= Associated Press}}</ref> He later reiterated during a trip to Moscow that Ukraine would remain a \"European, non-aligned state\".<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thenews.com.pk/TodaysPrintDetail.aspx?ID=227513&Cat=1&dt=3/24/2010 |title= Ukraine vows new page in ties with Russia |date= 6 March 2010 |work= The News International |accessdate= 9 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/7774665/Ukraine-drops-Nato-membership-pursuit.html |title= Ukraine drops Nato membership pursuit |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |date= 28 May 2010 |accessdate=7 June 2010}}</ref> Then, on 3 June 2010 the [[Verkhovna Rada|Ukrainian parliament]] voted to exclude the goal of \"integration into Euro-Atlantic security and NATO membership\" from the country's national security strategy in a bill drafted by Yanukovych himself.<ref name=radanonato>[http://euobserver.com/24/30212 Ukraine drops NATO membership bid], [[EUobserver]] (6 June 2010)</ref> The bill forbade Ukraine's membership in any military bloc, but allowed for co-operation with alliances such as NATO.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/10229626.stm Ukraine's parliament votes to abandon Nato ambitions], [[BBC News]] (3 June 2010)</ref>\n\n[[File:Secretary Kerry Joins President Obama for Meeting With Ukrainian President Poroshenko Before NATO Summit in Wales (14950820747).jpg|thumb|[[Petro Poroshenko]] was elected as President of Ukraine in 2014, and met with NATO leaders prior to the [[2014 Wales summit|Wales summit]] about relations with the alliance.|alt=A group of men and women is Western business attire sit around a circular table with a blue tablecloth.]]\n\nFollowing months of [[Euromaidan]] street protests that began because of his refusal to sign an [[Ukraine\u2013European Union Association Agreement|Association Agreement with the European Union]] in favor of deals from Russia, President Yanukovych fled Kyiv in February 2014, ultimately to Russia, and parliament voted to remove him from his post. This brought another change in direction of Ukraine's association with Europe and by extension NATO. In 2014, [[2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine|pro-Russian unrest]] occurred in eastern Ukraine and [[Crimea]] was [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|annexed by the Russian Federation]] in March. As part of an effort to assuage concerned groups, newly installed Prime Minister [[Arseniy Yatsenyuk]] addressed the topic in a speech on 18 March 2014, emphasizing that Ukraine was not seeking NATO membership.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/03/18/uk-ukraine-crisis-nato-idUKBREA2H0DO20140318 |title= PM tells Ukrainians: No NATO membership, armed groups to disarm |first= Pavel |last= Polityuk |date= 18 March 2014 |work= Reuters |accessdate= 27 March 2014}}</ref> US President [[Barack Obama]] echoed this position the following week, while calling for greater NATO presence in Eastern Europe.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/03/26/us-usa-eu-summit-nato-idUSBREA2P1XJ20140326 |title= Obama says NATO needs to boost presence in eastern Europe |first1= Adrian |last1= Croft |first2= Jeff |last2= Mason |date= 26 March 2014 |accessdate= 27 March 2014 |work= Reuters}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in response to the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|Russian military intervention in Ukraine]],<ref name=\"uk.reuters.com\">{{Citation|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/04/17/russia-putin-crimea-idUKL6N0N921H20140417|title=Putin admits Russian forces were deployed to Crimea|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|date=17 April 2014|quote=\"We had to take unavoidable steps so that events did not develop as they are currently developing in southeast Ukraine.&nbsp;... Of course our troops stood behind Crimea's self-defence forces.\"}}</ref> Yatsenyuk announced his intentions to resume the bid for NATO integration on 29 August 2014,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28978699 |date= 9 August 2014 |title= Ukraine to seek Nato membership, says PM Yatsenyuk |work= BBC News |accessdate= 9 February 2015}}</ref> and in December 2014, Ukraine's parliament voted to drop the non-aligned status that it adopted in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-30587924 |title= Ukraine votes to drop non-aligned status |work= BBC News |date= 23 December 2014 |accessdate= 23 December 2014}}</ref> [[Secretary General of NATO|NATO Secretary General]] [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]] has stated that NATO membership is still an option for Ukraine,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.euronews.com/2014/02/26/door-to-nato-remains-open-for-ukraine/|agency=Euronews|title=Door to NATO remains open for Ukraine|date=26 February 2014|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> and support for NATO membership has risen to 63.9 percent in government-controlled Ukraine according to a July 2015 poll.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/281737.html |title= Support for joining NATO considerably increases in Ukraine \u2013poll |date= 3 August 2015 |accessdate= 4 August 2015 |work= Interfax-Ukraine}}</ref> Previous polls had shown that the decline in opposition to membership was linked to the ongoing Russian intervention.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.latimes.com/world/europe/la-fg-ukraine-russia-eu-nato-20140514-story.html |title= Russian aggression driving Ukrainians toward EU, NATO, poll finds |work= The Los Angeles Times |first= Carol J. |last= Williams |date= 14 May 2014 |accessdate= 15 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 June 2017, Ukraine's [[Verkhovna Rada]] passed a law making integration with NATO a foreign policy priority.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/427216.html|title=Rada restores Ukraine's course for NATO membership as foreign policy priority|date=2017-06-08|work=Interfax-Ukraine|access-date=2017-06-08}}</ref>  In July 2017 Poroshenko announced that he would seek the opening of negotiations on a [[Membership Action Plan]] with NATO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ukraine-nato-idUSKBN19V12V|title=Pledging reforms by 2020, Ukraine seeks route into NATO|date=2017-07-10|accessdate=2017-07-22|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\nBy March 2018, NATO had recognized Ukraine as an aspirant country.<ref name=aspirant/>\n\nOn September 20, 2018, the Ukrainian parliament approved amendments to the constitution that would make the accession of the country to NATO and the EU a central goal and the main foreign policy objective.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ukraine pushes ahead with plans to secure NATO membership |url=https://www.apnews.com/dff40992fcc446f6808d02d03b35e4bc |website=Associated Press |accessdate=October 15, 2018|date=2018-09-20 }}</ref>\n\n==Membership debates==\n{{Further|Foreign relations of NATO}}\n\n===Finland===\n[[File:Finnish border in Raattentie - panoramio.jpg|thumb|The [[Finnish\u2013Russian border|border between Finland and Russia]] is about 1,340&nbsp;km (833&nbsp;mi) long.{{sfn|Grenfell|Jopling|2008|p=13}}|alt=A simple white fence with a red and yellow gate behind it set across a dirt path in a green forest.]]\n[[Finland]] participates in nearly all sub-areas of the Partnership for Peace programme, and has provided peacekeeping forces to both the Afghanistan and Kosovo missions. The possibility of Finland's membership in NATO was one of the most important issues debated in relation to the [[2006 Finnish presidential election|Finnish presidential election of 2006]], and continues to be a significant issue in Finnish politics.<ref name=sauli>{{cite news|url=http://www.worldpress.org/Europe/2279.cfm|title=Finland Debates Its Ties With NATO|first=Jeroen|last=Bult|date= 3 March 2006|accessdate=20 September 2008|work=Worldpress}}</ref> In 2007, Finland made various technical preparations for membership, with the then Defence Minister [[Jyri H\u00e4k\u00e4mies]] eager to pursue NATO membership.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://euobserver.com/9/23948|work=EUobserver|title=Finland waits for new EU treaty before NATO membership review|first=Andrew|last=Rettman|date=26 April 2007|accessdate=20 September 2008}}</ref> Nevertheless, public interest in the issue has since decreased. In April 2014, the government announced that they would sign a \"Memorandum of Understanding\" with NATO on Finland's readiness to receive military assistance and to aid NATO in equipment maintenance. However, Defence Minister [[Carl Haglund]] emphasized that this memorandum would not be a step towards membership.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.finnbay.com/finland-signs-memorandum-of-understanding-with-nato/ |title= Finland To Sign Memorandum Of Understanding With NATO |date= 22 April 2014 |accessdate= 22 April 2014 |work= Finnbay}}</ref>\n\nOut of the major Finnish political parties, the [[National Coalition Party]] and [[Swedish People's Party of Finland]] support NATO membership. In 2016, the party conference of the National Coalition Party agreed that Finland should apply for membership \"in the next few years\".<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.verkkouutiset.fi/politiikka/kokoomuksen%20kannanotot-51679 |title= Kokoomus p\u00e4\u00e4tti Nato-linjastaan: Puolustusliittoon l\u00e4hivuosina |date= 12 June 2016 |accessdate= 12 June 2016 |publisher= Verkkouutiset}}</ref> In the vision of the Swedish People's Party of Finland, Finland will be a NATO member in 2025.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://yle.fi/uutiset/rkp_on_nyt_virallisesti_nato-puolue/8951589 |title= RKP on nyt virallisesti Nato-puolue |date= 12 June 2016 |accessdate= 12 June 2016 |publisher= Yle}}</ref> Many individual politicians have advocated for NATO as well, including the current President [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]] and former Prime Minister [[Alexander Stubb]],<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/06/14/us-finland-primeminister-idUSKBN0EP0EW20140614 |title= Stubb to be Finland's next PM, backs NATO membership |first1= Jussi |last1= Rosendahl |first2= Sakari |last2= Suoninen |date= 14 June 2014 |accessdate= 14 June 2014 |work= Reuters}}</ref> as well as former President [[Martti Ahtisaari]],<ref name=sauli/><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.alaskadispatch.com/article/20140412/ex-president-ahtisaari-calls-finland-join-nato-sweden |title= Ex-President Ahtisaari calls on Finland to join NATO with Sweden |work= Alaska Dispatch |agency= YLE News |date= 12 April 2014 |accessdate= 18 April 2014 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140419031103/https://www.alaskadispatch.com/article/20140412/ex-president-ahtisaari-calls-finland-join-nato-sweden |archivedate= 19 April 2014 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> who has argued that Finland should join all the organizations supported by other Western democracies in order \"to shrug off once and for all the burden of [[Finlandization]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www2.hs.fi/english/archive/news.asp?id=20031215IE6|title=Former President Ahtisaari: NATO membership would put an end to Finlandisation murmurs|work=Helsingin Sanomat|date=15 December 2003|accessdate=20 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205075236/http://www2.hs.fi/english/archive/news.asp?id=20031215IE6|archivedate=5 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Two other former presidents from the [[Social Democratic Party of Finland|Social Democratic Party]], [[Tarja Halonen]] and [[Mauno Koivisto]], have publicly opposed the idea, arguing that NATO membership would deteriorate Finland's relations with [[Russia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www2.hs.fi/english/archive/news.asp?id=20040120IE3|title=Finland, NATO, and Russia|work=Helsingin Sanomat|date=20 January 2004|accessdate=20 September 2008|first=Max|last=Jakobson|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205075241/http://www2.hs.fi/english/archive/news.asp?id=20040120IE3|archivedate=5 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFinland has received some very critical feedback from Russia for even considering the possibility of joining NATO,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.finnbay.com/media/news/russian-foreign-minister-lavro-finland-wouldnt-dare-nato-membership/ |title= Russian Foreign Minister Lavrov: Finland Wouldn't Dare for NATO Membership |date= 15 June 2014 |accessdate= 15 June 2014 |work= Finnbay}}</ref> with a 2009 study suggesting this could have repercussions for Russia's relations with the EU and NATO as a whole.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.da.mod.uk/colleges/arag/document-listings/special/09(14)%20KGSE%20Web.pdf|title=Waking the Neighbour: Finland, NATO and Russia: Keir Giles and Susanna Eskola, UK Defence Academy, November 2009|publisher=}}</ref> Following the 2008 [[Russo-Georgian War]], [[Prime Minister of Finland|Finnish Prime Minister]] [[Matti Vanhanen]] reiterated that Finland had no plans to join NATO, and stated that the main lesson of the war was the need for closer ties to Russia.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aqM3uWSVFD7s Deeper Russia Ties Is Georgia War Lesson, Finnish Premier Says] [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] Retrieved on 9 October 2009</ref> In a June 2014 interview in the Finnish newspaper ''[[Hufvudstadsbladet]]'', Vladimir Putin's personal envoy [[Sergey Alexandrovich Markov]] accused Finland of extreme \"Russophobia\" and suggested that Finland joining NATO could start World War III.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://barentsobserver.com/en/security/2014/06/putin-envoy-warns-finland-against-joining-nato-09-06 |title= Putin envoy warns Finland against joining NATO |work= [[Barents Observer]] |first= Thomas |last= Nilsen |date= 9 June 2014 |accessdate= 9 June 2014}}</ref>  In July 2016, Putin stated on a visit to Finland that Russia would increase the number of troops on the Finnish border if Finland were to join NATO. He also warned that NATO would \"fight to the last Finn against Russia\".<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.hs.fi/kotimaa/a1467354133054 |title= Putin moitti Natoa tiukasti Suomen-vierailullaan |work= Helsingin Sanomat |date= 2 July 2016 |accessdate= 3 July 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.helsinkitimes.fi/finland/finland-news/domestic/14078-putin-has-toughened-up-his-rhetoric-views-expert.html Putin has toughened up his rhetoric, views expert]. helsinkitimes.fi (5 July 2016). Retrieved on 22 July 2016.</ref>\n\nA survey conducted by Finnish pollster EVA in January 2015 found that 43 percent of Finns polled opposed NATO membership, while 26 percent supported and 32 percent were undecided. EVA has noted a downward trend in the percent opposed that started in 1998, including a steep decline after the [[2012 Finnish presidential election|2012 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eva.fi/blog/2015/02/03/evan-arvo-ja-asennetutkimuksen-ennakkotieto-nato-kannat-muuttuneet-myonteisemmiksi/|title=MEVAn Arvo- ja asennetutkimuksen ennakkotieto: Nato-kannat muuttuneet my\u00f6nteisemmiksi|date=3 February 2015|accessdate=11 February 2015|work=Elinkeinoel\u00e4m\u00e4n valtuuskunta|language=Finnish}}</ref> In March 2014, during [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|Russia's annexation of Crimea]], one survey showed only 22 percent supported membership,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/850491.shtml |title= Most Fins reject NATO membership despite Ukraine crisis |agency= Xinhua |work= Global Times |date= 24 March 2014 |accessdate= 27 March 2014}}</ref> though a second showed that 53 percent would support membership if Finnish leadership recommended it.<ref>{{cite news |title= Verkkouutiset selvitti: Kansa valmis Natoon, jos valtiojohto niin haluaa |url= http://www.verkkouutiset.fi/kotimaa/nato%20galluppi%20julki%20ti-17919 |date= 25 March 2014 |work= Verkkouutiset |first= Satu |last= Schauman |accessdate= 1 September 2014 |language= Finnish}}</ref> Support for a military alliance with neighbor [[Sweden]] was also high, at 54 percent,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140326/DEFREG01/303260045/Majority-Finns-Support-Swedish-Military-Alliance |title= Majority of Finns Support Swedish Military Alliance |work= Defense News |date= 26 March 2014 |accessdate= 27 March 2014 |first= Gerard |last= O'Dwyer}}</ref> and Finland could possibly seek an enlarged role for [[NORDEFCO]].<ref name=DW>{{cite news|last=Steffen|first=Sarah|title=NATO next for Sweden and Finland?|url=http://www.dw.de/nato-next-for-sweden-and-finland/a-17519846|newspaper=DeutscheWelle|date=26 March 2014}}</ref> [[Minister of Defence (Finland)|Finnish Minister of Defence]] Carl Haglund suggested that a referendum on NATO membership could be held sometime after the [[2015 Finnish parliamentary election|2015 parliamentary election]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/06/18/us-finland-nato-defenceminister-idUSKBN0ET1V320140618 |title= Finnish reasons for joining NATO 'stronger than ever': defense minister |first1= Sakari |last1= Suoninen |first2= Jussi |last2= Rosendahl |date= 18 June 2014 |accessdate= 18 June 2014 |work= Reuters}}</ref>  A poll from October 2017 showed that support for membership remained at 22%, while rising to 33% in the suggested scenario in which Sweden would join.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hs.fi/politiikka/art-2000005436683.html|title=HS-gallup: Suomalaiset tyrm\u00e4\u00e4v\u00e4t Nato-j\u00e4senyyden \u2013 mutta onko Suomi jo tiiviimmin Naton kyljess\u00e4 kuin kansa tajuaakaan?|work=Helsingin Sanomat|date=5 November 2017|accessdate=5 November 2017}}</ref> The newest poll from December 2019 showed support decreasing further to 20%, while 56% opposed joining the alliance and 24% were unsure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hs.fi/politiikka/art-2000006343787.html|title=Suomalaisilta yh\u00e4 selv\u00e4 ei Nato-j\u00e4senyydelle|work=Helsingin Sanomat|date=15 December 2019|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ireland===\n{{Further|Ireland\u2013NATO relations}}\n[[File:20140828 Irish delegation at opening ceremonies.jpg|thumb|Ireland currently does not seek to join NATO, but does work to improve the [[Defence Forces (Ireland)|Defence Forces]]' interoperability with NATO<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thejournal.ie/ireland-committed-to-partnership-for-peace-but-has-no-plans-to-join-nato-shatter-838562-Mar2013/ |title= Ireland committed to Partnership for Peace but has no plans to join NATO \u2013 Shatter |first= Jennifer |last= Wade |newspaper= The Journal |date= 21 March 2013 |accessdate= 20 February 2016}}</ref>|alt=Male and female soldiers wearing camouflage marching behind the Irish tri-color flag.]]\n[[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] has been a member of NATO's [[Partnership for Peace]] (PfP) programme and [[Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council]] (EAPC) since 1999, but has a traditional policy of [[Irish neutrality|military neutrality]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NATO's 'neutral' European partners: valuable contributors or free riders?|url=http://www.nato.int/docu/review/2013/partnerships-nato-2013/NATOs-neutral-European-partners/EN/index.htm|publisher=NATO Review Magazine|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref> Ireland participates in the alliance's PfP Planning and Review Process (PARP), which aims to increase the [[interoperability]] of the Irish military, the [[Defence Forces (Ireland)|Defence Forces]], with other NATO member states and bring them into line with accepted international standards so as to successfully deploy with other professional military forces on [[peacekeeping]] operations overseas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Defence Questions: Irish cooperation with NATO in Ukraine|url=http://www.eoghanmurphy.ie/category/pqs/defence/|publisher=Eoghan Murphy TD|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref> Ireland supplied a small number of troops to the NATO-led [[International Security Assistance Force]] (ISAF) in [[Afghanistan]] (2001\u20132014) and supports the ongoing NATO-led [[Kosovo Force]] (KFOR).<ref>{{cite web|title=Current Missions > ISAF |url=http://www.military.ie/en/overseas/current-missions/isaf/ |publisher=Defence Forces Ireland |accessdate=15 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716013153/http://www.military.ie/en/overseas/current-missions/isaf/ |archivedate=16 July 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Current Missions > KFOR|url=http://www.military.ie/en/overseas/current-missions/kfor/|publisher=Defence Forces Ireland|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nCurrently no major political party in Ireland fully supports ascension into NATO, a reflection on public and media opinion in the country.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Carroll|first1=Sinead|title=Poll: Should Ireland give up its neutrality?|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/poll-should-ireland-give-up-its-neutrality-793681-Feb2013/|accessdate=15 July 2015|publisher=thejournal.ie|date=13 February 2013}}</ref> There are a number of politicians who do support Ireland joining NATO, mainly within the centre-right [[Fine Gael]] party, but the majority of politicians still do not.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCullagh|first1=David|title=David McCullagh blogs on Ireland's defence policy|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/primetime/2015/0519/702284-defending-ireland/|accessdate=18 July 2015|publisher=RT\u00c9 Prime Time|date=19 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Roche|first1=Barry|title=Ireland should change position on military neutrality, says academic|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/ireland-should-change-position-on-military-neutrality-says-academic-1.1912307?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.irishtimes.com%2Fnews%2Fpolitics%2Fireland-should-change-position-on-military-neutrality-says-academic-1.1912307|accessdate=15 July 2015|publisher=The Irish Times|date=30 August 2014}}</ref> The nationalist party [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] proposed a [[Amendments to the Constitution of Ireland|constitutional amendment]] to prohibit the country from joining a military alliance like NATO, but the legislation failed to pass the [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] in April 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.derryjournal.com/news/martina-anderson-calls-for-irish-neutrality-referendum-amid-fears-over-european-militarisation-1-8883514 |title= Martina Anderson calls for Irish neutrality referendum amid fears over European militarisation |newspaper= Derry Journal |first= Kevin |last= Mullan |date= 9 April 2019 |accessdate= 29 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/bills/bill/2018/121/ |title= Thirty-Eighth Amendment of the Constitution (Neutrality) Bill 2018 |website= Houses of the Oireachtas |date= 11 April 2019 |accessdate= 29 January 2020}}</ref> It is widely understood that a [[referendum]] would have to be held before any changes could be made to neutrality or to joining NATO.<ref>{{cite web|title=Challenges and opportunities abroad: White paper on foreign policy|url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/AWData/Library3/Library2/DL033049.pdf#page=20|publisher=Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade Ireland|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref> Former [[Secretary General of NATO]] [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]] said during a visit to the country in 2013 that the \"door is open\" for Ireland to join NATO at any time.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lynch|first1=Suzanne|title=Door is open for Ireland to join Nato, says military alliance's chief|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/door-is-open-for-ireland-to-join-nato-says-military-alliance-s-chief-1.1251258|accessdate=15 July 2015|publisher=The Irish Times|date=11 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Moldova===\n{{Further|Moldova\u2013NATO relations}}\n[[Moldova]]'s constitution forbids the country from joining a military alliance, but some politicians, such as former Moldovan Minister of Defence [[Vitalie Marinu\u021ba]], have suggested joining NATO as part of a larger European integration. Moldova joined NATO's [[Partnership for Peace]] in 1994, and initiated an Individual Partnership Action Plan in 2010.<ref name=Sanchez>{{cite news|last=Sanchez|first=W. Alex|title=Moldova and NATO: Expansion Stops at the Dniester River?|url=http://www.e-ir.info/2013/01/09/moldova-and-nato-expansion-stops-at-the-dniester-river/|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=E-International Relations|date=9 January 2013}}</ref> Following the 2014 [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|annexation of Crimea by Russia]], NATO officials warned that [[Russia]] might seek to annex [[Transnistria]], a breakaway Moldovan region.<ref name=Morello>{{cite news|last=Morello|first=Carol|title=NATO general warns of further Russian aggression|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/nato-general-warns-of-further-russian-aggression/2014/03/23/2ff63bb6-b269-11e3-8020-b2d790b3c9e1_story.html|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Washington Post|date=23 March 2014}}</ref> This separatist issue could preclude Moldova from joining NATO.<ref name=Sanchez/>\n\n===Serbia===\n[[File:Ne\u0107u Nato.JPG|thumb|NE\u0106U NATO (''I do not want NATO'') anti-NATO graffiti in [[Belgrade]]|alt=A white wall with black spray painted words \"Ne\u0107u Nato\" on it.]]\nThe [[NATO intervention in Bosnia and Herzegovina]] in 1992 and the [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]] in 1999 resulted in strained relations between [[Serbia]] and NATO. Relations were further strained following [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|Kosovo's declaration of independence]] in 2008 while a [[United Nations Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo|protectorate of the United Nations]] with security support from NATO. However, Serbia was invited and joined the [[Partnership for Peace]] programme during the [[2006 Riga summit]] and in 2008, was invited to enter the intensified dialogue programme whenever the country is ready.<ref name=Serbia_ID>{{cite news|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=03&nav_id=49084|title=NATO offers \"intensified dialogue\" to Serbia|work=B92|date= 3 April 2008|accessdate=20 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[National Assembly (Serbia)|Serbia's Parliament]] passed a resolution in 2007 which declared their [[Neutral country|military neutrality]] until such time as a referendum was held on the issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/insight/strategies.php?yyyy=2007&mm=12&nav_id=46517|title=Serbian parliament's Kosovo resolution|date=27 December 2007|accessdate=17 December 2013|publisher=[[B92]]}}</ref> On 1 October 2008, Serbian Defence Minister [[Dragan \u0160utanovac]] signed the Information Exchange Agreement with NATO, one of the prerequisites for fuller membership in the [[Partnership for Peace]] programme.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics.php?yyyy=2008&mm=10&dd=01&nav_id=53883|title= \u0160utanovac, NATO sign agreement|work=b92|date=1 October 2008|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> In April 2011 Serbia's request for an IPAP was approved by NATO,<ref name=serbia>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_50100.htm |title=NATO's relations with Serbia |date=16 January 2015 |accessdate=9 February 2015 |publisher=[[NATO]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112045834/http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_50100.htm |archivedate=12 November 2013 }}</ref> and Serbia submitted a draft IPAP in May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gov.rs/en/press-service/statements/12420-serbia-and-nato-are-we-at-a-turning-point|title= Serbia and NATO, are we at a turning point?|date=25 July 2013|accessdate=11 November 2013|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Serbia)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Serbia]]}}</ref>  The agreement was finalized on 15 January 2015.<ref name=\"serbia-ipap\">{{cite news |url= http://www.infobalkans.com/2015/01/16/dacic-ipap-step-forward-serbia-nato-relations |title= Dacic: IPAP, step forward in Serbia-NATO relations |work= infoBalkans |agency= [[Tanjug]] |date= 16 January 2015 |accessdate= 16 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nA [[CeSID]] poll in June 2015 conducted with the support of the [[United States Agency for International Development]] (USAID) indicated that only 12 percent of those polled supported for NATO membership, down from 25 percent in 2012, and 73 percent were opposed.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://inserbia.info/today/2015/06/serbia-only-50-pct-of-citizens-support-eu-integration-73-pct-against-nato-membership/ |title= Serbia: Only 50 pct of citizens support EU integration, 73 pct against NATO membership |work= InSerbia |agency= Tanjug |date= 30 June 2015 |accessdate= 23 July 2015}}</ref> The minor [[Liberal Democratic Party (Serbia)|Liberal Democratic Party]] and [[Serbian Renewal Movement]] remain the most vocal political parties in favor of NATO membership.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.euractiv.com/enlargement/nato-serbia-relations-new-strate-analysis-500499 |title= NATO-Serbia relations: New strategies or more of the same? |date= 10 December 2010 |accessdate= 25 June 2014 |first= Jelena |last= Radoman |work= EurActiv}}</ref> Although [[Accession of Serbia to the European Union|Serbia aspires to join the European Union]], Serbia may seek to maintain military neutrality, joining neither NATO or the [[Collective Security Treaty Organization]] (CSTO).<ref name=\"Srpska\"/><ref name=UPI>{{cite news|title=Swiss envoy: Serbia doesn't need to join NATO|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/Special/2013/11/26/Swiss-envoy-Serbia-doesnt-need-to-join-NATO/UPI-20211385442120/|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=UPI|date=26 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Sweden===\n[[File:Estonia's Admiral Pitka Recon Challenge.jpg|thumb|Sweden has close relations with NATO and NATO members, and participates in training exercises like the Admiral Pitka Recon Challenge in Estonia.|alt=Six flags are held by a line of soldiers in camouflage as they stand in front of trees and a beige building.]]\nIn 1949, [[Sweden]] chose not to join NATO and declared a security policy aiming for [[Swedish neutrality|non-alignment]] in peace and neutrality in war.{{sfn|Agius|2006|p=103\u2013105}} A modified version now qualifies non-alignment in peace for possible neutrality in war. This position was maintained without much discussion during the [[Cold War]]. Since the 1990s, however, there has been an active debate in Sweden on the question of NATO membership in the [[Post\u2013Cold War era|post\u2013Cold War]] world.{{sfn|Agius|2006|p=142\u2013147}} These ideological divides were visible in November 2006 when Sweden could either buy two new transport planes or join NATO's plane pool, and in December 2006, when Sweden was invited to join the [[NATO Response Force]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sweden 'should join NATO plane pool'|work=The Local| date=11 November 2006|url=http://www.thelocal.se/20061111/5481|accessdate=20 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sweden could join new NATO force|work=[[The Local]]|date=2 December 2006|url=http://www.thelocal.se/20061202/5670|accessdate=20 September 2008}}</ref> Sweden has been an active participant in NATO-led missions in Bosnia ([[Implementation Force|IFOR]] and [[Stabilisation Force in Bosnia and Herzegovina|SFOR]]), Kosovo ([[Kosovo Force|KFOR]]), Afghanistan ([[International Security Assistance Force|ISAF]]), and Libya ([[Operation Unified Protector]]).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/news_93853.htm |title= Sweden: one of NATO's most active and effective partners |date= 14 January 2013 |publisher= NATO |accessdate= 9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe ruling Swedish [[Swedish Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]] have remained in favour of neutrality and non-alignment.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21604586-russia-stokes-fresh-debate-among-nordics-about-nato-membership-what-price-neutrality |title= What price neutrality? |work= The Economist |date= 21 June 2014 |accessdate= 5 May 2015}}</ref> This preference is shared by their partners, the [[Green Party (Sweden)|Green Party]], as well as the [[Left Party (Sweden)|Left Party]]. The centre-right [[Moderate Party]] and the [[Liberals (Sweden)|Liberal Party]] are the largest parties by current parliamentary representation in favor of NATO membership.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.thelocal.se/20090513/19406 |work= The Local |title= Liberals: Sweden must join NATO |date= 13 May 2009 |accessdate= 9 February 2015 |first1= Peter Vinthagen |last1= Simpson |first2= Lydia |last2= Parafianowicz}}</ref> The 2014 [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|Russian annexation of Crimea]] is credited with renewed public calls for NATO membership from notable politicians.<ref name=Ford>{{cite news|last=Ford|first=Matt|title=After Crimea, Sweden Flirts With Joining NATO|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2014/03/after-crimea-sweden-flirts-with-joining-nato/284362/|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=The Atlantic|date=12 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304554004579422572239271130 |title= Sweden Mulls \"Doctrine Shift\" in Defense After Russian Incursion in Ukraine |work= The Wall Street Journal |first= Niclas |last= Rolander |date= 6 March 2014 |accessdate= 27 March 2014}}</ref> The [[Centre Party (Sweden)|Centre Party]] was opposed to NATO membership until September 2015, when party leadership under [[Annie L\u00f6\u00f6f]] announced that they would motion to change the party policy in order to push for Sweden to join NATO at their next party conference. The [[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Christian Democrats]], also previously opposed, likewise voted to support NATO membership at their party meeting on 9 October 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/10/09/uk-sweden-nato-idUKKCN0S32I520151009 |title= Swedish centre right in favour of NATO membership |work= Reuters |first= Johan |last= Ahlander |date= 9 October 2015 |accessdate= 10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nPolling has shown a rise in support for NATO membership among Swedes since 2008 according to [[Ipsos]] polling, going from 22 percent in May 2008 to 33 percent in January 2015,<ref name=Oct2014/><ref>{{cite news|title=More Swedes show support for Nato|date=9 January 2015|url= http://www.thelocal.se/20150109/more-swedes-show-support-for-nato|work=The Local|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref> with another from the [[SOM Institute]] in May 2015 showing similar numbers.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thelocal.se/20150520/nearly-one-third-of-swedes-want-to-join-nato |title= Nearly one-third of Swedes want to join Nato |work= The Local |date= 20 May 2015 |accessdate= 1 September 2015}}</ref> According to ''[[Svenska Dagbladet]]'', support in 2011 was at 23 percent,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thelocal.se/20130516/47930 |title= More Swedes in favour of joining Nato: poll |date= 16 May 2013 |accessdate= 27 March 2014 |work= The Local}}</ref> and has risen somewhat significantly to 41 percent in September 2015, when only 39 percent of respondents were opposed to NATO membership.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thelocal.se/20150914/poll-more-swedes-now-for-nato-than-against |title= More Swedes want to join Nato than stay out |work= The Local |date= 15 September 2015 |accessdate= 14 September 2015}}</ref> An October 2014 survey commissioned by [[TV4 News]] also showed slightly more respondents supporting membership than opposing it.<ref name=Oct2014>{{cite news |url=http://www.thelocal.se/20141029/support-swells-for-swedish-nato-membership |title= Swedish support for joining Nato swells |date= 29 October 2014 |work= The Local |accessdate= 30 October 2014}}</ref> In 2014, news that a military expert in Sweden had calculated that the country could hold out for a week if attacked temporarily lifted support for NATO membership in polls.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.realclearworld.com/articles/2014/04/09/sweden_and_finland_face_their_russian_fears.html |title= Sweden and Finland Face Their Russian Fears |first= Suvi |last= Turtiainen |work= Real Clear World |date= 9 April 2014 |accessdate= 22 April 2014}}</ref> A May 2017 poll by [[Pew Research Center|Pew]] showed that support for membership had risen to 47 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2017/05/23/natos-image-improves-on-both-sides-of-atlantic/|title=NATO's Image Improves on Both Sides of Atlantic|last=Stokes|first=Bruce|date=2017-05-23|website=Pew Research Center's Global Attitudes Project|access-date=2017-05-28}}</ref>\n\n===Other countries===\n{{see also|Foreign relations of NATO}}\n[[File:Malta - Dingli - Triq Panoramika - Radar 15 ies.jpg|thumb|A NATO radar facility in [[Malta]]. Like other non-NATO member European states, Malta has generally cooperative relations with the organization.{{sfn|Smith|2006|pp=446\u2013448}}|alt=A sea-side cliff topped by a small white, spherical structure.]]\n[[Austria]] and [[Switzerland]] are both members of the [[Partnership for Peace]], and border NATO member states. [[Malta]] is also a member of the Partnership for Peace and the [[European Union]].<ref name=Ranier>{{cite news|last=Fsadni|first=Ranier|title=The meaning of neutrality|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20130425/opinion/The-meaning-of-neutrality.467064|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Times of Malta|date=25 April 2013}}</ref> However, each country has a long-standing policy of [[neutrality (international relations)|neutrality]]. [[Cyprus]] is the only [[member state of the European Union]] that is not a member of the Partnership for Peace, with any treaty blocked by [[Turkey]]'s concerns regarding the [[Cyprus dispute]].<ref name=Dempsey>{{cite news|last=Dempsey|first=Judy|title=Between the European Union and NATO, Many Walls|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/25/world/europe/25iht-letter.html|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=New York Times|date=24 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Kosovo)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[Enver Hoxhaj]], integration with NATO is a priority for [[Kosovo]], which [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|declared independence from Serbia]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa-ks.net/?page=1,4,2375|title=Hoxhaj: Pas an\u00ebtarit v\u00ebzhgues n\u00eb Asamblen\u00eb Parlamentare t\u00eb NATO-s, Kosova edhe me ushtri|date=24 June 2014|accessdate=27 July 2015|language=Albanian|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Kosovo}}</ref> Hoxhaj stated in 2014 that the country's goal is to be a NATO member by 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa-ks.net/?page=1,4,2335&offset=1|title=Hoxhaj n\u00eb Mitrovic\u00eb, Kosova an\u00ebtar\u00ebsohet n\u00eb NATO para 2022|date=2014-05-16|accessdate=2014-05-16|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Kosovo)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Kosovo]]}}</ref> However, four [[Member states of NATO|NATO member states]]\u2014[[Greece]], [[Romania]], [[Spain]], and [[Slovakia]]\u2014do not [[International recognition of Kosovo|recognize]] Kosovo's independence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.de/kosovo-question-still-divides-eu/a-16226802|title=Kosovo question still divides EU|work=Deutsche Welle|date=8 September 2012|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> [[United Nations]] membership, which Kosovo does not have, is considered to be necessary for NATO membership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics.php?yyyy=2013&mm=02&dd=05&nav_id=84531|title=Daily: No NATO membership for Kosovo|date=5 February 2013|accessdate=11 November 2013}}</ref> In December 2018, the [[Prime Minister of Kosovo|Kosovar Prime Minister Ramush Haradinaj]] stated that Kosovo will apply for NATO membership after the formation of the [[Kosovo Armed Forces]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://top-channel.tv/english/kosovo-pm-after-approving-army-kosovo-will-apply-for-nato/|title=Kosovo PM: \"After approving army, Kosovo will apply for NATO\"|website=top-channel.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref>\n\n[[Russia]], [[Armenia]], [[Belarus]], and [[Kazakhstan]] are all members of the [[Collective Security Treaty Organization]] (CSTO), an alternative military alliance. In 2009, Russian envoy [[Dmitry Rogozin]] did not rule out joining NATO at some point, but stated that Russia was currently more interested in leading a coalition as a [[great power]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://euobserver.com/13/27890| title= Russia does not rule out future NATO membership| publisher= EUobserver| accessdate=1 May 2009}}</ref> [[Azerbaijan]] has committed to a policy of [[neutral country|neutrality]], but has not ruled out eventually joining NATO or the CSTO.<ref name=AzNeutral>{{cite news|title=Azerbaijan not to join any military coalition including NATO|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/710870.shtml|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Xinhua|date=23 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=ZeeNews>{{cite news|title=Azerbaijan not to join NATO|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/world/azerbaijan-not-to-join-nato_850713.html|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Zee News|date=25 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nSome individuals have proposed expanding NATO outside of Europe, although doing so would require amending Article 10 of the [[North Atlantic Treaty]].<ref name=Global>{{cite news|last=Daalder|first=Ivo|title=Global NATO|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/61922/ivo-h-daalder-and-james-goldgeier/global-nato|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Foreign Affairs|date=October 2006|author2=James Goldgeier}}</ref> Christopher Sands of the [[Hudson Institute]] proposed [[Mexico|Mexican]] membership of NATO in order to enhance NATO cooperation with Mexico and develop a \"North American pillar\" for regional security.<ref name=Sands>{{cite news|last=Sands|first=Christopher|title=Why NATO Should Accept Mexico|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/christopher-sands/nato-mexico_b_1525638.html|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=18 May 2012}}</ref> In June 2013, [[Colombia]]n President [[Juan Manuel Santos]] stated his hope that Colombia's cooperation with NATO could result in NATO membership, though his Foreign Minister, Juan Carlos Pinzon, quickly clarified that Colombia is not actively seeking NATO membership.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.foxnews.com/world/2013/06/04/colombia-minister-says-no-to-nato-membership/ |title= Colombia Minister Says No to NATO Membership |agency= Associated Press |work= Fox News |date= 4 June 2014 |accessdate= 25 June 2014}}</ref> [[Ivo Daalder]] and [[James Goldgeier]] proposed a \"global NATO\" that would incorporate democratic states from around the world, including [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Japan]], [[South Korea]], [[Brazil]], [[South Africa]], and [[India]],<ref name=Global/> while [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] presidential candidate [[Rudy Giuliani]] suggested expanding NATO to include [[Singapore]], [[Israel]], [[Australia]], [[India]], and [[Japan]].<ref name=Giuliani>{{cite news|last=Woodroofe|first=Thom|title=NATO: the Australian experience|url=http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/4022640.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130219172836/http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/4022640.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 February 2013|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=ABC|date=12 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2019, US President, [[Donald Trump]] said he would make [[Brazil]] a [[Major non-NATO ally]] at a meeting with Brazilian President, [[Jair Bolsonaro]] at the [[White House]]. During a joint press conference, President Trump expressed support for the eventual ascension of Brazil into NATO.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/434767-trump-suggests-admitting-brazil-to-nato-alliance|title=Trump suggests admitting Brazil to NATO alliance|last=Samuels|first=Brett|date=2019-03-19|website=The Hill|language=en|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref> France however has rejected the proposal claiming Article 10 of the treaty limits geography of membership to European countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1103470/france-news-emmanuel-macron-donald-trump-nato-brazil|title=France rejects Trump demand to give Brazil NATO membership|last=McGuinness|first=Romina|date=2019-03-21|website=Express|language=en|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\nInternal enlargement is the process of new member states arising from the break-up of or secession from an existing member state. There have been and are a number of [[List of active separatist movements in Europe|active separatist movements within member states]]. The [[Scottish National Party]] agreed at its [[NATO debate in the Scottish National Party|conference in 2012]] that it wished for Scotland to retain its NATO membership were it to become independent from the United Kingdom.\n\nOn January 9, 2020, Donald Trump said he was of the opinion that the alliance should expand into the Middle East.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-proposed-national-environmental-policy-act-regulations/|title=Remarks by President Trump on Proposed National Environmental Policy Act Regulations|date=January 9, 2020|website=White House|language=en|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Foreign relations of NATO]]\n* [[Individual Partnership Action Plan]]\n* [[Major non-NATO ally]]\n* [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]]\n* [[Partnership for Peace]]\n*[[Withdrawal from NATO]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last= Ambrosio |first= Thomas |authorlink= Thomas Ambrosio |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=gG1kLrmKrfEC&pg=PA150 |title= Authoritarian Backlash: Russian Resistance to Democratization in the Former Soviet Union |publisher= Ashgate Publishing, Ltd. |year= 2013 |isbn= 978-1-4094-9889-6 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Agius |first= Christine |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ALBZJ3sG_EgC&pg=PA104 |title= The social construction of Swedish neutrality: Challenges to Swedish identity and sovereignty |publisher= Manchester University Press |year= 2006 |isbn= 978-1-84779-199-3 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Barany |first= Zoltan |title= The Future of NATO Expansion: Four Case Studies |publisher= Cambridge University Press |year= 2003 |isbn= 978-1-139-44044-8 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=txlteD2HG9EC&pg=PA16 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1= David |first1= Charles-Philippe |last2= Levesque |first2= Jacques |title= Future of NATO: Enlargement, Russia, and European Security |publisher= McGill-Queen's Press |year= 1999 |isbn= 978-0-7735-6785-6 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=U0DKEhe7Z6EC&pg=PA200 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1= Frappi |first1= Carlo |last2= Carati |first2= Andrea |title= NATO in the 60th anniversary of the North Atlantic Treaty |publisher= FrancoAngeli |year= 2009 |isbn= 978-88-568-1977-9 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=gEob0P4--JcC&pg=PA50 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Gheciu |first= Alexandra |title= NATO in the New Europe: The Politics of International Socialization After the Cold War |publisher= Stanford University Press |year= 2005 |isbn= 978-0-8047-6766-8 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=o8FvL55amrIC&pg=PA72 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last = Gorbachev |first = Mikhail |authorlink = Mikhail Gorbachev |year = 1996 |title = Memoirs |url = https://archive.org/details/memoirsgorb00gorb |url-access = registration |location = London |publisher = Doubleday |isbn = 978-0-385-40668-0 |ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book |last1= Grenfell |first1= Julian |last2= Jopling |first2= Thomas Michael |authorlink1= Julian Grenfell, 3rd Baron Grenfell |authorlink2= Michael Jopling, Baron Jopling |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=luPEikc7-0oC&pg=PA13&lpg=PA13 |title= FRONTEX: the EU external borders agency, 9th report of session 2007\u201308 |publisher= House of Lords Stationery Office |year= 2008 |isbn= 978-0-10-401232-1 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Magone |first= Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda |title= Contemporary Spanish Politics |publisher= Taylor & Francis |year= 2009 |isbn= 978-0-415-42188-1 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=vbh5UkfRtbAC&pg=PA385 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Smith |first= Simon C. |title= Malta: British documents on the end of empire |publisher= University of London Institute of Commonwealth Studies |year= 2006 |isbn= 978-0-11-290590-5 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=NcNiMSATVDUC&pg=PA446 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Thiele |first= Ralph |title= Mediterranean Security After EU and NATO Enlargement |publisher= Rubbettino Editore |year= 2005 |isbn= 978-88-498-1037-0 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=qHjx_RTGYxQC&pg=PA73 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Trifunovska |first= Sne\u017eana |title= The Transatlantic Alliance on the Eve of the New Millennium |publisher= Martinus Nijhoff Publishers |year= 1996 |isbn= 978-90-411-0243-0 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=LI6nQwERi8oC&pg=PA16 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Trifunovska |first= Sne\u017eana |title= North Atlantic Treaty Organization |publisher= Kluwer Law International |year= 2010 |isbn= 978-90-411-3328-1 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=6ZXH7R5sQTMC&pg=PA36 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Wolchik |first= Sharon L. |last2= Curry |first2= Jane Leftwich |title= Central and East European Politics: From Communism to Democracy |publisher= Rowman & Littlefield |year= 2011 |isbn= 978-0-7425-6734-4 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=BjVNJ1REkoEC&pg=PA148 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Yekelchyk |first= Serhy |authorlink= Serhy Yekelchyk |title= Ukraine: Birth of a Modern Nation |publisher= [[Oxford University Press]] |year= 2007 |isbn= 978-0-19-530546-3 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=2CHiBwAAQBAJ |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150206200940/http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_49212.htm Official NATO enlargement site]\n\n{{NATO candidates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Enlargement Of Nato}}\n[[Category:Enlargement of NATO| ]]\n[[Category:Enlargement of intergovernmental organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the historical and future expansion of NATO|the composition of NATO|Member states of NATO}}\n{{short description|countries joining the military alliance}}\n{{Use American English|date = April 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n[[File:Map of NATO chronological.gif|350px|right|thumb|Map of NATO countries' chronological membership|alt=An animation showing the year and location of counties as they joined the alliance.]]\n\n'''Enlargement of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization''' ('''NATO''') is the process of including new member states in [[NATO]]. NATO is a [[military alliance]] of twenty-eight [[Europe]]an and two [[North America]]n countries that constitutes a system of [[collective defense]]. The process of joining the alliance is governed by Article 10 of the [[North Atlantic Treaty]], which allows only for the invitation of \"other European States\", and by subsequent agreements. Countries wishing to join have to meet certain requirements and complete a multi-step process involving political dialogue and military integration. The accession process is overseen by the [[North Atlantic Council]], NATO's governing body.\n\nAfter its formation in 1949 with [[North Atlantic Treaty#Founding members|twelve founding members]], NATO grew by including [[Greece]] and [[Turkey]] in 1952 and [[West Germany]] in 1955, and then later [[Spain]] in 1982. After the [[Cold War]] ended, and [[Germany reunited]] in 1990, there was a debate in NATO about continued expansion eastward. In 1999, [[Poland]], [[Hungary]], and the [[Czech Republic]] joined NATO, amid much debate within the organization and Russian opposition. Another expansion came with the accession of seven [[Central and Eastern Europe]]an countries: [[Bulgaria]], [[Estonia]], [[Latvia]], [[Lithuania]], [[Romania]], [[Slovakia]], and [[Slovenia]]. These nations were first invited to start talks of membership during the [[2002 Prague summit]], and joined NATO shortly before the [[2004 Istanbul summit]]. [[Albania]] and [[Croatia]] joined on 1 April 2009, prior to the [[2009 Strasbourg\u2013Kehl summit]]. The most recent member states to be added to NATO are [[Montenegro]] on 5 June 2017 and [[North Macedonia]] on 27 March 2020.\n\nAs of 2020, NATO officially recognizes [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] as an official candidate and two aspiring members: [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and   [[Ukraine]]. Future expansion is currently a topic of debate in several countries outside the alliance, and countries like [[Sweden]], [[Finland]], and [[Serbia]] have open political debate on the topic of membership, while in countries like [[Ukraine]], support and opposition to membership is tied to ethnic and nationalist ideologies. The incorporation of countries formerly part of the [[Eastern Bloc]] and the [[Soviet Union]] has been a cause of [[NATO-Russia relations|increased tension]] between NATO countries and [[Russia]].\n\n==Past enlargements==\n{{See also|Member states of NATO}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-27106-0001, Paris, Verhandlungen \u00fcber NATO-Beitritt.jpg|thumb|[[London and Paris Conferences|Negotiations in London and Paris]] in 1954 ended the [[Allied-occupied Germany|allied occupation]] of [[West Germany]] and allowed for its rearmament as a NATO member.|alt=Four men stand behind podiums with their country names of France, Germany, United Kingdom, and United States, in front of a backdrop of the Eiffel Tower.]]\nNATO has added new members seven times since its founding in 1949 to include twenty-nine members. Twelve countries were part of the founding of NATO: [[Belgium]], [[Canada]], [[Denmark]], [[France]], [[Iceland]], [[Italy]], [[Luxembourg]], [[the Netherlands]], [[Norway]], [[Portugal]], the [[United Kingdom]], and the [[United States]]. The [[Cold War (1947\u20131953)|early years of the Cold War]] saw a stark divide between Capitalist states, backed by United States, and [[Soviet Empire|Communist satellite states]] of the [[Soviet Union]]. This divide eased inclusion of [[Portugal under Salazar]] in NATO and encouraged the anti-Communist governments of [[Greece]] and [[Turkey]] to join NATO in 1952. Greece would suspend its membership in 1974, over the [[Turkish invasion of Cyprus]], but rejoined in 1980 with Turkey's cooperation.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.ibtimes.com/why-turkey-nato-704333 |title= Why Is Turkey In NATO? |work= The International Business Times |first= Palash |last= Ghosh |date= 26 June 2012 |accessdate= 13 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Bonn\u2013Paris conventions]] ended the allies\u2019 occupation of [[West Germany]], and were ratified in part on the condition that West Germany join NATO, which it did in 1955.<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://www.nato.int/docu/review/2005/issue2/english/history.html |title= Germany's accession to NATO: 50 years on |journal= NATO Review |date=Summer 2005 |first= Helga |last= Haftendorn |accessdate= 13 September 2014}}</ref> Though initially isolationist, [[Francoist Spain|Spain under Francisco Franco]] was staunchly anti-Communist, and bound by regular defence agreements with NATO countries.{{sfn|Magone|2009|p=439}} After [[Spanish transition to democracy|its transition to democracy]], [[Spain]] came under pressure to normalize its European relations, including joining NATO, which it did in 1982. A [[1986 Spanish NATO membership referendum|referendum in 1986]] confirmed popular support for this.{{sfn|Magone|2009|pp=385\u2013386}}\n\n===German reunification===\nThe first post-Cold War expansion of NATO came with [[German reunification]] on {{Nowrap|3 October}} 1990, when the former [[East Germany]] became part of the Federal Republic of Germany and the alliance. This had been agreed in the [[Treaty on the Final Settlement with Respect to Germany|Two Plus Four Treaty]] earlier in the year. To secure Soviet approval of a united Germany remaining in NATO, it was agreed that foreign troops and nuclear weapons would not be stationed in the former East Germany, and the topic of further NATO expansion east was raised.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/141845/mary-elise-sarotte/a-broken-promise |title= A Broken Promise? |first= Mary Elise |last= Sarotte |work= [[Foreign Affairs]] |date=September\u2013October 2014 |accessdate= 28 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThere is no mention of NATO enlargement in the September\u2013October 1990 agreements on German reunification, so there was no ''formal commitment'' not to expand.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Kramer|first=Mark|last2=Shifrinson|first2=Joshua R. Itzkowitz|date=2017-07-01|title=NATO Enlargement\u2014Was There a Promise?|journal=International Security|volume=42|issue=1|pages=186\u2013192|doi=10.1162/isec_c_00287|issn=0162-2889}}</ref><ref name=\"International Security\" /> Whether or not the West ''informally committed'' to not enlarge NATO to the East is a matter of dispute among historians and international relations scholars.<ref name=\":0\" /> Harvard University historian Mark Kramer rejects that an informal agreement existed,<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kramer|first=Mark|date=2009-04-01|title=The Myth of a No-NATO-Enlargement Pledge to Russia|journal=The Washington Quarterly|volume=32|issue=2|pages=39\u201361|doi=10.1080/01636600902773248|issn=0163-660X}}</ref> whereas [[Texas A&M University]] political scientist Joshua R. Itzkowitz Shifrinson argues that an informal agreement existed.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"International Security\" /> In December 2017, Svetlana Savranskaya and Tom Blanton of the [[National Security Archive]] at George Washington University argued that newly declassified documents showed that an informal agreement existed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nsarchive.gwu.edu/briefing-book/russia-programs/2017-12-12/nato-expansion-what-gorbachev-heard-western-leaders-early|title=NATO Expansion: What Gorbachev Heard {{!}} National Security Archive|last=|first=|date=|website=nsarchive.gwu.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/when-washington-assured-russia-nato-would-not-expand|title=When Washington Assured Russia NATO Would Not Expand {{!}}}}</ref>\n\n[[Jack Matlock]], US ambassador to the Soviet Union during its final years, said that the West gave a \"clear commitment\" not to expand, and declassified documents indicate that Soviet negotiators were given the oral impression by diplomats like [[Hans-Dietrich Genscher]] and [[James Baker]] that NATO membership was off the table for countries such as [[Czechoslovakia]], [[Hungary]], or [[Poland]].<ref name=\"Spiegel review\">{{Cite news |last1= Klussmann |first1= Uwe |last2= Schepp |first2= Matthias |last3= Wiegrefe |first3= Klaus |date= 26 November 2009 |title= NATO's Eastward Expansion: Did the West Break Its Promise to Moscow? |url= http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/nato-s-eastward-expansion-did-the-west-break-its-promise-to-moscow-a-663315.html |work= [[Spiegel Online]] |accessdate= 7 April 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"International Security\">{{cite news|title= Deal or No Deal? The End of the Cold War and the U.S. Offer to Limit NATO Expansion |doi=10.1162/ISEC_a_00236}}</ref> In 1996, Gorbachev wrote in his ''Memoirs'', that \"during the negotiations on the unification of Germany they gave assurances that NATO would not extend its zone of operation to the east,\"{{sfn|Gorbachev|1996|p=675}} and repeated this view in an interview in 2008.<ref name=\"me\">{{cite news |title = Gorbachev: US could start new Cold War |author=Blomfield A and Smith M |location=Paris |date=6 May 2009 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/russia/1933223/Gorbachev-US-could-start-new-Cold-War.html |publisher=The Telegraph |accessdate=22 May 2009}}</ref> However, in 2014, Gorbachev said \"The topic of 'NATO expansion' was not discussed at all [in 1990], and it wasn't brought up in those years. I say this with full responsibility. Western leaders didn't bring it up, either.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2014/11/06/did-nato-promise-not-to-enlarge-gorbachev-says-no/|title=Did NATO Promise Not to Enlarge? Gorbachev Says \"No\"|last=Pifer|first=Steven|date=|work=Brookings|access-date=2017-09-11|language=en-US}}</ref> Eduard Shevardnadze, foreign minister of the Soviet Union between 1985 and 1991, has always maintained that \"NATO's expansion beyond German borders never came up for negotiation.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> According to [[Robert Zoellick]], a [[United States Department of State|State Department]] official involved in the Two Plus Four negotiating process, no formal commitment regarding enlargement was made.<ref>{{cite news |first=Robert B. |last=Zoellick |url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-65576869 |title=The Lessons of German Unification |publisher=[[The National Interest]] |date=22 September 2000}}</ref>\n\n===Visegr\u00e1d Group===\n[[File:NATO Summit in Washington 1999.jpg|thumb|NATO added the [[Czech Republic]], [[Hungary]], and [[Poland]] at the [[1999 Washington summit]], and established the protocol for Membership Action Plans.|alt=A long red table makes a pentagon around a blue floor with the NATO compass logo, while many rows of people in suits sit on all sides.]]\nIn February 1991, Poland, Hungary, and the [[Czech Republic]] and [[Slovakia]] (as Czechoslovakia) formed the [[Visegr\u00e1d Group]] to push for [[European integration]] under the [[European Union]] and NATO, as well as to conduct military reforms in line with NATO standards. Internal NATO reaction to these former [[Warsaw Pact]] countries was initially negative, but by the [[1991 Rome summit]] in November, members agreed to a series of goals that could lead to accession, such as market and democratic liberalization, and that NATO should be a partner in these efforts. In subsequent years, wider forums for regional cooperation between NATO and its eastern neighbors were set up, including the [[North Atlantic Cooperation Council]] (later the [[Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council]]) and the [[Partnership for Peace]].{{sfn|David|Levesque|1999|p=200\u2013201}}\n\nWhile the other Visegr\u00e1d members were invited to join NATO at its [[1997 Madrid summit]], Slovakia was excluded based on what several members considered undemocratic actions by nationalist Prime Minister [[Vladim\u00edr Me\u010diar]].{{sfn|Gheciu|2005|p=72}} [[Romania]] and [[Slovenia]] were both considered for invitation in 1997, and each had the backing of a prominent NATO member, France and Italy respectively, but support for enlargement was not unanimous, particularly in the [[United States Congress|US Congress]].{{sfn|Barany|2003|pp=23\u201325}} In an open letter to US President [[Bill Clinton]], more than forty foreign policy experts including [[Bill Bradley]], [[Sam Nunn]], [[Gary Hart]], [[Paul Nitze]], and [[Robert McNamara]] expressed their concerns about NATO expansion as both expensive and unnecessary given the lack of an external threat from Russia at that time.{{sfn|Barany|2003|pp=16\u201318}}\n\nA 2006 study in the journal ''Security Studies'' argued that the NATO enlargements in 1999 and 2004 contributed to democratic consolidation in Central and Eastern Europe.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Epstein|first=Rachel|date=2006|title=Nato Enlargement and the Spread of Democracy: Evidence and Expectations|journal=Security Studies|volume=14|pages=63\u2013105|doi=10.1080/09636410591002509}}</ref>\n\n===Vilnius Group===\n[[File:Flags of Nato, Bulgaria, European Union - Military club, Plovdiv, Bulgaria.JPG|thumb|250px|Flags of NATO, Bulgaria, European Union at the Military club of [[Plovdiv]], [[Bulgaria]]]]\n\nShortly after the fall of the Berlin wall in 1989, the [[Presidency of George H. W. Bush|George H.W. Bush administration]] (1989-1993) began to debate internally whether enlargement of NATO was feasible and desirable.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Shifrinson|first=Joshua R.|date=2020|title=NATO enlargement and US foreign policy: the origins, durability, and impact of an idea|url=https://doi.org/10.1057/s41311-020-00224-w|journal=International Politics|language=en|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1057/s41311-020-00224-w|issn=1740-3898|via=}}</ref> By mid-1992, a consensus emerged within the administration that NATO enlargement was a wise realpolitik measure to strengthen American hegemony.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shifrinson|first=Joshua R. Itzkowitz|date=2020-04-01|title=Eastbound and down:The United States, NATO enlargement, and suppressing the Soviet and Western European alternatives, 1990\u20131992|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/01402390.2020.1737931|journal=Journal of Strategic Studies|volume=0|issue=0|pages=1\u201331|doi=10.1080/01402390.2020.1737931|issn=0140-2390}}</ref> In the absence of NATO enlargment, Bush administration officials worried that the European Union might fill the security vacuum in Eastern Europe, and thus challenge American post-Cold War influence.<ref name=\":2\" /> There was an active debate within the [[Presidency of Bill Clinton|Clinton administration]] (1993-2001) about the enlargement of NATO. Within the administration, some preferred a \"relatively swift conferral of full membership to a narrow range of countries\" whereas others wanted \"a slower, phased conferral of limited membership to a wide range of states\". Ultimately, the proponents of the former won the debate within the administration. This coupled with \"pleas from Central and Eastern European leaders, missteps by Russian President Boris Yeltsin, and victory by the pro-expansion Republican Party in the 1994 U.S. congressional election all helped advocates of full-membership enlargement to win.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sarotte|first=M.E.|date=2019-07-01|title=How to Enlarge NATO: The Debate inside the Clinton Administration, 1993\u201395|journal=International Security|volume=44|issue=1|pages=7\u201341|doi=10.1162/isec_a_00353|issn=0162-2889}}</ref>\n\nDomestic politics in Central and Eastern European countries continued to push for more enlargement, and political parties reluctant to move on NATO membership, such as the [[Bulgarian Socialist Party]] and Slovak [[People's Party \u2013 Movement for a Democratic Slovakia|HZDS]], were voted out of office.{{sfn|Barany|2003|pp=190, 48\u201350}} Hungary's interest in joining was confirmed by a [[1997 Hungarian NATO membership referendum|November 1997 referendum]] that returned 85.3 percent in favor of membership.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/17/world/hungarians-approve-nato-membership.html |title= Hungarians Approve NATO Membership |first= Jane |last= Perlez |work= The New York Times |date= 17 November 1997 |accessdate= 4 December 2014}}</ref> Russia's actions in the [[First Chechen War]] were also a motivating factor for several countries that had memories of similar Soviet offensives.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Chechnya Summons Uneasy Memories in Former East Bloc |url = http://articles.latimes.com/1995-01-14/news/mn-20008_1_soviet-union |newspaper= The Los Angeles Times |first= Dean E. |last= Murphy |date= 14 January 1995 |accessdate= 22 November 2015 |issn= 0458-3035}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bulgaria, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Romania, Slovakia, and Slovenia Join NATO DOD 106625793-5d3e18a1d58aa.webm|thumb|right|250px|start=00:14|US President [[George W. Bush]] makes a speech when Bulgaria, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Romania, Slovakia, and Slovenia Join NATO]]\nAt the [[1999 Washington summit]], where Hungary, Poland, and the Czech Republic officially joined, NATO also issued new guidelines for membership with individualized \"Membership Action Plans\" for [[Albania]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Estonia]], [[Latvia]], [[Lithuania]], [[North Macedonia]], Romania, Slovakia, and Slovenia.{{sfn|Wolchik|Curry|2011|p=148}} In May 2000, these countries joined with [[Croatia]] to form the [[Vilnius Group]] in order to cooperate and lobby for common NATO membership, and by the [[2002 Prague summit]] seven were invited for membership, which took place at the [[2004 Istanbul summit]].<ref name=soured>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-29030744 |title= Why Nato-Russia relations soured before Ukraine |date= 2 September 2014 |accessdate= 1 October 2014 |first= Laurence |last= Peter |work= BBC News}}</ref>  Russia was particularly upset with the addition of the three [[Baltic states]], the first countries that were part of the Soviet Union to join NATO.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Umland|first=Andreas|date=2016|title=Intermarium: The Case for Security Pact of the Countries between the Baltic and Black Seas|url=http://nbn-resolving.de/urn:nbn:de:0168-ssoar-48562-7|journal=IndraStra Global|language=en|volume=2|issue=4|pages=2}}</ref><ref name=soured/>\n\n===Adriatic Charter===\n\nCroatia also started a Membership Action Plan at the 2002 summit, leading to a national debate on whether a referendum on NATO membership needed to be held there. Croatian Prime Minister [[Ivo Sanader]] ultimately agreed in January 2008, as part of forming a coalition government with the [[Croatian Peasant Party|HSS]] and [[Croatian Social Liberal Party|HSLS]] parties, not to officially propose one.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://dalje.com/en-croatia/no-smoking-law-alcohol-limit-yes-referendum-no/111642 |title= No Smoking Law, Alcohol Limit-Yes, Referendum-No |work= Dalje |date= 4 January 2008 |accessdate= 9 January 2015 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150109232942/http://dalje.com/en-croatia/no-smoking-law-alcohol-limit-yes-referendum-no/111642 |archivedate= 9 January 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> [[Montenegro]] declared independence on 3 June 2006, and the new country subsequently joined the Partnership for Peace programme at the [[2006 Riga summit]].  Albania and Croatia were invited to join NATO at the [[2008 Bucharest summit]] that April, though Slovenia threatened to hold up Croatian membership over [[Croatia\u2013Slovenia border disputes|their border dispute]] in the [[Bay of Piran]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/23/world/europe/23croatia.html |title= Slovenia Border Spat Imperils Croatia's NATO Bid |work= The New York Times |first= Dan |last= Bilefsky |date= 22 March 2009 |accessdate= 9 January 2015}}</ref> Slovenia did ratify Croatia's accession protocol in February 2009,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://dalje.com/en-croatia/slovenia-ratifies-croatias-accession-in-nato/232508 |title= Slovenia Ratifies Croatia's Accession in NATO |date= 9 February 2008 |accessdate= 9 January 2015 |work= Dalje |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150109232952/http://dalje.com/en-croatia/slovenia-ratifies-croatias-accession-in-nato/232508 |archivedate= 9 January 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> and Croatia and Albania both officially joined NATO just prior to the [[2009 Strasbourg\u2013Kehl summit]], with little opposition from Russia.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.nbcnews.com/id/29995397/ns/world_news-europe/t/albania-croatia-become-nato-members/ |title= Albania, Croatia become NATO members |work= NBC News |agency= Associated Press |date= 1 April 2009 |accessdate= 9 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nMontenegro applied for a Membership Action Plan on 5 November 2008,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/60927/montenegro-hands-over-application-for-nato-s-map.html|title=Montenegro Hands over Application for NATO's MAP|date=6 November 2008|accessdate=9 February 2015|work=Turkish Weekly|agency=MIA|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209180451/http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/60927/montenegro-hands-over-application-for-nato-s-map.html|archivedate=9 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which was granted in December 2009.<ref name=\"rttnews.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rttnews.com/Content/GeneralNews.aspx?Node=B1&Id=1148255|title=Montenegro Joins NATO Membership Action Plan|date=4 December 2009|accessdate=4 December 2009}}</ref> Montenegro also began full membership with the [[Adriatic Charter]] of NATO aspirants in May 2009.<ref name=\"montenegro-timeline\">{{cite web |url= http://www.mvpei.gov.me/en/sections/NATO/Development-of-relations-between-Montenegro-and-NA/ |title= Development of relations between Montenegro and NATO \u2013 key dates |work= Ministry of Foreign Affairs and European Integration |year= 2013 |accessdate= 5 June 2015 |archive-url= https://archive.today/20160316070917/http://www.mvpei.gov.me/en/sections/NATO/Development-of-relations-between-Montenegro-and-NA/ |archive-date= 16 March 2016 |url-status= dead }}</ref><ref name=\"nato-montenegro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_49736.htm|title=NATO's relations with Montenegro|date=19 November 2014|accessdate=9 February 2015|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref>  On December 2, 2015, NATO formally invited Montenegro to join the alliance,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/12/02/us-nato-montenegro-idUSKBN0TL0J620151202 |title= NATO invites Montenegro to join alliance, defying Russia |first1= Robin |last1= Emmott |first2= Sabine |last2= Siebold |work= Reuters |date= 2 December 2015 |accessdate= 2 December 2015}}</ref> with negotiations concluding in May 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://staging.hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/E/EU_NATO?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-05-19-12-59-28 |title= NATO formally invites Montenegro as 29th member |agency= Associated Press |first1= John-Thor |last1= Dahlburg |first2= Matthew |last2= Lee |date= 19 May 2016 |accessdate= 19 May 2016 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://archive.today/20160521123400/http://staging.hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/E/EU_NATO?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2016-05-19-12-59-28 |archivedate= 21 May 2016 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Montenegro formally joined NATO on 5 June 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2017/06/06/world/politics-diplomacy-world/montenegro-becomes-natos-29th-member-amid-bitter-opposition-moscow/ |title= Montenegro becomes NATO's 29th member amid bitter opposition from Moscow |website= The Japan Times |agency= AFP-JIJI |date= 5 June 2017 |accessdate= 5 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[North Macedonia]] joined the [[Partnership for Peace]] in 1995, and commenced its Membership Action Plan in 1999, at the same time as [[Albania]]. At the [[2008 Bucharest summit]], [[Greece]] blocked a proposed invitation because it believed that its neighbor's constitutional name implies territorial aspirations toward its own region of [[Macedonia (Greece)|Greek Macedonia]]. NATO nations agreed that the country would receive an invitation upon resolution of the [[Macedonia naming dispute]].<ref name=veto>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7329963.stm|title= Nato Macedonia veto stokes tension|first=Oana|last=Lungescu|work=BBC News |date=2 April 2008|accessdate=12 May 2008}}</ref> Macedonia sued Greece at the [[International Court of Justice]] (ICJ) over their veto of Macedonia's NATO membership.  Macedonia was part of the [[Vilnius Group]], and had formed the [[Adriatic Charter]] with Croatia and Albania in 2003 to better coordinate NATO accession.{{sfn|Thiele|2005|pp=73\u201374}}  On 12 June 2017, Prime Minister [[Zoran Zaev]] signaled he would consider alternatives names for the country in order to strike a compromise with Greece, settle the naming dispute, and lift Greek objections to Macedonia joining the alliance.  The naming dispute was resolved with the [[Prespa Agreement]] in June 2018 under which the country adpoted the name North Macedonia, which was supported by [[2018 Macedonian referendum|a referendum]] in September 2018. NATO invited North Macedonia to begin membership talks on 11 July 2018,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/nato-invites-macedonia-begin-membership-talks-join-issue-56511753|title=NATO invites Macedonia to begin membership talks, says it can join once name issue is resolved|date=2019-07-11|work=ABC News|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711200547/https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/nato-invites-macedonia-begin-membership-talks-join-issue-56511753|archive-date=11 July 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> and formal accession talks began on 18 October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_159541.htm|title=Formal Accession Talks with Skopje begin at NATO Headquarters|date=2018-10-08|website=NATO|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref> NATO's members signed North Macedonia's accession protocol on 6 February 2019,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47139118|title=Macedonia signs Nato accession agreement|date=2019-02-06|website=[[BBC]]|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref> and most countries ratified the accession treaty in 2019, with [[Spain]] ratifying its accession protocol in March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.dailysabah.com/world/europe/nato-door-open-to-north-macedonia-after-spains-approval |title= North Macedonia will join NATO after depositing it's instrument of accession. |newspaper= Daily Sabah |agency= German Press Agency |date= 17 March 2020 |accessdate= 19 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Assembly of North Macedonia|Sobranie]] also ratified the treaty unanimously on 11 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/02/11/world/europe/ap-eu-north-macedonia-nato.html |title= North Macedonia Parliament Backs NATO Accession |newspaper= The New York Times |agency= Associated Press |date= 11 February 2020 |accessdate= 17 February 2020}}</ref> North Macedonia eventually became a NATO member state on 27 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_174589.htm|title=North Macedonia joins NATO as 30th Ally |date=27 March 2020 |website=NATO}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/north-macedonia-joins-the-nato-alliance/ |title=North Macedonia Joins the NATO Alliance |date=27 March 2020 |website=U.S. Department of State}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Country\n!Enlargement\n|rowspan=20|[[File:History of NATO enlargement.svg|700px|Map of NATO expansion since 1949|alt=A map of Europe with eight colors that refer to the year different countries joined the alliance.]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 18 February 1952 || {{flagcountry|Greece}} || rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|First\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Turkey}}\n|-\n|9 May 1955 || {{flagcountry|Germany}} || align=center| Second\n|-\n|30 May 1982 || {{flagcountry|Spain}} || align=center| Third\n|-\n|3 October 1990 || style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| [[German reunification]]\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 12 March 1999 || {{flagcountry|Czech Republic}} || rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Fourth\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Hungary}}\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Poland}}\n|-\n|rowspan=7| 29 March 2004 || {{flagcountry|Bulgaria}} || rowspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Fifth\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Estonia}}\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Latvia}}\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Lithuania}}\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Romania}}\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Slovakia}}\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Slovenia}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 1 April 2009 || {{flagcountry|Albania}} || rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Sixth\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Croatia}}\n|-\n|5 June 2017 || {{flagcountry|Montenegro}} || align=center| Seventh\n|-\n|27 March 2020 || {{flagcountry|North Macedonia}} || align=center| Eighth\n|}\n\n==Criteria and process==\n\n===Article 10===\nThe [[North Atlantic Treaty]] is the basis of the organization and as such, any changes including new membership requires ratification by all current signers of the treaty. The treaty's Article 10 describes how non-member states may join [[NATO]], and outlines NATO's \"open door\" policy:\n{{quote|1=The Parties may by unanimous agreement, invite any other European State in a position to further the principles of this Treaty and to contribute to the security of the North Atlantic area to accede to this Treaty. Any State so invited may become a Party to the Treaty by depositing its instrument of accession with the Government of the United States of America. The Government of the United States of America will inform each of the Parties of the deposit of each such instrument of accession.<ref>{{cite wikisource |title=North Atlantic Treaty |year=1949}}</ref>}}\nThis article poses two general limits to non-member states. First, only European states are eligible for new membership, and second, these states not only need the approval of all the existing member states, but every member state can put some criteria forward that have to be attained. In practice, NATO formulates a common set of criteria, but for instance [[Greece]] blocked the Republic of Macedonia's accession to NATO for many years due to the [[Macedonia naming dispute|disagreement over the use of the name Macedonia]]. Turkey similarly opposes the participation of the [[Republic of Cyprus]] with NATO institutions as long as the [[Cyprus dispute]] is not resolved.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.economist.com/node/14416843 |title= Fogh in the Aegean |date= 10 September 2009 |work= [[The Economist]] |accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nSince the [[1991 Rome summit]], when the delegations of its member states officially offered cooperation with Europe's newly democratic states, NATO has addressed and further defined the expectations and procedure for adding new members. The [[1994 Brussels summit#Accomplishments|1994 Brussels Declaration]] reaffirmed the principles in Article 10 and led to the \"Study on NATO Enlargement\". Published in September 1995, the study outlined the \"how and why\" of possible enlargement in Europe,<ref name=Trifunovska>{{harvnb|Trifunovska|2010|pp=36\u201337}}</ref> highlighting three principles from the 1949 treaty for members to have: \"democracy, individual liberty, and rule of law\".{{sfn|Frappi|Carati|2009|p=50}}\n\nAs NATO Secretary General [[Willy Claes]] noted, the 1995 study did not specify the \"who or when,\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/transatlantic-rift-haunts-nato-1571999.html |title= Transatlantic rift haunts Nato |first= Andrew |last= Marshall |date= 8 February 1995 |accessdate= 30 December 2014}}</ref> though it discussed how the then newly formed [[Partnership for Peace]] and [[North Atlantic Cooperation Council]] could assist in the enlargement process,{{sfn|Trifunovska|1996|pp=16\u201317}} and noted that on-going territorial disputes could be an issue for whether a country was invited.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.themoscowtimes.com/opinion/article/putins-nato-fears-are-groundless/502886.html |title= Putin's NATO Fears Are Groundless |first= Steven |last= Pifer |work= The Moscow Times |date= 2 July 2014 |accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref> At the [[1997 Madrid summit]], the heads of state of NATO issued the \"Madrid Declaration on Euro-Atlantic Security and Cooperation\" which invited three Eastern European countries to join the alliance, out of the twelve that had at that point requested to join, laying out a path for others to follow.<ref name=Trifunovska/>\n\n===Membership Action Plan===\nThe biggest step in the formalization of the process for inviting new members came at the [[1999 Washington summit]] when the Membership Action Plan (MAP) mechanism was approved as a stage for the current members to regularly review the formal applications of aspiring members. A country's participation in MAP entails the annual presentation of reports concerning its progress on five different measures:<ref>{{cite press release |url= http://www.nato.int/docu/pr/1999/p99-066e.htm |title= Membership Action Plan (MAP) |id= NAC-S(99)66 |work= NATO |date= 24 April 1999 |accessdate= 5 February 2015}}</ref>\n*Willingness to settle international, ethnic or external territorial disputes by peaceful means, commitment to the rule of law and human rights, and democratic control of armed forces\n*Ability to contribute to the organization's defence and missions\n*Devotion of sufficient resources to armed forces to be able to meet the commitments of membership\n*Security of sensitive information, and safeguards ensuring it\n*Compatibility of domestic legislation with NATO cooperation\n\nNATO provides feedback as well as technical advice to each country and evaluates its progress on an individual basis.<ref name=topic>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_49212.htm |title=NATO enlargement |work=NATO Topics |date=12 June 2014 |accessdate=29 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206200940/http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_49212.htm |archivedate=6 February 2015 }}</ref> Once a country is agreed to meet the requirements, NATO can issue that country an invitation to begin accession talks.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1079718.html |title= NATO: What Is A Membership Action Plan? |first= Claire |last= Bigg |work= Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date= 2 April 2008 |accessdate= 6 February 2015}}</ref> Currently, one country has a Membership Action Plan: [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref name=MAP>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_37356.htm |title=Membership Action Plan (MAP) |date=18 February 2019 |accessdate=29 January 2020 |publisher=[[NATO]] |df=dmy }}</ref> Former MAP participants were [[Accession of Albania to NATO|Albania]] and [[Accession of Croatia to NATO|Croatia]] between May 2002 and April 2009, [[Montenegro-NATO relations|Montenegro]] between December 2009 and June 2017 and [[North Macedonia-NATO relations|North Macedonia]] between April 1999 and March 2020, when they joined NATO. The final accession process, once invited, involves five steps leading up to the signing of the accession protocols and the acceptance and ratification of those protocols by the governments of the current NATO members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/docu/comm/2002/0211-prague/more_info/membership.htm|title=The Road to NATO membership|work=[[NATO]]|date=21 September 2007|accessdate=14 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Intensified Dialogue===\nIntensified Dialogue was first introduced in April 2005 at an informal meeting of foreign ministers in Vilnius, Lithuania, as a response to Ukrainian aspirations for NATO membership and related reforms taking place under President [[Viktor Yushchenko]], and which followed the 2002 signing of the NATO\u2013Ukraine Action Plan under his predecessor, [[Leonid Kuchma]].<ref name=topic/> This formula, which includes discussion of a \"full range of political, military, financial and security issues relating to possible NATO membership\" had its roots in the [[1997 Madrid summit]], where the participants had agreed \"to continue the Alliance's intensified dialogues with those nations that aspire to NATO membership or that otherwise with to pursue a dialogue with NATO on membership questions\".<ref name=\"NATO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/docu/update/2005/04-april/e0421b.htm|title=NATO launches 'Intensified Dialogue' with Ukraine|publisher=NATO|date=20 April 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2006, [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] became the second to be offered the Intensified Dialogue status, following a rapid change in foreign policy under President [[Mikhail Saakashvili]],<ref name=\"georgia-id\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/docu/update/2006/09-september/e0921c.htm|title=NATO offers Intensified Dialogue to Georgia|publisher=NATO|date=21 September 2006}}</ref> and what they perceived as a demonstration of military readiness during the [[2006 Kodori crisis]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1070226.html |title= Georgia: Kodori Operation Raises NATO Questions |first= Richard |last= Giragosian |work= Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date= 31 July 2006 |accessdate= 5 February 2015}}</ref> [[Montenegro]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], and [[Serbia]] similarly received offers at the April [[2008 Bucharest summit]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://euobserver.com/defence/25921 |title= France signals full return to NATO |work= EUobserver |first= Elitsa |last= Vucheva |date= 4 April 2008 |accessdate= 6 February 2015}}</ref> While their neighbors both requested and accepted the dialogue programme, Serbia's offer was presented to guarantee the possibility of future ties with the alliance.<ref name=Serbia_ID/>\n\n==Current status==\n[[File:NATO affiliations in Europe.svg|thumb|400px|Map of NATO in Europe{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}{{legend|darkblue|[[Members of NATO]]|outline=black}}{{legend|#2a7fff|[[Membership Action Plan]]|outline=black}}{{legend|darkgreen|[[Intensified Dialogue]]|outline=black}}{{Col-break}}{{legend|#ffd900|[[Individual Partnership Action Plan]]|outline=black}}{{legend|#ff7826|[[Partnership for Peace]] (PfP)|outline=black}}{{legend|red|[[Partnership for Peace#Aspiring members|Aspiring PfP members]]|outline=black}}{{col-end}} note that Membership Action Plan and Intensified Dialogue countries are also Partnership for Peace members |alt=A map of Europe with countries in six different colors based on their affiliation with NATO.]]\nBosnia and Herzegovina is the only country with a Membership Action Plan, which together with Georgia, were named NATO \"aspirant countries\" at the North Atlantic Council meeting on 7 December 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/natosource/russia-says-georgias-entry-to-nato-could-lead-to-war |title= Russia says Georgia's entry to NATO could lead to war |date= 9 December 2011 |agency= RIA Novosti |accessdate= 30 December 2014 |work= The Atlantic Council}}</ref>  Ukraine was recognized as an aspirant country after the [[2014 Ukrainian revolution]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+ NATO Aspirant Countries\n!Country<ref name=aspirant>{{cite web|url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/topics_49212.htm|title=Enlargement|date=2018-03-09|accessdate=2018-03-10|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref>\n![[Partnership for Peace]]<ref name=pfpsigs>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/pfp/sig-cntr.htm|title=Signatures of Partnership for Peace Framework Document|date=10 January 2012|accessdate=9 February 2015|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref>\n![[Individual Partnership Action Plan]]<ref name=IPAP>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_49290.htm|title=Individual Partnership Action Plans|accessdate=2013-11-13|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref>\n!Intensified Dialogue\n!Membership Action Plan<ref name=MAP/>\n!Accession Protocol\n|-\n|{{flag|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}||<span style=\"display:none\">2006\u201312</span> December 2006||<span style=\"display:none\">2008-01</span> September 2008<ref name=bosnia>{{cite web |url= http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_49127.htm |title= NATO's relations with Bosnia and Herzegovina |work= NATO |date= 17 June 2014 |accessdate= 5 June 2015}}</ref>||<span style=\"display:none\">2008-04</span> April 2008<ref name=bbc2008>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7329963.stm |work= BBC News |title= Nato Macedonia veto stokes tension |date= 4 April 2008 |accessdate= 5 February 2015}}</ref>||<span style=\"display:none\">2010-04</span> December 2018<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/nato-approves-membership-action-plan-with-bosnia-12-05-2018|title=NATO Approves Membership Action Plan for Bosnia|last=|first=|date=|website=balkaninsight.com|access-date=}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Originally invited to join the MAP in April 2010 under the condition that no Annual National Programme would be launched until one of the conditions for the [[High Representative for Bosnia and Herzegovina#Conditions for closure of the Office of the High Representative|OHR closure]] \u2013 the transfer of control of immovable defence property to the central Bosnian authorities from the two regional [[Political divisions of Bosnia and Herzegovina|political entities]] \u2013 was fulfilled.<ref name=\"bbcbih\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8638794.stm|title=Bosnia gets Nato membership plan|work=BBC News |date=22 April 2010|accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref>  Condition waived in 2018.|group=Note}} ||\n|-\n|{{flag|Georgia (country)|name=Georgia}} ||<span style=\"display:none\">1994-03</span> March 1994||<span style=\"display:none\">2004\u201310</span> October 2004||<span style=\"display:none\">2006\u201309</span> September 2006<ref>{{cite news |url= http://civil.ge/eng/article.php?id=13613|work= Civil Georgia|title=NATO Grants 'Intensified Dialogue' to Georgia|date=21 September 2006|accessdate=15 September 2008}}</ref>|| || \n|-\n|{{flag|Ukraine}} ||<span style=\"display:none\">1994-02</span> February 1994 || <span style=\"display:none\">2002-11</span> {{#tag:ref|NATO\u2013Ukraine Action Plan adopted on 22 November 2002.<ref name=NATOUkraineAP>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/ar/SID-40166323-FEE6CCD2/natolive/official_texts_19547.htm|title=NATO-Ukraine Action Plan|date=2002-11-22|accessdate=2013-11-11|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref>|group=Note}} || <span style=\"display:none\">2005-04</span> April 2005<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nato.int/docu/update/2005/04-april/e0421b.htm|work= NATO Update|title=NATO launches 'Intensified Dialogue' with Ukraine|date=21 April 2005|accessdate=21 April 2005}}</ref>|| ||\n|}\n{{reflist|group=Note|close}}\n\n===Bosnia and Herzegovina===\n{{main|Accession of Bosnia and Herzegovina to NATO}}\n[[File:Romanian Armored Personnel Carrier.JPEG|thumb|NATO-led Romanian [[IFOR]] peacekeepers patrolled Bosnia and Herzegovina under [[Operation Joint Endeavour]].|alt=A green tank with white letters spelling \"IFOR\" drives on a paved road lined with trees.]]\nThe [[Operation Deliberate Force|1995 NATO bombing of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] targeted the [[Army of Republika Srpska|Bosnian Serb Army]] and together with international pressure led to the resolution of the [[Bosnian War]] and the signing of the [[Dayton Agreement]] in 1995. Since then, NATO has led the [[Implementation Force]] and [[Stabilisation Force in Bosnia and Herzegovina|Stabilization Force]], and other peacekeeping efforts in the country. Bosnia and Herzegovina joined the Partnership for Peace in 2006, and signed an agreement on security cooperation in March 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/region.php?yyyy=2007&mm=03&dd=19&nav_id=40222| title=Bosnia, NATO sign security deal|date=19 March 2007|work= B92|accessdate=22 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nBosnia and Herzegovina began further cooperation with NATO within their Individual Partnership Action Plan in January 2008.<ref name=bosnia/> The country then started the process of Intensified Dialogue at the [[2008 Bucharest summit]].<ref name=bbc2008>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7329963.stm |work= BBC News |title= Nato Macedonia veto stokes tension |date= 4 April 2008 |accessdate= 5 February 2015}}</ref> The country was invited to join the [[Adriatic Charter]] of NATO aspirants in September 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://2009-2017.state.gov/p/eur/rls/fs/112766.htm |title= Adriatic Charter Fact Sheet |work= Bureau of European and Eurasian Affairs |publisher= U.S. Department of State |date= 25 August 2011 |accessdate= 5 June 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] within [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] has expressed willingness to join NATO, however, it faces consistent political pressure from [[Republika Srpska]], the other political entity in the country, alongside its partners in [[Russia]].  On 2 October 2009, [[Haris Silajd\u017ei\u0107]], the Bosniak Member of the Presidency, announced official application for Membership Action Plan. On 22 April 2010, NATO agreed to launch the Membership Action Plan for Bosnia and Herzegovina, but with certain conditions attached.<ref name=\"bbcbih\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8638794.stm|title=Bosnia gets Nato membership plan|work=BBC News |date=22 April 2010|accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref> Turkey is thought to be the biggest supporter of Bosnian membership, and heavily influenced the decision.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.danas.org/content/nato_bih/2020960.html |title= BiH dobila zeleno svjetlo za MAP |work= |first= Lejla |last= Sari\u0107 |date= 23 April 2010 |accessdate= 6 February 2015 |language= Bosnian}}</ref>\n\nThe conditions of the MAP, however, stipulated that no Annual National Programme could be launched until 63 military facilities are transferred from [[Political divisions of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia's political divisions]] to the central government, which is one of the conditions for the [[High Representative for Bosnia and Herzegovina#Conditions for closure of the Office of the High Representative|OHR closure]].<ref name=BosniaMAP>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/news_62811.htm|title=Bosnia and Herzegovina and Membership Action Plan|date=22 April 2010|accessdate=17 November 2013|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/07/05/nato-rules-out-admitting-new-members-anytime-soon/ |title= NATO rules out admitting new members anytime soon |work= Fox News |date= 5 July 2014 |agency= Associated Press |accessdate= 6 February 2015}}</ref> The leadership of the [[Republika Srpska]] has opposed this transfer as a loss of autonomy.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://euobserver.com/defence/29924 |title= Nato grants Bosnia pre-membership status |work= EUobserver |first= Valentina |last= Pop |date= 23 April 2010 |accessdate= 6 February 2015}}</ref> All movable property, including all weapons and other army equipment, is fully registered as the property of the country starting 1 January 2006.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.mod.gov.ba/files/file/zakoni/Zakon-o-odbrani-bs.pdf|title=Law on Defence of Bosnia and Herzegovina|access-date=6 December 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403214419/http://www.mod.gov.ba/files/file/zakoni/Zakon-o-odbrani-bs.pdf|archive-date=3 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>  A ruling of the [[Constitutional Court of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] on 6 August 2017 decided that a disputed military facility in [[Han Pijesak]] is to be registered as property of Bosnia and Herzegovina. It is expected to be a precedent for all other similar facilities, and could thus be the final factor that will enable the activation of the MAP for Bosnia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/court-rejects-bosnian-serb-claim-to-army-facilities-08-16-2017|title=Court Rejects Bosnian Serb Claim to Army Facilities|date=2017-08-16|accessdate=2017-08-18|first=Danijel|last=Kovacevic}}</ref>  Despite that all immovable property is not fully registered, NATO approved the activation of the Membership Action Plan for Bosnia and Herzegovina, and called on Bosnia to submit an Annual National Program on 5 December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/nato-approves-membership-action-plan-with-bosnia-12-05-2018|title=NATO Approves Membership Action Plan for Bosnia|last=Lakic|first=Mladen|date=2018-12-05|website=Balkan Insight|language=en|access-date=2018-12-05}}</ref>\n\nAn August 2010 poll showed that 70 percent of the country supports NATO membership, but results were very different in the two constituent entities. While 90 percent of the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] supported NATO membership, only 33 percent in Republika Srpska did.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.debatesinternational.org/sites/default/files/Bosnia%20and%20Herzegovina%20Poll%20Report%20August%202010.pdf |page= 35 |title= Public Opinion Poll Bosnia and Herzegovina |date= August 2010 |work= National Democratic Institute |accessdate= 25 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nBosnian chances of joining NATO may depend on Serbia's attitude towards the alliance, since the leadership of Republika Srpska might be reluctant to go against Serbian interests.<ref name=\"Srpska\">{{cite news|title=Bosnia's NATO hopes 'depend on Serbia'|url=http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/164962/bosnia-39-s-nato-hopes-39-depend-on-serbia-39.html|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=The Journal of Turkish Weekly|date=27 March 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328042929/http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/164962/bosnia-39-s-nato-hopes-39-depend-on-serbia-39.html|archivedate=28 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  In October 2017, the [[National Assembly (Republika Srpska)|National Assembly of the Republika Srpska]] passed a nonbinding resolution opposing NATO membership for Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/bosnian-serbs-pass-resolution-against-nato-membership/2017/10/18/ced82e48-b3e0-11e7-9b93-b97043e57a22_story.html|title=Bosnian Serbs pass resolution against NATO membership|date=18 October 2017|newspaper=The Washington Post|accessdate=18 October 2017|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n===Georgia===\n{{Further|Georgia\u2013NATO relations}}\n[[File:Nato poster tbilisi.jpg|thumb|upright|An August 2009 sign in downtown [[Tbilisi]] promoting eventual integration with NATO|alt=A blue poster at a bus stop with the NATO logo and the words \"OUR FOREIGN POLICY PRIORITY IS THE INTEGRATION INTO NATO\" in white.]]\n[[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] moved quickly following the [[Rose Revolution]] in 2003 to seek closer ties with NATO. Georgia's northern neighbor, [[Russia]], opposed the closer ties, including those expressed at the [[2008 Bucharest summit]] where NATO members promised that Georgia would eventually join the organization.<ref name=stopped/>\n\nComplications in the relationship between NATO and Georgia includes the presence of Russian military forces in internationally recognized Georgian territory as a result of multiple recent conflicts, like the 2008 [[Russo-Georgian War]] over the territories of [[Abkhazia]] and [[South Ossetia]], both of which are home to a large number of citizens of the Russian Federation. On 21 November 2011, [[President of Russia|Russian President]] [[Dmitry Medvedev]] while addressing soldiers in [[Vladikavkaz]] near the Georgian border stated that Russia's 2008 invasion had prevented any further NATO enlargement into the former [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] sphere.<ref name=stopped>{{cite news| url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2011/11/21/idINIndia-60645720111121 | work=Reuters | title=Russia says Georgia war stopped NATO expansion | date=21 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nA [[2008 Georgian referendum|nonbinding referendum in 2008]] resulted in 72.5 percent of voters supporting NATO accession.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sputniknews.com/world/20080111/96285713.html|title=Georgians back NATO membership in referendum|date=11 January 2008|agency=RIA Novosti|work=Sputnik International|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref> In May 2013, [[Prime Minister of Georgia|Georgian Prime Minister]] [[Bidzina Ivanishvili]] stated that his goal was to get a Membership Action Plan (MAP) for his country from NATO in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurasianet.org/node/66914|title=Ivanishvili: We Will Get NATO MAP in 2014|last=Kucera|first=Joshua|date=2 May 2013|accessdate=17 August 2013}}</ref> In June 2014, diplomats from NATO suggested that while a MAP was unlikely, a package of \"reinforced cooperation\" agreements was a possible compromise.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/06/20/us-nato-georgia-idUSKBN0EV1HZ20140620 |title= NATO unlikely to grant Georgia step to membership: diplomats |first= Adrian |last= Croft |work= Reuters |date= 20 June 2014 |accessdate= 20 June 2014}}</ref> [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]] confirmed that this could include the building of military capabilities and armed forces training.<ref name=\"georgia-2014\">{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/06/25/us-nato-enlargement-idUSKBN0F00IJ20140625 |title= NATO will not offer Georgia membership step, avoiding Russia clash |first= Adrian |last= Croft |work= Reuters |date= 25 June 2014 |accessdate= 25 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Russian Foreign Minister [[Sergey Lavrov]] said that \"NATO approaching our borders is a threat to Russia.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Lavrov: If Georgia Joins NATO, Relations Will Be Spoiled |url=http://georgiatoday.ge/news/17482/Lavrov%3A-If-Georgia-Joins-NATO%2C-Relations-Will-Be-Spoiled |work=Georgia Today |date=26 September 2019}}</ref> He was quoted as saying that if [[NATO]] accepts Georgian membership with the article on collective defense covering only Tbilisi-administered territory (i.e., excluding the Georgian territories of [[Abkhazia]] and [[South Ossetia]], both of which are currently an [[List of states with limited recognition|unrecognized breakaway republics]] supported by Russia), \"we will not start a war, but such conduct will undermine our relations with NATO and with countries who are eager to enter the alliance.\"<ref name=LavrovNATO2019>{{cite web|url=https://agenda.ge/en/news/2019/2582 |title=Russian FM Lavrov supports resumption of flights to Georgia as Georgians 'realised consequences' of June 20 |publisher=Agenda.ge |date=2019-09-26 |accessdate=2019-09-29}}</ref>\n\n===Ukraine===\n{{Further|Ukraine\u2013NATO relations}}\n[[File:Vladimir Putin and Viktor Yanukovych in 2006.jpg|thumb|As president, [[Viktor Yanukovych]] pursued closer relations with Russia.|alt=Two men in suits sit talking around a low wooden table.]]\n[[Ukraine]]'s present and future relationship with NATO has been politically divisive, and is part of a larger debate between Ukraine's political and cultural ties to both the European Union and Russia. It established ties to the alliance with a NATO\u2013Ukraine Action Plan on 22 November 2002,<ref name=NATOUkraineAP>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/ar/SID-40166323-FEE6CCD2/natolive/official_texts_19547.htm|title=NATO-Ukraine Action Plan|date=2002-11-22|accessdate=2013-11-11|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_37750.htm?|title=NATO's relations with Ukraine|date=16 December 2014|accessdate=9 February 2015|publisher=[[NATO]]}}</ref> and joined NATO's [[Partnership for Peace]] initiative in February 2005.{{sfn|Yekelchyk|2007|p=202}} Then in April 2005, Ukraine entered into the Intensified Dialogue programme with NATO.<ref name=\"NATO\"/>\n\nIn March 2008, under [[President of Ukraine|Ukrainian President]] [[Viktor Yushchenko]] and [[Prime Minister of Ukraine|Prime Minister]] [[Yulia Tymoshenko]], Ukraine sent an official letter of application for a Membership Action Plan (MAP), the first step in joining NATO. These leaders however guaranteed their opposition that membership in any military alliance would not pass without public approval in a referendum.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/ukraine/2008/ukraine-080119-rianovosti01.htm|title=Ukraine will not join NATO without referendum|work=GlobalSecurity|date=19 January 2008|accessdate=20 September 2008| volume=5|issue=173}}</ref> This idea had gained support from a number of NATO leaders, particularly those in [[Central and Eastern Europe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://spectator.sme.sk/c/20001838/president-gasparovic-meets-ukrainian-foreign-affairs-minister.html|title= President Ga\u0161parovi\u010d meets Ukrainian Foreign Affairs Minister|work=[[The Slovak Spectator]]|date=20 March 2006|accessdate=20 September 2008| first=Marta|last=\u010eurianov\u00e1}}</ref> Russian leaders like Prime Minister and President-Elect [[Dmitry Medvedev]] made clear their opposition to Ukraine membership, and leading up to the April [[2008 Bucharest summit]] their emissary actively lobbied against a Ukrainian MAP. After some debate among members at the summit, NATO Secretary General [[Jaap de Hoop Scheffer]] declared in a press conference that Ukraine, together with Georgia, would someday join NATO, but neither would begin Membership Action Plans.{{sfn|Ambrosio|2013|pp=150\u2013154}} At this summit, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]], in his last international speech before switching jobs with Medvedev, listed his grievances with NATO, and called Ukrainian membership \"a direct threat\" to his country.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/05/world/europe/05nato.html |title= Putin, at NATO Meeting, Curbs Combative Rhetoric |first= Steven |last= Erlanger |date= 5 April 2008 |work= The New York Times |accessdate= 27 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:\u041c\u0430\u043a\u043a\u0435\u0439\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u0404\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0456.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Euromaidan]] protests that led to [[Viktor Yanukovych]] fleeing the presidency attracted support from Western politicians.|alt=Dozens of blue and yellow Ukrainian flags are held aloft in a wide crowd watching large screens on a square building.]]\nThe [[2010 Ukrainian presidential election|2010 election]] returned [[Viktor Yanukovych]] to the presidency and marked a turnaround in Ukraine's relations with NATO. In February 2010, he stated that Ukraine's relations with NATO were currently \"well-defined\", and that there was \"no question of Ukraine joining NATO\". He said the issue of Ukrainian membership of NATO might \"emerge at some point, but we will not see it in the immediate future\".<ref>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/ukraine/2010/ukraine-100213-rianovosti02.htm Yanukovych opens door to Russian navy keeping base in Ukraine] GlobalSecurity.org Retrieved on 9 March 2010</ref> While visiting [[Brussels]] in March 2010, he further stated that there would be no change to Ukraine's status as a member of the alliance's outreach programme.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/ukraines-yanukovych-eu-ties-a-key-priority-60720.html |title= Ukraine's Yanukovych: EU ties a 'key priority' |work= [[Kyiv Post]] |date= 1 March 2010 |accessdate= 7 April 2015 |agency= Associated Press}}</ref> He later reiterated during a trip to Moscow that Ukraine would remain a \"European, non-aligned state\".<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thenews.com.pk/TodaysPrintDetail.aspx?ID=227513&Cat=1&dt=3/24/2010 |title= Ukraine vows new page in ties with Russia |date= 6 March 2010 |work= The News International |accessdate= 9 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/7774665/Ukraine-drops-Nato-membership-pursuit.html |title= Ukraine drops Nato membership pursuit |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |date= 28 May 2010 |accessdate=7 June 2010}}</ref> Then, on 3 June 2010 the [[Verkhovna Rada|Ukrainian parliament]] voted to exclude the goal of \"integration into Euro-Atlantic security and NATO membership\" from the country's national security strategy in a bill drafted by Yanukovych himself.<ref name=radanonato>[http://euobserver.com/24/30212 Ukraine drops NATO membership bid], [[EUobserver]] (6 June 2010)</ref> The bill forbade Ukraine's membership in any military bloc, but allowed for co-operation with alliances such as NATO.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/10229626.stm Ukraine's parliament votes to abandon Nato ambitions], [[BBC News]] (3 June 2010)</ref>\n\n[[File:Secretary Kerry Joins President Obama for Meeting With Ukrainian President Poroshenko Before NATO Summit in Wales (14950820747).jpg|thumb|[[Petro Poroshenko]] was elected as President of Ukraine in 2014, and met with NATO leaders prior to the [[2014 Wales summit|Wales summit]] about relations with the alliance.|alt=A group of men and women is Western business attire sit around a circular table with a blue tablecloth.]]\n\nFollowing months of [[Euromaidan]] street protests that began because of his refusal to sign an [[Ukraine\u2013European Union Association Agreement|Association Agreement with the European Union]] in favor of deals from Russia, President Yanukovych fled Kyiv in February 2014, ultimately to Russia, and parliament voted to remove him from his post. This brought another change in direction of Ukraine's association with Europe and by extension NATO. In 2014, [[2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine|pro-Russian unrest]] occurred in eastern Ukraine and [[Crimea]] was [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|annexed by the Russian Federation]] in March. As part of an effort to assuage concerned groups, newly installed Prime Minister [[Arseniy Yatsenyuk]] addressed the topic in a speech on 18 March 2014, emphasizing that Ukraine was not seeking NATO membership.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/03/18/uk-ukraine-crisis-nato-idUKBREA2H0DO20140318 |title= PM tells Ukrainians: No NATO membership, armed groups to disarm |first= Pavel |last= Polityuk |date= 18 March 2014 |work= Reuters |accessdate= 27 March 2014}}</ref> US President [[Barack Obama]] echoed this position the following week, while calling for greater NATO presence in Eastern Europe.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/03/26/us-usa-eu-summit-nato-idUSBREA2P1XJ20140326 |title= Obama says NATO needs to boost presence in eastern Europe |first1= Adrian |last1= Croft |first2= Jeff |last2= Mason |date= 26 March 2014 |accessdate= 27 March 2014 |work= Reuters}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in response to the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|Russian military intervention in Ukraine]],<ref name=\"uk.reuters.com\">{{Citation|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/04/17/russia-putin-crimea-idUKL6N0N921H20140417|title=Putin admits Russian forces were deployed to Crimea|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|date=17 April 2014|quote=\"We had to take unavoidable steps so that events did not develop as they are currently developing in southeast Ukraine.&nbsp;... Of course our troops stood behind Crimea's self-defence forces.\"}}</ref> Yatsenyuk announced his intentions to resume the bid for NATO integration on 29 August 2014,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28978699 |date= 9 August 2014 |title= Ukraine to seek Nato membership, says PM Yatsenyuk |work= BBC News |accessdate= 9 February 2015}}</ref> and in December 2014, Ukraine's parliament voted to drop the non-aligned status that it adopted in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-30587924 |title= Ukraine votes to drop non-aligned status |work= BBC News |date= 23 December 2014 |accessdate= 23 December 2014}}</ref> [[Secretary General of NATO|NATO Secretary General]] [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]] has stated that NATO membership is still an option for Ukraine,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.euronews.com/2014/02/26/door-to-nato-remains-open-for-ukraine/|agency=Euronews|title=Door to NATO remains open for Ukraine|date=26 February 2014|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> and support for NATO membership has risen to 63.9 percent in government-controlled Ukraine according to a July 2015 poll.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/281737.html |title= Support for joining NATO considerably increases in Ukraine \u2013poll |date= 3 August 2015 |accessdate= 4 August 2015 |work= Interfax-Ukraine}}</ref> Previous polls had shown that the decline in opposition to membership was linked to the ongoing Russian intervention.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.latimes.com/world/europe/la-fg-ukraine-russia-eu-nato-20140514-story.html |title= Russian aggression driving Ukrainians toward EU, NATO, poll finds |work= The Los Angeles Times |first= Carol J. |last= Williams |date= 14 May 2014 |accessdate= 15 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 June 2017, Ukraine's [[Verkhovna Rada]] passed a law making integration with NATO a foreign policy priority.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/427216.html|title=Rada restores Ukraine's course for NATO membership as foreign policy priority|date=2017-06-08|work=Interfax-Ukraine|access-date=2017-06-08}}</ref>  In July 2017 Poroshenko announced that he would seek the opening of negotiations on a [[Membership Action Plan]] with NATO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ukraine-nato-idUSKBN19V12V|title=Pledging reforms by 2020, Ukraine seeks route into NATO|date=2017-07-10|accessdate=2017-07-22|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\nBy March 2018, NATO had recognized Ukraine as an aspirant country.<ref name=aspirant/>\n\nOn September 20, 2018, the Ukrainian parliament approved amendments to the constitution that would make the accession of the country to NATO and the EU a central goal and the main foreign policy objective.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ukraine pushes ahead with plans to secure NATO membership |url=https://www.apnews.com/dff40992fcc446f6808d02d03b35e4bc |website=Associated Press |accessdate=October 15, 2018|date=2018-09-20 }}</ref>\n\n==Membership debates==\n{{Further|Foreign relations of NATO}}\n\n===Finland===\n[[File:Finnish border in Raattentie - panoramio.jpg|thumb|The [[Finnish\u2013Russian border|border between Finland and Russia]] is about 1,340&nbsp;km (833&nbsp;mi) long.{{sfn|Grenfell|Jopling|2008|p=13}}|alt=A simple white fence with a red and yellow gate behind it set across a dirt path in a green forest.]]\n[[Finland]] participates in nearly all sub-areas of the Partnership for Peace programme, and has provided peacekeeping forces to both the Afghanistan and Kosovo missions. The possibility of Finland's membership in NATO was one of the most important issues debated in relation to the [[2006 Finnish presidential election|Finnish presidential election of 2006]], and continues to be a significant issue in Finnish politics.<ref name=sauli>{{cite news|url=http://www.worldpress.org/Europe/2279.cfm|title=Finland Debates Its Ties With NATO|first=Jeroen|last=Bult|date= 3 March 2006|accessdate=20 September 2008|work=Worldpress}}</ref> In 2007, Finland made various technical preparations for membership, with the then Defence Minister [[Jyri H\u00e4k\u00e4mies]] eager to pursue NATO membership.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://euobserver.com/9/23948|work=EUobserver|title=Finland waits for new EU treaty before NATO membership review|first=Andrew|last=Rettman|date=26 April 2007|accessdate=20 September 2008}}</ref> Nevertheless, public interest in the issue has since decreased. In April 2014, the government announced that they would sign a \"Memorandum of Understanding\" with NATO on Finland's readiness to receive military assistance and to aid NATO in equipment maintenance. However, Defence Minister [[Carl Haglund]] emphasized that this memorandum would not be a step towards membership.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.finnbay.com/finland-signs-memorandum-of-understanding-with-nato/ |title= Finland To Sign Memorandum Of Understanding With NATO |date= 22 April 2014 |accessdate= 22 April 2014 |work= Finnbay}}</ref>\n\nOut of the major Finnish political parties, the [[National Coalition Party]] and [[Swedish People's Party of Finland]] support NATO membership. In 2016, the party conference of the National Coalition Party agreed that Finland should apply for membership \"in the next few years\".<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.verkkouutiset.fi/politiikka/kokoomuksen%20kannanotot-51679 |title= Kokoomus p\u00e4\u00e4tti Nato-linjastaan: Puolustusliittoon l\u00e4hivuosina |date= 12 June 2016 |accessdate= 12 June 2016 |publisher= Verkkouutiset}}</ref> In the vision of the Swedish People's Party of Finland, Finland will be a NATO member in 2025.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://yle.fi/uutiset/rkp_on_nyt_virallisesti_nato-puolue/8951589 |title= RKP on nyt virallisesti Nato-puolue |date= 12 June 2016 |accessdate= 12 June 2016 |publisher= Yle}}</ref> Many individual politicians have advocated for NATO as well, including the current President [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]] and former Prime Minister [[Alexander Stubb]],<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/06/14/us-finland-primeminister-idUSKBN0EP0EW20140614 |title= Stubb to be Finland's next PM, backs NATO membership |first1= Jussi |last1= Rosendahl |first2= Sakari |last2= Suoninen |date= 14 June 2014 |accessdate= 14 June 2014 |work= Reuters}}</ref> as well as former President [[Martti Ahtisaari]],<ref name=sauli/><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.alaskadispatch.com/article/20140412/ex-president-ahtisaari-calls-finland-join-nato-sweden |title= Ex-President Ahtisaari calls on Finland to join NATO with Sweden |work= Alaska Dispatch |agency= YLE News |date= 12 April 2014 |accessdate= 18 April 2014 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140419031103/https://www.alaskadispatch.com/article/20140412/ex-president-ahtisaari-calls-finland-join-nato-sweden |archivedate= 19 April 2014 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> who has argued that Finland should join all the organizations supported by other Western democracies in order \"to shrug off once and for all the burden of [[Finlandization]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www2.hs.fi/english/archive/news.asp?id=20031215IE6|title=Former President Ahtisaari: NATO membership would put an end to Finlandisation murmurs|work=Helsingin Sanomat|date=15 December 2003|accessdate=20 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205075236/http://www2.hs.fi/english/archive/news.asp?id=20031215IE6|archivedate=5 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Two other former presidents from the [[Social Democratic Party of Finland|Social Democratic Party]], [[Tarja Halonen]] and [[Mauno Koivisto]], have publicly opposed the idea, arguing that NATO membership would deteriorate Finland's relations with [[Russia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www2.hs.fi/english/archive/news.asp?id=20040120IE3|title=Finland, NATO, and Russia|work=Helsingin Sanomat|date=20 January 2004|accessdate=20 September 2008|first=Max|last=Jakobson|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205075241/http://www2.hs.fi/english/archive/news.asp?id=20040120IE3|archivedate=5 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFinland has received some very critical feedback from Russia for even considering the possibility of joining NATO,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.finnbay.com/media/news/russian-foreign-minister-lavro-finland-wouldnt-dare-nato-membership/ |title= Russian Foreign Minister Lavrov: Finland Wouldn't Dare for NATO Membership |date= 15 June 2014 |accessdate= 15 June 2014 |work= Finnbay}}</ref> with a 2009 study suggesting this could have repercussions for Russia's relations with the EU and NATO as a whole.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.da.mod.uk/colleges/arag/document-listings/special/09(14)%20KGSE%20Web.pdf|title=Waking the Neighbour: Finland, NATO and Russia: Keir Giles and Susanna Eskola, UK Defence Academy, November 2009|publisher=}}</ref> Following the 2008 [[Russo-Georgian War]], [[Prime Minister of Finland|Finnish Prime Minister]] [[Matti Vanhanen]] reiterated that Finland had no plans to join NATO, and stated that the main lesson of the war was the need for closer ties to Russia.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aqM3uWSVFD7s Deeper Russia Ties Is Georgia War Lesson, Finnish Premier Says] [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] Retrieved on 9 October 2009</ref> In a June 2014 interview in the Finnish newspaper ''[[Hufvudstadsbladet]]'', Vladimir Putin's personal envoy [[Sergey Alexandrovich Markov]] accused Finland of extreme \"Russophobia\" and suggested that Finland joining NATO could start World War III.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://barentsobserver.com/en/security/2014/06/putin-envoy-warns-finland-against-joining-nato-09-06 |title= Putin envoy warns Finland against joining NATO |work= [[Barents Observer]] |first= Thomas |last= Nilsen |date= 9 June 2014 |accessdate= 9 June 2014}}</ref>  In July 2016, Putin stated on a visit to Finland that Russia would increase the number of troops on the Finnish border if Finland were to join NATO. He also warned that NATO would \"fight to the last Finn against Russia\".<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.hs.fi/kotimaa/a1467354133054 |title= Putin moitti Natoa tiukasti Suomen-vierailullaan |work= Helsingin Sanomat |date= 2 July 2016 |accessdate= 3 July 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.helsinkitimes.fi/finland/finland-news/domestic/14078-putin-has-toughened-up-his-rhetoric-views-expert.html Putin has toughened up his rhetoric, views expert]. helsinkitimes.fi (5 July 2016). Retrieved on 22 July 2016.</ref>\n\nA survey conducted by Finnish pollster EVA in January 2015 found that 43 percent of Finns polled opposed NATO membership, while 26 percent supported and 32 percent were undecided. EVA has noted a downward trend in the percent opposed that started in 1998, including a steep decline after the [[2012 Finnish presidential election|2012 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eva.fi/blog/2015/02/03/evan-arvo-ja-asennetutkimuksen-ennakkotieto-nato-kannat-muuttuneet-myonteisemmiksi/|title=MEVAn Arvo- ja asennetutkimuksen ennakkotieto: Nato-kannat muuttuneet my\u00f6nteisemmiksi|date=3 February 2015|accessdate=11 February 2015|work=Elinkeinoel\u00e4m\u00e4n valtuuskunta|language=Finnish}}</ref> In March 2014, during [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|Russia's annexation of Crimea]], one survey showed only 22 percent supported membership,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/850491.shtml |title= Most Fins reject NATO membership despite Ukraine crisis |agency= Xinhua |work= Global Times |date= 24 March 2014 |accessdate= 27 March 2014}}</ref> though a second showed that 53 percent would support membership if Finnish leadership recommended it.<ref>{{cite news |title= Verkkouutiset selvitti: Kansa valmis Natoon, jos valtiojohto niin haluaa |url= http://www.verkkouutiset.fi/kotimaa/nato%20galluppi%20julki%20ti-17919 |date= 25 March 2014 |work= Verkkouutiset |first= Satu |last= Schauman |accessdate= 1 September 2014 |language= Finnish}}</ref> Support for a military alliance with neighbor [[Sweden]] was also high, at 54 percent,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140326/DEFREG01/303260045/Majority-Finns-Support-Swedish-Military-Alliance |title= Majority of Finns Support Swedish Military Alliance |work= Defense News |date= 26 March 2014 |accessdate= 27 March 2014 |first= Gerard |last= O'Dwyer}}</ref> and Finland could possibly seek an enlarged role for [[NORDEFCO]].<ref name=DW>{{cite news|last=Steffen|first=Sarah|title=NATO next for Sweden and Finland?|url=http://www.dw.de/nato-next-for-sweden-and-finland/a-17519846|newspaper=DeutscheWelle|date=26 March 2014}}</ref> [[Minister of Defence (Finland)|Finnish Minister of Defence]] Carl Haglund suggested that a referendum on NATO membership could be held sometime after the [[2015 Finnish parliamentary election|2015 parliamentary election]].<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/06/18/us-finland-nato-defenceminister-idUSKBN0ET1V320140618 |title= Finnish reasons for joining NATO 'stronger than ever': defense minister |first1= Sakari |last1= Suoninen |first2= Jussi |last2= Rosendahl |date= 18 June 2014 |accessdate= 18 June 2014 |work= Reuters}}</ref>  A poll from October 2017 showed that support for membership remained at 22%, while rising to 33% in the suggested scenario in which Sweden would join.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hs.fi/politiikka/art-2000005436683.html|title=HS-gallup: Suomalaiset tyrm\u00e4\u00e4v\u00e4t Nato-j\u00e4senyyden \u2013 mutta onko Suomi jo tiiviimmin Naton kyljess\u00e4 kuin kansa tajuaakaan?|work=Helsingin Sanomat|date=5 November 2017|accessdate=5 November 2017}}</ref> The newest poll from December 2019 showed support decreasing further to 20%, while 56% opposed joining the alliance and 24% were unsure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hs.fi/politiikka/art-2000006343787.html|title=Suomalaisilta yh\u00e4 selv\u00e4 ei Nato-j\u00e4senyydelle|work=Helsingin Sanomat|date=15 December 2019|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ireland===\n{{Further|Ireland\u2013NATO relations}}\n[[File:20140828 Irish delegation at opening ceremonies.jpg|thumb|Ireland currently does not seek to join NATO, but does work to improve the [[Defence Forces (Ireland)|Defence Forces]]' interoperability with NATO<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thejournal.ie/ireland-committed-to-partnership-for-peace-but-has-no-plans-to-join-nato-shatter-838562-Mar2013/ |title= Ireland committed to Partnership for Peace but has no plans to join NATO \u2013 Shatter |first= Jennifer |last= Wade |newspaper= The Journal |date= 21 March 2013 |accessdate= 20 February 2016}}</ref>|alt=Male and female soldiers wearing camouflage marching behind the Irish tri-color flag.]]\n[[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] has been a member of NATO's [[Partnership for Peace]] (PfP) programme and [[Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council]] (EAPC) since 1999, but has a traditional policy of [[Irish neutrality|military neutrality]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NATO's 'neutral' European partners: valuable contributors or free riders?|url=http://www.nato.int/docu/review/2013/partnerships-nato-2013/NATOs-neutral-European-partners/EN/index.htm|publisher=NATO Review Magazine|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref> Ireland participates in the alliance's PfP Planning and Review Process (PARP), which aims to increase the [[interoperability]] of the Irish military, the [[Defence Forces (Ireland)|Defence Forces]], with other NATO member states and bring them into line with accepted international standards so as to successfully deploy with other professional military forces on [[peacekeeping]] operations overseas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Defence Questions: Irish cooperation with NATO in Ukraine|url=http://www.eoghanmurphy.ie/category/pqs/defence/|publisher=Eoghan Murphy TD|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref> Ireland supplied a small number of troops to the NATO-led [[International Security Assistance Force]] (ISAF) in [[Afghanistan]] (2001\u20132014) and supports the ongoing NATO-led [[Kosovo Force]] (KFOR).<ref>{{cite web|title=Current Missions > ISAF |url=http://www.military.ie/en/overseas/current-missions/isaf/ |publisher=Defence Forces Ireland |accessdate=15 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716013153/http://www.military.ie/en/overseas/current-missions/isaf/ |archivedate=16 July 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Current Missions > KFOR|url=http://www.military.ie/en/overseas/current-missions/kfor/|publisher=Defence Forces Ireland|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nCurrently no major political party in Ireland fully supports ascension into NATO, a reflection on public and media opinion in the country.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Carroll|first1=Sinead|title=Poll: Should Ireland give up its neutrality?|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/poll-should-ireland-give-up-its-neutrality-793681-Feb2013/|accessdate=15 July 2015|publisher=thejournal.ie|date=13 February 2013}}</ref> There are a number of politicians who do support Ireland joining NATO, mainly within the centre-right [[Fine Gael]] party, but the majority of politicians still do not.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCullagh|first1=David|title=David McCullagh blogs on Ireland's defence policy|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/primetime/2015/0519/702284-defending-ireland/|accessdate=18 July 2015|publisher=RT\u00c9 Prime Time|date=19 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Roche|first1=Barry|title=Ireland should change position on military neutrality, says academic|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/ireland-should-change-position-on-military-neutrality-says-academic-1.1912307?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.irishtimes.com%2Fnews%2Fpolitics%2Fireland-should-change-position-on-military-neutrality-says-academic-1.1912307|accessdate=15 July 2015|publisher=The Irish Times|date=30 August 2014}}</ref> The nationalist party [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] proposed a [[Amendments to the Constitution of Ireland|constitutional amendment]] to prohibit the country from joining a military alliance like NATO, but the legislation failed to pass the [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] in April 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.derryjournal.com/news/martina-anderson-calls-for-irish-neutrality-referendum-amid-fears-over-european-militarisation-1-8883514 |title= Martina Anderson calls for Irish neutrality referendum amid fears over European militarisation |newspaper= Derry Journal |first= Kevin |last= Mullan |date= 9 April 2019 |accessdate= 29 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/bills/bill/2018/121/ |title= Thirty-Eighth Amendment of the Constitution (Neutrality) Bill 2018 |website= Houses of the Oireachtas |date= 11 April 2019 |accessdate= 29 January 2020}}</ref> It is widely understood that a [[referendum]] would have to be held before any changes could be made to neutrality or to joining NATO.<ref>{{cite web|title=Challenges and opportunities abroad: White paper on foreign policy|url=http://opac.oireachtas.ie/AWData/Library3/Library2/DL033049.pdf#page=20|publisher=Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade Ireland|accessdate=15 July 2015}}</ref> Former [[Secretary General of NATO]] [[Anders Fogh Rasmussen]] said during a visit to the country in 2013 that the \"door is open\" for Ireland to join NATO at any time.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lynch|first1=Suzanne|title=Door is open for Ireland to join Nato, says military alliance's chief|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/door-is-open-for-ireland-to-join-nato-says-military-alliance-s-chief-1.1251258|accessdate=15 July 2015|publisher=The Irish Times|date=11 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Moldova===\n{{Further|Moldova\u2013NATO relations}}\n[[Moldova]]'s constitution forbids the country from joining a military alliance, but some politicians, such as former Moldovan Minister of Defence [[Vitalie Marinu\u021ba]], have suggested joining NATO as part of a larger European integration. Moldova joined NATO's [[Partnership for Peace]] in 1994, and initiated an Individual Partnership Action Plan in 2010.<ref name=Sanchez>{{cite news|last=Sanchez|first=W. Alex|title=Moldova and NATO: Expansion Stops at the Dniester River?|url=http://www.e-ir.info/2013/01/09/moldova-and-nato-expansion-stops-at-the-dniester-river/|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=E-International Relations|date=9 January 2013}}</ref> Following the 2014 [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|annexation of Crimea by Russia]], NATO officials warned that [[Russia]] might seek to annex [[Transnistria]], a breakaway Moldovan region.<ref name=Morello>{{cite news|last=Morello|first=Carol|title=NATO general warns of further Russian aggression|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/nato-general-warns-of-further-russian-aggression/2014/03/23/2ff63bb6-b269-11e3-8020-b2d790b3c9e1_story.html|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Washington Post|date=23 March 2014}}</ref> This separatist issue could preclude Moldova from joining NATO.<ref name=Sanchez/>\n\n===Serbia===\n[[File:Ne\u0107u Nato.JPG|thumb|NE\u0106U NATO (''I do not want NATO'') anti-NATO graffiti in [[Belgrade]]|alt=A white wall with black spray painted words \"Ne\u0107u Nato\" on it.]]\nThe [[NATO intervention in Bosnia and Herzegovina]] in 1992 and the [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]] in 1999 resulted in strained relations between [[Serbia]] and NATO. Relations were further strained following [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|Kosovo's declaration of independence]] in 2008 while a [[United Nations Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo|protectorate of the United Nations]] with security support from NATO. However, Serbia was invited and joined the [[Partnership for Peace]] programme during the [[2006 Riga summit]] and in 2008, was invited to enter the intensified dialogue programme whenever the country is ready.<ref name=Serbia_ID>{{cite news|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=03&nav_id=49084|title=NATO offers \"intensified dialogue\" to Serbia|work=B92|date= 3 April 2008|accessdate=20 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[National Assembly (Serbia)|Serbia's Parliament]] passed a resolution in 2007 which declared their [[Neutral country|military neutrality]] until such time as a referendum was held on the issue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/insight/strategies.php?yyyy=2007&mm=12&nav_id=46517|title=Serbian parliament's Kosovo resolution|date=27 December 2007|accessdate=17 December 2013|publisher=[[B92]]}}</ref> On 1 October 2008, Serbian Defence Minister [[Dragan \u0160utanovac]] signed the Information Exchange Agreement with NATO, one of the prerequisites for fuller membership in the [[Partnership for Peace]] programme.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics.php?yyyy=2008&mm=10&dd=01&nav_id=53883|title= \u0160utanovac, NATO sign agreement|work=b92|date=1 October 2008|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> In April 2011 Serbia's request for an IPAP was approved by NATO,<ref name=serbia>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_50100.htm |title=NATO's relations with Serbia |date=16 January 2015 |accessdate=9 February 2015 |publisher=[[NATO]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112045834/http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/topics_50100.htm |archivedate=12 November 2013 }}</ref> and Serbia submitted a draft IPAP in May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gov.rs/en/press-service/statements/12420-serbia-and-nato-are-we-at-a-turning-point|title= Serbia and NATO, are we at a turning point?|date=25 July 2013|accessdate=11 November 2013|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Serbia)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Serbia]]}}</ref>  The agreement was finalized on 15 January 2015.<ref name=\"serbia-ipap\">{{cite news |url= http://www.infobalkans.com/2015/01/16/dacic-ipap-step-forward-serbia-nato-relations |title= Dacic: IPAP, step forward in Serbia-NATO relations |work= infoBalkans |agency= [[Tanjug]] |date= 16 January 2015 |accessdate= 16 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nA [[CeSID]] poll in June 2015 conducted with the support of the [[United States Agency for International Development]] (USAID) indicated that only 12 percent of those polled supported for NATO membership, down from 25 percent in 2012, and 73 percent were opposed.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://inserbia.info/today/2015/06/serbia-only-50-pct-of-citizens-support-eu-integration-73-pct-against-nato-membership/ |title= Serbia: Only 50 pct of citizens support EU integration, 73 pct against NATO membership |work= InSerbia |agency= Tanjug |date= 30 June 2015 |accessdate= 23 July 2015}}</ref> The minor [[Liberal Democratic Party (Serbia)|Liberal Democratic Party]] and [[Serbian Renewal Movement]] remain the most vocal political parties in favor of NATO membership.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.euractiv.com/enlargement/nato-serbia-relations-new-strate-analysis-500499 |title= NATO-Serbia relations: New strategies or more of the same? |date= 10 December 2010 |accessdate= 25 June 2014 |first= Jelena |last= Radoman |work= EurActiv}}</ref> Although [[Accession of Serbia to the European Union|Serbia aspires to join the European Union]], Serbia may seek to maintain military neutrality, joining neither NATO or the [[Collective Security Treaty Organization]] (CSTO).<ref name=\"Srpska\"/><ref name=UPI>{{cite news|title=Swiss envoy: Serbia doesn't need to join NATO|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/Special/2013/11/26/Swiss-envoy-Serbia-doesnt-need-to-join-NATO/UPI-20211385442120/|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=UPI|date=26 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Sweden===\n[[File:Estonia's Admiral Pitka Recon Challenge.jpg|thumb|Sweden has close relations with NATO and NATO members, and participates in training exercises like the Admiral Pitka Recon Challenge in Estonia.|alt=Six flags are held by a line of soldiers in camouflage as they stand in front of trees and a beige building.]]\nIn 1949, [[Sweden]] chose not to join NATO and declared a security policy aiming for [[Swedish neutrality|non-alignment]] in peace and neutrality in war.{{sfn|Agius|2006|p=103\u2013105}} A modified version now qualifies non-alignment in peace for possible neutrality in war. This position was maintained without much discussion during the [[Cold War]]. Since the 1990s, however, there has been an active debate in Sweden on the question of NATO membership in the [[Post\u2013Cold War era|post\u2013Cold War]] world.{{sfn|Agius|2006|p=142\u2013147}} These ideological divides were visible in November 2006 when Sweden could either buy two new transport planes or join NATO's plane pool, and in December 2006, when Sweden was invited to join the [[NATO Response Force]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sweden 'should join NATO plane pool'|work=The Local| date=11 November 2006|url=http://www.thelocal.se/20061111/5481|accessdate=20 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sweden could join new NATO force|work=[[The Local]]|date=2 December 2006|url=http://www.thelocal.se/20061202/5670|accessdate=20 September 2008}}</ref> Sweden has been an active participant in NATO-led missions in Bosnia ([[Implementation Force|IFOR]] and [[Stabilisation Force in Bosnia and Herzegovina|SFOR]]), Kosovo ([[Kosovo Force|KFOR]]), Afghanistan ([[International Security Assistance Force|ISAF]]), and Libya ([[Operation Unified Protector]]).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/news_93853.htm |title= Sweden: one of NATO's most active and effective partners |date= 14 January 2013 |publisher= NATO |accessdate= 9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe ruling Swedish [[Swedish Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]] have remained in favour of neutrality and non-alignment.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21604586-russia-stokes-fresh-debate-among-nordics-about-nato-membership-what-price-neutrality |title= What price neutrality? |work= The Economist |date= 21 June 2014 |accessdate= 5 May 2015}}</ref> This preference is shared by their partners, the [[Green Party (Sweden)|Green Party]], as well as the [[Left Party (Sweden)|Left Party]]. The centre-right [[Moderate Party]] and the [[Liberals (Sweden)|Liberal Party]] are the largest parties by current parliamentary representation in favor of NATO membership.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.thelocal.se/20090513/19406 |work= The Local |title= Liberals: Sweden must join NATO |date= 13 May 2009 |accessdate= 9 February 2015 |first1= Peter Vinthagen |last1= Simpson |first2= Lydia |last2= Parafianowicz}}</ref> The 2014 [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|Russian annexation of Crimea]] is credited with renewed public calls for NATO membership from notable politicians.<ref name=Ford>{{cite news|last=Ford|first=Matt|title=After Crimea, Sweden Flirts With Joining NATO|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2014/03/after-crimea-sweden-flirts-with-joining-nato/284362/|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=The Atlantic|date=12 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304554004579422572239271130 |title= Sweden Mulls \"Doctrine Shift\" in Defense After Russian Incursion in Ukraine |work= The Wall Street Journal |first= Niclas |last= Rolander |date= 6 March 2014 |accessdate= 27 March 2014}}</ref> The [[Centre Party (Sweden)|Centre Party]] was opposed to NATO membership until September 2015, when party leadership under [[Annie L\u00f6\u00f6f]] announced that they would motion to change the party policy in order to push for Sweden to join NATO at their next party conference. The [[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Christian Democrats]], also previously opposed, likewise voted to support NATO membership at their party meeting on 9 October 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/10/09/uk-sweden-nato-idUKKCN0S32I520151009 |title= Swedish centre right in favour of NATO membership |work= Reuters |first= Johan |last= Ahlander |date= 9 October 2015 |accessdate= 10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nPolling has shown a rise in support for NATO membership among Swedes since 2008 according to [[Ipsos]] polling, going from 22 percent in May 2008 to 33 percent in January 2015,<ref name=Oct2014/><ref>{{cite news|title=More Swedes show support for Nato|date=9 January 2015|url= http://www.thelocal.se/20150109/more-swedes-show-support-for-nato|work=The Local|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref> with another from the [[SOM Institute]] in May 2015 showing similar numbers.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thelocal.se/20150520/nearly-one-third-of-swedes-want-to-join-nato |title= Nearly one-third of Swedes want to join Nato |work= The Local |date= 20 May 2015 |accessdate= 1 September 2015}}</ref> According to ''[[Svenska Dagbladet]]'', support in 2011 was at 23 percent,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thelocal.se/20130516/47930 |title= More Swedes in favour of joining Nato: poll |date= 16 May 2013 |accessdate= 27 March 2014 |work= The Local}}</ref> and has risen somewhat significantly to 41 percent in September 2015, when only 39 percent of respondents were opposed to NATO membership.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thelocal.se/20150914/poll-more-swedes-now-for-nato-than-against |title= More Swedes want to join Nato than stay out |work= The Local |date= 15 September 2015 |accessdate= 14 September 2015}}</ref> An October 2014 survey commissioned by [[TV4 News]] also showed slightly more respondents supporting membership than opposing it.<ref name=Oct2014>{{cite news |url=http://www.thelocal.se/20141029/support-swells-for-swedish-nato-membership |title= Swedish support for joining Nato swells |date= 29 October 2014 |work= The Local |accessdate= 30 October 2014}}</ref> In 2014, news that a military expert in Sweden had calculated that the country could hold out for a week if attacked temporarily lifted support for NATO membership in polls.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.realclearworld.com/articles/2014/04/09/sweden_and_finland_face_their_russian_fears.html |title= Sweden and Finland Face Their Russian Fears |first= Suvi |last= Turtiainen |work= Real Clear World |date= 9 April 2014 |accessdate= 22 April 2014}}</ref> A May 2017 poll by [[Pew Research Center|Pew]] showed that support for membership had risen to 47 percent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2017/05/23/natos-image-improves-on-both-sides-of-atlantic/|title=NATO's Image Improves on Both Sides of Atlantic|last=Stokes|first=Bruce|date=2017-05-23|website=Pew Research Center's Global Attitudes Project|access-date=2017-05-28}}</ref>\n\n===Other countries===\n{{see also|Foreign relations of NATO}}\n[[File:Malta - Dingli - Triq Panoramika - Radar 15 ies.jpg|thumb|A NATO radar facility in [[Malta]]. Like other non-NATO member European states, Malta has generally cooperative relations with the organization.{{sfn|Smith|2006|pp=446\u2013448}}|alt=A sea-side cliff topped by a small white, spherical structure.]]\n[[Austria]] and [[Switzerland]] are both members of the [[Partnership for Peace]], and border NATO member states. [[Malta]] is also a member of the Partnership for Peace and the [[European Union]].<ref name=Ranier>{{cite news|last=Fsadni|first=Ranier|title=The meaning of neutrality|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20130425/opinion/The-meaning-of-neutrality.467064|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Times of Malta|date=25 April 2013}}</ref> However, each country has a long-standing policy of [[neutrality (international relations)|neutrality]]. [[Cyprus]] is the only [[member state of the European Union]] that is not a member of the Partnership for Peace, with any treaty blocked by [[Turkey]]'s concerns regarding the [[Cyprus dispute]].<ref name=Dempsey>{{cite news|last=Dempsey|first=Judy|title=Between the European Union and NATO, Many Walls|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/25/world/europe/25iht-letter.html|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=New York Times|date=24 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Kosovo)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] [[Enver Hoxhaj]], integration with NATO is a priority for [[Kosovo]], which [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|declared independence from Serbia]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa-ks.net/?page=1,4,2375|title=Hoxhaj: Pas an\u00ebtarit v\u00ebzhgues n\u00eb Asamblen\u00eb Parlamentare t\u00eb NATO-s, Kosova edhe me ushtri|date=24 June 2014|accessdate=27 July 2015|language=Albanian|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Kosovo}}</ref> Hoxhaj stated in 2014 that the country's goal is to be a NATO member by 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa-ks.net/?page=1,4,2335&offset=1|title=Hoxhaj n\u00eb Mitrovic\u00eb, Kosova an\u00ebtar\u00ebsohet n\u00eb NATO para 2022|date=2014-05-16|accessdate=2014-05-16|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Kosovo)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Kosovo]]}}</ref> However, four [[Member states of NATO|NATO member states]]\u2014[[Greece]], [[Romania]], [[Spain]], and [[Slovakia]]\u2014do not [[International recognition of Kosovo|recognize]] Kosovo's independence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.de/kosovo-question-still-divides-eu/a-16226802|title=Kosovo question still divides EU|work=Deutsche Welle|date=8 September 2012|accessdate=5 June 2015}}</ref> [[United Nations]] membership, which Kosovo does not have, is considered to be necessary for NATO membership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics.php?yyyy=2013&mm=02&dd=05&nav_id=84531|title=Daily: No NATO membership for Kosovo|date=5 February 2013|accessdate=11 November 2013}}</ref> In December 2018, the [[Prime Minister of Kosovo|Kosovar Prime Minister Ramush Haradinaj]] stated that Kosovo will apply for NATO membership after the formation of the [[Kosovo Armed Forces]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://top-channel.tv/english/kosovo-pm-after-approving-army-kosovo-will-apply-for-nato/|title=Kosovo PM: \"After approving army, Kosovo will apply for NATO\"|website=top-channel.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref>\n\n[[Russia]], [[Armenia]], [[Belarus]], and [[Kazakhstan]] are all members of the [[Collective Security Treaty Organization]] (CSTO), an alternative military alliance. In 2009, Russian envoy [[Dmitry Rogozin]] did not rule out joining NATO at some point, but stated that Russia was currently more interested in leading a coalition as a [[great power]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://euobserver.com/13/27890| title= Russia does not rule out future NATO membership| publisher= EUobserver| accessdate=1 May 2009}}</ref> [[Azerbaijan]] has committed to a policy of [[neutral country|neutrality]], but has not ruled out eventually joining NATO or the CSTO.<ref name=AzNeutral>{{cite news|title=Azerbaijan not to join any military coalition including NATO|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/710870.shtml|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Xinhua|date=23 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=ZeeNews>{{cite news|title=Azerbaijan not to join NATO|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/world/azerbaijan-not-to-join-nato_850713.html|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Zee News|date=25 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nSome individuals have proposed expanding NATO outside of Europe, although doing so would require amending Article 10 of the [[North Atlantic Treaty]].<ref name=Global>{{cite news|last=Daalder|first=Ivo|title=Global NATO|url=http://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/61922/ivo-h-daalder-and-james-goldgeier/global-nato|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Foreign Affairs|date=October 2006|author2=James Goldgeier}}</ref> Christopher Sands of the [[Hudson Institute]] proposed [[Mexico|Mexican]] membership of NATO in order to enhance NATO cooperation with Mexico and develop a \"North American pillar\" for regional security.<ref name=Sands>{{cite news|last=Sands|first=Christopher|title=Why NATO Should Accept Mexico|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/christopher-sands/nato-mexico_b_1525638.html|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=18 May 2012}}</ref> In June 2013, [[Colombia]]n President [[Juan Manuel Santos]] stated his hope that Colombia's cooperation with NATO could result in NATO membership, though his Foreign Minister, Juan Carlos Pinzon, quickly clarified that Colombia is not actively seeking NATO membership.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.foxnews.com/world/2013/06/04/colombia-minister-says-no-to-nato-membership/ |title= Colombia Minister Says No to NATO Membership |agency= Associated Press |work= Fox News |date= 4 June 2014 |accessdate= 25 June 2014}}</ref> [[Ivo Daalder]] and [[James Goldgeier]] proposed a \"global NATO\" that would incorporate democratic states from around the world, including [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Japan]], [[South Korea]], [[Brazil]], [[South Africa]], and [[India]],<ref name=Global/> while [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] presidential candidate [[Rudy Giuliani]] suggested expanding NATO to include [[Singapore]], [[Israel]], [[Australia]], [[India]], and [[Japan]].<ref name=Giuliani>{{cite news|last=Woodroofe|first=Thom|title=NATO: the Australian experience|url=http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/4022640.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130219172836/http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/4022640.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 February 2013|accessdate=28 March 2014|newspaper=ABC|date=12 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, 2019, US President, [[Donald Trump]] said he would make [[Brazil]] a [[Major non-NATO ally]] at a meeting with Brazilian President, [[Jair Bolsonaro]] at the [[White House]]. During a joint press conference, President Trump expressed support for the eventual ascension of Brazil into NATO.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/434767-trump-suggests-admitting-brazil-to-nato-alliance|title=Trump suggests admitting Brazil to NATO alliance|last=Samuels|first=Brett|date=2019-03-19|website=The Hill|language=en|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref> France however has rejected the proposal claiming Article 10 of the treaty limits geography of membership to European countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1103470/france-news-emmanuel-macron-donald-trump-nato-brazil|title=France rejects Trump demand to give Brazil NATO membership|last=McGuinness|first=Romina|date=2019-03-21|website=Express|language=en|access-date=2019-03-25}}</ref>\n\nInternal enlargement is the process of new member states arising from the break-up of or secession from an existing member state. There have been and are a number of [[List of active separatist movements in Europe|active separatist movements within member states]]. The [[Scottish National Party]] agreed at its [[NATO debate in the Scottish National Party|conference in 2012]] that it wished for Scotland to retain its NATO membership were it to become independent from the United Kingdom.\n\nOn January 9, 2020, Donald Trump said he was of the opinion that the alliance should expand into the Middle East.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/remarks-president-trump-proposed-national-environmental-policy-act-regulations/|title=Remarks by President Trump on Proposed National Environmental Policy Act Regulations|date=January 9, 2020|website=White House|language=en|access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Foreign relations of NATO]]\n* [[Individual Partnership Action Plan]]\n* [[Major non-NATO ally]]\n* [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]]\n* [[Partnership for Peace]]\n*[[Withdrawal from NATO]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last= Ambrosio |first= Thomas |authorlink= Thomas Ambrosio |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=gG1kLrmKrfEC&pg=PA150 |title= Authoritarian Backlash: Russian Resistance to Democratization in the Former Soviet Union |publisher= Ashgate Publishing, Ltd. |year= 2013 |isbn= 978-1-4094-9889-6 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Agius |first= Christine |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=ALBZJ3sG_EgC&pg=PA104 |title= The social construction of Swedish neutrality: Challenges to Swedish identity and sovereignty |publisher= Manchester University Press |year= 2006 |isbn= 978-1-84779-199-3 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last= Barany |first= Zoltan |title= The Future of NATO Expansion: Four Case Studies |publisher= Cambridge University Press |year= 2003 |isbn= 978-1-139-44044-8 |url= https://books.google.com/book